<body data-page-type="hub"><header><div class="header-content"><a class="brand" href="../index.html" aria-label="Home"><img src="../assets/logo.png" alt="BCODe"><span class="tag">Documentation</span></a><a class="header-link" href="../docs/index.html" aria-label="Documentation"><img src="../assets/documentation.svg" alt=""> Documentation</a></div></header><main><div class="container"><div class="stack"><section class="card"><h1 style="margin:0 0 6px;">Documentation</h1><p style="margin:0;">Browse pages, or search by title and optionally search within document contents.</p><div class="search-row hub-top-search"><input id="docSearch" class="search-input" type="search" placeholder="Filter by document title" aria-label="Filter docs"><label class="toggle"><input id="withinToggle" type="checkbox"> Search within documentation</label></div></section><section class="card" style="padding:14px;"><div class="doc-grid" id="docCards"></div></section></div></div></main><script>window.__DOCS_DATA__=[{"slug": "intro", "display_title": "Intro", "preview_title": "Intro_to_BCODe_v2 窶・Local Preview", "description": "BCODe 窶・A Stream-Native Telemetry & Control Architecture A Narrative, Publication-Depth Technical Introduction (Integrated Edition) ------------------------------------------------------------------------ Docu?", "corpus_text": "BCODe 窶・A Stream-Native Telemetry & Control Architecture A Narrative, Publication-Depth Technical Introduction (Integrated Edition) ------------------------------------------------------------------------ Document intent This document is intentionally descriptive rather than purely normative. The companion BCODe texts define exact syntax and strict interpretation rules; this publication is meant to tell a coherent story about why the format looks the way it does, how a parser experiences the stream, and what patterns emerge when you build telemetry and control systems around line-atomic statements. It is written so that a reader can understand BCODe窶冱 窶忤hys, hows, and whats窶・without needing to read the normative specifications first窶背hile still staying consistent with them. ------------------------------------------------------------------------ Introduction 窶・Structure Before Meaning When two systems communicate, they do not exchange 窶徇eaning.窶・They exchange structure. Meaning is inferred only after both sides agree on how that structure is organized. Without shared structure, a stream of bytes is indistinguishable from noise. Even when the bytes are human-readable, without an agreed grammar the receiver cannot know where one idea ends and the next begins. Inside a running program, information lives as objects, references, pointers, arrays, and nested memory graphs. These internal representations are optimized for computation, not transmission. The moment information leaves process memory and crosses a boundary窶背hether that boundary is a thread, a device bus, a network socket, or a storage medium窶琶t must be serialized. Serialization is the act of turning an in-memory structure into a transferable representation that another system can parse and reconstruct. Serialization transforms internal structure into a transferable form. JSON, XML, CSV, and binary encodings are all answers to this problem. Each chooses a different balance between verbosity, readability, structure, and efficiency. JSON, in particular, provides a broadly interoperable way to encode hierarchical data, and that ubiquity is why it is often the default choice when teams need 窶彗 format窶・quickly. JSON, for example, excels at representing hierarchical documents. It is readable, human-friendly, and widely supported. However, JSON assumes a bounded document. It expects braces to close, arrays to terminate, and the entire object to exist as a coherent structure before it is considered valid. That is a great fit for web APIs and stored records, but it is a more awkward fit for unbounded streams where data is continuously emitted and partial delivery must never be mistaken for a valid update. BCODe was conceived for a different environment. It is designed for byte streams where you might attach in the middle, where you might drop bytes, and where you must recover deterministically without inventing a separate framing protocol. In practice, that environment includes serial ports, TCP streams, WebSockets, pipes, embedded consoles, and other 窶彗lways-on窶・transports. BCODe assumes that communication may be continuous. It assumes that streams may never end. It assumes that atomicity matters more than hierarchy. And it assumes that measurement quality is as important as measurement value. Those assumptions are not aesthetic窶杯hey directly shape the grammar. ------------------------------------------------------------------------ The Foundational Assumption: Continuous Streams Many real-world systems do not exchange documents. They exchange state. A furnace controller reports temperatures continuously. A sensor array emits readings every few milliseconds. An embedded device accepts commands over a serial line that may remain open for hours. In these systems, 窶徼he message窶・is not a file; it is an evolving timeline of updates. In such environments: There may be no clear 窶彳nd of file.窶・A stream might be a session that lasts days. Noise may appear mid-stream. A UART can glitch; a TCP connection can drop segments. Partial updates must never commit. A half-parsed command must not take effect. Recovery must be possible without restarting the session. Devices often cannot reset just because a host reconnected. BCODe is built around these realities. Where JSON is document-native, BCODe is stream-native. Where JSON emphasizes nested structure, BCODe emphasizes deterministic latching. That emphasis is visible in one idea that shows up again and again: BCODe commits an update only at an explicit 窶徑ine latch窶・byte. ------------------------------------------------------------------------ Structural Philosophy 窶・Determinism by ASCII Columns BCODe does not rely on nested braces or balanced punctuation to determine structure. Instead, it classifies characters by ASCII column ranges and assigns structural meaning accordingly. This makes the parser窶冱 job closer to a finite-state machine than a recursive tree builder, which is exactly what you want in firmware and in high-throughput stream tooling. 3.1 ASCII columns used Table 3.1 窶・ASCII columns and structural roles ASCII range Column Typical chars BCODe role --- --- --- --- 0x20窶・x3F 2 <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" SP ! \" ## %% && ' ( ) + , - . / 0窶・ : (;) < = ? $$</code </pre Field content, qualifiers, numeric punctuation, payload/comment markers, exponent markers 0x40窶・x5F 3 <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" @ A窶纏 [ \\ ] ^ </code </pre Parameter characters (terminate intermediate fields) 0x60窶・x7F 4 <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" a窶奴 DEL {} </code </pre Command characters (terminate line and latch). The byte DEL (0x7F) is reserved for parser reset/resynchronization (Section 15.1). This classification means a parser does not need to track arbitrary-depth nested structure . It does not need to count braces across recursive object graphs, nor maintain a stack for arrays-of-arrays. Instead, it mostly performs single-pass token accumulation and reacts to ASCII-column terminators. The only intentional 窶徇ode switches窶・are bounded payload modes (such as %窶ｦ% hex payloads, $窶ｦ strings, and &窶ｦ raw-binary), which are delimited and therefore do not create unbounded nesting depth. Design note 窶・terminators as both separators and identifiers BCODe fuses two jobs into one byte: the terminator both separates fields and identifies the destination slot (parameter or command). In JSON, separators like , and structural punctuation like : primarily provide structure only ; identity typically lives in a string key (for example, \"temperatureC\": 12.3). In BCODe, the terminator itself carries the identity (窶ｦT means 窶徼his field is T窶・, which is why a flat line remains self-indexing under simple stream processing. That simplicity is deliberate. It enables deterministic parsing even in constrained microcontrollers, and it also makes stream tooling (filters, reducers, log processors) predictable. A related design consequence is that BCODe naturally remains grep-friendly . Because lines are flat and parameter identities are stable, you can filter by parameter letters, by command letters, or by response tags without having to parse a nested tree first. ------------------------------------------------------------------------ The Atomic Line Model Consider the minimal statement: Syntax Meaning --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" 72A 0.0a</code </pre Assigns&nbsp;A=72&nbsp;and&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;atomically&nbsp;on&nbsp;command&nbsp;a. This can be treated as: As digits arrive, the parser accumulates a numeric value. When the character A (column 3) appears, the field is terminated and assigned to parameter A. The parser continues accumulating until it encounters a (column 4). The moment a is read, the entire line commits atomically. The key point is not merely that the line ends窶琶t is that the parser treats the line as not real until the latch byte arrives. A simple parser sketch looks like this: This atomic latch model ensures that incomplete transmissions never produce partial state updates. If noise corrupts the stream before the command byte arrives, no commit occurs. In JSON, a missing brace invalidates the document. In BCODe, a missing command byte simply means 窶從o commit yet.窶・That distinction matters in continuous telemetry because it converts 窶彡orruption窶・into 窶彭elay窶・instead of 窶彡atastrophic parse failure.窶・------------------------------------------------------------------------ The 32-Parameter Reality (and Why It窶冱 a Feature) BCODe defines exactly 32 parameter identities . Identity is derived from the low five bits of the terminator byte. In practice, most implementations use A窶纏 for domain payload parameters and reserve a small subset of symbols (like @, [, ], ^, \\) for conventions. Those symbol choices are not magical in the base protocol 窶杯hey are the result of shared, higher窶鼠evel profiles. In particular, BCODe.meta uses a few of these non窶疎lphabetic identities for 窶徘rotocol plumbing窶・(requests vs responses, unsolicited lines, sequence counters, and atomic multi窶鼠ine packets). This is why you窶冤l often see advice like 窶徨eserve non窶疎lphabetics for common scenarios窶・ it keeps your A窶纏 space clean for domain telemetry while still giving you standardized structure when you need it. This bounded model provides multiple advantages: Parser memory usage is fixed. A receiver can store a complete line in a predictable footprint. Presence masks fit in a 32-bit integer. This makes reducers and filters extremely efficient. Reducer logic is efficient. Summaries like 窶徇issing,窶・窶徭tale,窶・窶彭iagnostic,窶・窶彙ounded,窶・or 窶彳xact窶・can be represented as bitmasks. Schema discipline is encouraged. You must decide what each parameter means rather than letting keys sprawl. Unlike JSON, where arbitrary keys may appear at runtime, BCODe constrains identity intentionally. This encourages stable mappings and interoperability. It also pushes protocol designers toward publishing a parameter map table (what each letter means per command context) and discourages brittle schemas where a value is only meaningful 窶彿f the other fields are present.窶・------------------------------------------------------------------------ Multi-Parameter Telemetry 窶・Narrative Walkthrough Example: Temperature control with explicit intent and latch-on-command This example is deliberately 窶彳ngineering-shaped窶・ it shows a host expressing intent (a bound) rather than pretending it knows the device窶冱 exact internal resolution, while also illustrating why the explicit command byte matters in streams. Definitions (for this example only): T 窶・temperature process variable / setpoint parameter (chosen by convention for this device) (Best Practices: 窶徘ublish a parameter map table窶・ c 窶・a control command class (device-specific semantics layered on BCODe syntax) (Meta + Rest conventions) 窶・lower-bound qualifier (窶彗t least窶・ (Interpretation v10: bounds are not hard values) ! 窶・staleness modifier (窶忻alue is usable but not fresh窶・ (Interpretation v10: orthogonal freshness) CMD terminator 窶・the trailing lowercase command byte (c) that latches the line atomically (Syntax: latch-on-command) Host request (intent, not exactness): Syntax Meaning --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" &gt;1200T 0.0c</code </pre Assigns&nbsp;T=1200&nbsp;and&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;atomically&nbsp;on&nbsp;command&nbsp;c. Narrative: The host is saying 窶徇ake temperature at least 1200.窶・The device can choose the nearest representable setpoint 竕･ 1200 (or reject it), and it can apply internal safety policy without the host baking those details into a client library. Device direct acknowledgement (applied setpoint echoed): Syntax Meaning --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" ^ 1200T 0.0c</code </pre Assigns&nbsp;^=(empty),&nbsp;T=1200&nbsp;and&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;atomically&nbsp;on&nbsp;command&nbsp;c. Device telemetry during warm-up (stale previous reading carried forward): Syntax Meaning --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" !1198T 0.0f</code </pre Assigns&nbsp;T=1198&nbsp;(stale)&nbsp;and&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;atomically&nbsp;on&nbsp;command&nbsp;f. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" 1201T 0.0f</code </pre Assigns&nbsp;T=1201&nbsp;and&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;atomically&nbsp;on&nbsp;command&nbsp;f. Why the explicit command byte matters: if the stream is interrupted halfway through 1200T 0.0c, nothing commits. The parser simply has an accumulator in progress until it sees the c latch byte. That means a line cannot 窶徂alf-apply窶・in the way some ad-hoc delimited protocols can when bytes are dropped mid-message. (Citations: Syntax 窶廚MD terminators latch a line窶・ Interpretation v10 窶彙ounds are not hard values窶・+ 窶徭tale is orthogonal窶・ Best Practices 窶彗void interparameter dependency窶・ Meta 窶弯/\\ tagging窶・ Rest 窶彡ontrol semantics on streams窶・ Syntax Meaning --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" 72A 18B 5C 0.0a</code </pre Assigns&nbsp;A=72,&nbsp;B=18,&nbsp;C=5&nbsp;and&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;atomically&nbsp;on&nbsp;command&nbsp;a. In this single line, three measurements are transmitted. Each parameter terminator assigns its numeric accumulator to a predefined slot. When the command terminator appears, the system commits the complete telemetry set. The viability of this model lies in its determinism. At no point does the parser need to guess structure. There is no ambiguity about where a field ends. There is no ambiguity about when a line commits. In telemetry systems where thousands of lines may pass per minute, such determinism reduces processing overhead and improves reliability. It also makes it practical to build stream transforms that operate on the fly窶播ropping certain parameters, rewriting qualifiers, or extracting reducer masks窶背ithout ever needing a full document parse. A complementary best practice is to keep parameters self-contained . If A is 窶徼emperature,窶・then the validity, staleness, diagnostic codes, and bounds should live in A rather than in a separate 窶徼emperature status窶・parameter. BCODe窶冱 qualifier system exists specifically to make that possible. ------------------------------------------------------------------------ Numeric Shapes and Precision Preservation BCODe窶冱 numeric design is less about 窶彿nventing new math窶・and more about making sure that the wire spelling stays stable while interpreters stay honest about what they know. The format is deliberately friendly to telemetry: values arrive as text, but a parser can hold them as raw components rather than immediately collapsing them into IEEE窶・54 floats. 7.1 The core idea: keep the integer pair and width Syntax Meaning --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" 12.34A</code </pre A&nbsp;has&nbsp;the&nbsp;numeric&nbsp;content&nbsp;12.34. BCODe encodes a fixed窶叢oint number as an integer pair separated by a single punctuation character. In the common spelling, the dot (.) separates value1 and value2 (e.g., 12.34). The comma form (,) uses the same structural idea but flips the sign of the second component窶盃seful when you want to express a negative fractional part without inventing an extra token. This is also a helpful contrast with JSON: JSON uses commas to separate values, but that comma doesn窶冲 identify the value or carry semantic payload. In BCODe, the character that ends a field (the parameter or command terminator) both separates and identifies what you just wrote, which is why a BCODe line stays unambiguous even when it窶冱 being typed into a live stream. By deferring floating conversion, BCODe avoids rounding drift and preserves the original transmitted precision. In long-running telemetry systems, this matters because the human spelling (窶・2.34窶・ can remain consistent across logs, firmware, and tools窶覇ven when different layers ultimately choose different numeric policies (fixed-point, rational, float). 7.2 Exponent suffixes: compact scale without changing the parsing substrate Exponent markers extend the same philosophy: keep the spelling compact while keeping the parsed representation deterministic. Syntax Meaning --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" 123 3A&#10;;123 ﾃ・10^3</code </pre A&nbsp;has&nbsp;the&nbsp;numeric&nbsp;content&nbsp;123. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" 123/2A&#10;;123 ﾃ・10^-2</code </pre A&nbsp;has&nbsp;the&nbsp;numeric&nbsp;content&nbsp;123. A useful narrative way to view this is: BCODe wants the wire form to behave like an engineering notebook or lab log窶把ompact, stable, and easy to scan窶背ithout forcing the receiver to commit to floating conversion earlier than it has to. 7.3 Reference tables (shapes, forms, exponent markers) Table 7.1 窶・Numeric shape classes (how many numbers a field carries) Shape ID Canonical spelling Description --- --- --- C0 Q T Empty field (no numeric content) C1 Q N [EXP] T Single-number field with optional exponent suffix C2 Q N S M [EXP] T Two-number field (fixed-point pair) with optional exponent suffix Table 7.2 窶・Field forms by terminator type (PARAM vs CMD) Form ID Shape Terminator Canonical spelling --- --- --- --- F0P C0 PARAM Q PARAM F1P C1 PARAM Q N [EXP] PARAM F2P C2 PARAM Q N S M [EXP] PARAM F0C C0 CMD Q CMD F1C C1 CMD Q N [EXP] CMD F2C C2 CMD Q N S M [EXP] CMD Table 7.3 窶・Exponent markers Marker Meaning Exponent value if digits omitted --- --- --- Positive exponent +1 (discouraged) / Negative exponent -1 (discouraged) 7.4 Worked micro-examples: parse once, then compute under a declared policy The practical pattern you窶冤l use in host tools and firmware is simple: parse the field , keep its raw components , and only then do arithmetic under an explicit policy. The point is not that BCODe 窶彭oes math,窶・but that it gives you a stable numeric substrate you can treat deterministically. Grouped example set 窶・basic operators, integer math, and mixed widths BCODe on the wire (three small 窶徙perand frames窶・: Syntax Meaning --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" 12.34A 5.06B 0.0m</code </pre Assigns&nbsp;A=12.34,&nbsp;B=5.06&nbsp;and&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;atomically&nbsp;on&nbsp;command&nbsp;m. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" 123A 10B 0.0m</code </pre Assigns&nbsp;A=123,&nbsp;B=10&nbsp;and&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;atomically&nbsp;on&nbsp;command&nbsp;m. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" 1.2A 3.045B 0.0m</code </pre Assigns&nbsp;A=1.2,&nbsp;B=3.045&nbsp;and&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;atomically&nbsp;on&nbsp;command&nbsp;m. This can be treated as (definitions shown once for the whole grouping): Plainly stated results: A small but useful telemetry pattern is to publish derived results as their own parameters so logs remain grep-friendly and self-contained (this is optional, and application-defined): Syntax Meaning --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" 17.40R 7.28S 62.40P 2.43Q 2.22M 0.0m</code </pre Assigns&nbsp;R=17.40,&nbsp;S=7.28,&nbsp;P=62.40,&nbsp;Q=2.43,&nbsp;M=2.22&nbsp;and&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;atomically&nbsp;on&nbsp;command&nbsp;m. Note: this section is intentionally 窶彡horeographed.窶・In real telemetry, you usually publish operands and either compute locally in the host/tool, or publish a smaller set of derived values as additional parameters when it improves observability. Measurement Quality as First-Class Data (Integrated Deep Dive) BCODe encodes measurement quality directly within the field using qualifiers. This is not 窶彳xtra metadata.窶・It is the core strategy for keeping lines flat, atomic, and self-contained. Before we deep dive into each value class, it窶冱 worth stating the motivating problem plainly: in many formats, 窶忻alue窶・and 窶忻alidity窶・become separate fields. Once they are separate, they can fall out of sync. Worse, every consumer must remember the coupling rule. BCODe avoids that by making 窶忻alidity窶・a property of the field itself. Here is the compact summary that many systems start with: Table 8.1 窶・Base qualifier combinations and standardized value classes (symbols show which base qualifiers are present) - < ? Base interpretation Notes --- --- --- --- --- --- Normal positive finite value Hard numeric value - Negative finite value Hard numeric value; sign preserved < Value less than stated Upper bound; not a hard value - < Negative value less than stated Upper bound on negative value Value greater than stated Lower bound; not a hard value - Negative value greater than stated Lower bound on negative value ? Unknown or pending calculation No numeric value should be used - ? Excessive noise / unstable signal Quality failure; numeric may be present but SHOULD NOT be treated as hard < ? Positive epsilon (smallest measurable +) Special finite sentinel - < ? Negative epsilon (smallest measurable -) Special finite sentinel ? Positive infinity Beyond measurable range - ? Negative infinity Below measurable range < Signaling NaN (sNaN) Reserved; only valid as C1; value1 encodes sNaN payload - < Signaling NaN (sNaN), sign preserved Reserved; only valid as C1; value1 encodes sNaN payload < ? Null value (no data available) Distinct from empty field; numeric digits MAY be 0 - < ? NaN (invalid computational result) Quiet/invalid; sign preserved; not a hard value The narrative subsections below repeatedly refer back to Table 8.1. When you窶决e implementing an interpreter, this table is effectively the decision surface that turns qualifiers into value classes. Now we expand each class as a standalone narrative subsection, preserving both syntax clarity and operational intuition. ------------------------------------------------------------------------ 8.1 Exact Numeric (Hard Numeric) Syntax No <, , or ? present. Optional leading - for sign. Syntax Meaning --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" 12A</code </pre A&nbsp;has&nbsp;the&nbsp;numeric&nbsp;content&nbsp;12. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" -5B</code </pre B&nbsp;has&nbsp;the&nbsp;numeric&nbsp;content&nbsp;5. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" 12.34C</code </pre C&nbsp;has&nbsp;the&nbsp;numeric&nbsp;content&nbsp;12.34. An exact numeric value represents a committed measurement. It signals that the device believes the number is meaningful and usable, within the resolution implied by its formatting and scaling. In control systems, this is the value class that most downstream logic expects; it is the 窶從ormal窶・case. BCODe窶冱 interpretation model deliberately allows you to treat 窶彳xact窶・as a high-confidence class. If you build typed accessors, they can refuse to return a hard numeric result unless the qualifiers indicate the field is exact. ------------------------------------------------------------------------ 8.2 Unknown / Pending (?) Syntax Syntax Meaning --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" ?A</code </pre A&nbsp;represents&nbsp;present&nbsp;but&nbsp;unknown/pending. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" ?12A&#10;;optional advisory diagnostic code</code </pre A&nbsp;is&nbsp;present&nbsp;but&nbsp;unknown/pending&nbsp;with&nbsp;advisory&nbsp;code&nbsp;12. The ? qualifier indicates that the value is unknown or pending. The field exists structurally, but the measurement is not currently available. This differs from omission. Omission means the parameter simply wasn窶冲 transmitted. ? means it was transmitted explicitly to say 窶廬 don窶冲 know yet.窶・Operationally, this is powerful because it lets a receiver distinguish between 窶徭ensor not part of this message窶・and 窶徭ensor is part of the system but currently unresolved.窶・That distinction often determines whether you wait, fallback, or fault. The optional digits may carry a diagnostic code, but the key is that the field should not be treated as a hard numeric measurement. ------------------------------------------------------------------------ 8.3 Noise / Unstable (-?) Syntax Syntax Meaning --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" -?A</code </pre A&nbsp;represents&nbsp;present&nbsp;but&nbsp;unstable/noisy. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" -?3A&#10;;optional advisory diagnostic code</code </pre A&nbsp;is&nbsp;present&nbsp;but&nbsp;unstable/noisy&nbsp;with&nbsp;advisory&nbsp;code&nbsp;3. The combination -? represents a noisy or unstable signal. The device is indicating that the measurement is fluctuating beyond acceptable thresholds, or that it has detected conditions that make the value unreliable. The field remains structurally present, but it must not be interpreted as a stable measurement. This class exists because telemetry reality is messier than 窶忻alid窶・or 窶徇issing.窶・In practice, sensors can be alive but unstable. Encoding that state inline avoids an entire family of schema patterns where you ship value plus stabilityFlag plus reasonCode and hope consumers interpret them consistently. ------------------------------------------------------------------------ 8.4 Epsilon (<? and -<?) Syntax Syntax Meaning --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" &lt;?A&#10;;+epsilon</code </pre A&nbsp;represents&nbsp;positive&nbsp;epsilon&nbsp;(smallest&nbsp;step). <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" -&lt;?A&#10;;-epsilon</code </pre A&nbsp;represents&nbsp;negative&nbsp;epsilon&nbsp;(smallest&nbsp;step). Epsilon represents the smallest representable increment of the device. It communicates resolution rather than magnitude. In telemetry, epsilon is a way to say 窶徼his value is at the granularity floor窶昶馬ot simply 窶徭mall.窶・In control semantics, epsilon is even more interesting because it lets a host express intent without knowing device quantization: Syntax Meaning --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" &lt;?C&#10;;increase by the smallest step for parameter C</code </pre C&nbsp;represents&nbsp;positive&nbsp;epsilon&nbsp;(smallest&nbsp;step). This avoids coupling host software to device implementation details. It also makes protocols more durable: devices can change internal resolution without forcing host updates, because the host is describing intent (窶徙ne step窶・ rather than implementation (窶・0.125窶・. ------------------------------------------------------------------------ 8.5 Infinity ( ? and - ?) Syntax Syntax Meaning --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" &gt;?A&#10;;+infinity</code </pre A&nbsp;represents&nbsp;positive&nbsp;infinity&nbsp;(beyond&nbsp;measurable&nbsp;range). <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" -&gt;?A&#10;;-infinity</code </pre A&nbsp;represents&nbsp;negative&nbsp;infinity&nbsp;(beyond&nbsp;measurable&nbsp;range). Infinity represents values beyond measurable range. Rather than clipping to a max integer or saturating silently, BCODe explicitly encodes overflow semantics. This makes telemetry more honest and more interpretable. In many systems, the difference between 窶忻ery high窶・and 窶徙ut of range窶・is operationally important. Infinity communicates the latter cleanly. It also avoids cross-language inconsistencies: JSON doesn窶冲 have a standard numeric representation for infinity, so different toolchains end up with different ad-hoc conventions. BCODe solves this on the wire. ------------------------------------------------------------------------ 8.6 Null (< ?) Syntax Syntax Meaning --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" &lt;&gt;?A</code </pre A&nbsp;represents&nbsp;explicitly&nbsp;null&nbsp;(no-data). <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" &lt;&gt;?0A&#10;;digits MAY be present; class remains NULL</code </pre A&nbsp;is&nbsp;explicitly&nbsp;null&nbsp;(no-data)&nbsp;with&nbsp;advisory&nbsp;code&nbsp;0. Null represents explicit no-data. It is not 窶忖nknown pending.窶・It is 窶彿ntentionally absent.窶・A device might send null when a sensor is disabled, when the data is deliberately cleared, or when the concept is not applicable in the current state. This class matters because telemetry often needs to distinguish 窶從ot yet窶・from 窶從ot applicable.窶・Without that distinction, consumers either guess or add separate schema flags. BCODe keeps it in one place: the field. ------------------------------------------------------------------------ 8.7 Quiet NaN (-< ?) Syntax Syntax Meaning --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" -&lt;&gt;?A</code </pre A&nbsp;represents&nbsp;explicitly&nbsp;null&nbsp;(no-data). Quiet NaN represents an invalid computational result. It implies that computation happened, but the result is undefined or unusable. The defining characteristic is that this state is not 窶徭ensor noise窶・and not 窶徇issing data窶昶琶t is 窶彿nvalid math.窶・In pipelines where values are derived from other signals, this class lets a device report a clear 窶彡alculation failure窶・outcome without inventing a new status parameter. Downstream systems can propagate or quarantine this state using policy logic, while keeping the telemetry representation compact. ------------------------------------------------------------------------ 8.8 Signaling NaN (< and -< ) with payload code Syntax Syntax Meaning --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" 17&lt;&gt;A</code </pre A&nbsp;carries&nbsp;a&nbsp;single-number&nbsp;field&nbsp;(integer),&nbsp;but&nbsp;the&nbsp;digits&nbsp;are&nbsp;not&nbsp;a&nbsp;simple&nbsp;base-10&nbsp;integer. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" -17&lt;&gt;A&#10;;signed code (if domain chooses)</code </pre A&nbsp;carries&nbsp;a&nbsp;single-number&nbsp;field&nbsp;(integer),&nbsp;but&nbsp;the&nbsp;digits&nbsp;are&nbsp;not&nbsp;a&nbsp;simple&nbsp;base-10&nbsp;integer. Signaling NaN carries a payload code in value1. Unlike quiet NaN, signaling NaN is meant to communicate a reason . It is an intentionally structured diagnostic channel. A device can embed a stable error identifier directly in the field that would normally carry the value. This supports a best-practices pattern: diagnostics without extra parameters . Rather than sending A plus A reason, the device can send one field that says 窶廣 is invalid and here is why.窶・The line remains atomic. The schema remains flat. ------------------------------------------------------------------------ 8.9 Staleness modifier (!) 窶・orthogonal freshness Syntax Syntax Meaning --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" !12.3A</code </pre A&nbsp;has&nbsp;the&nbsp;numeric&nbsp;content&nbsp;12.3,&nbsp;but&nbsp;it&nbsp;is&nbsp;stale. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" !&lt;&gt;?A</code </pre A&nbsp;represents&nbsp;explicitly&nbsp;null&nbsp;(no-data),&nbsp;but&nbsp;it&nbsp;is&nbsp;stale. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" !&gt;?A</code </pre A&nbsp;represents&nbsp;positive&nbsp;infinity&nbsp;(beyond&nbsp;measurable&nbsp;range),&nbsp;but&nbsp;it&nbsp;is&nbsp;stale. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" !17&lt;&gt;A</code </pre A&nbsp;carries&nbsp;a&nbsp;single-number&nbsp;field&nbsp;(integer),&nbsp;but&nbsp;the&nbsp;digits&nbsp;are&nbsp;not&nbsp;a&nbsp;simple&nbsp;base-10&nbsp;integer,&nbsp;but&nbsp;it&nbsp;is&nbsp;stale. The ! qualifier is orthogonal. It modifies freshness without altering the base value class. A stale numeric value remains numeric. A stale infinity remains infinity. A stale null remains null. Syntax (staleness examples) Syntax Meaning --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" !12.3A</code </pre A&nbsp;has&nbsp;the&nbsp;numeric&nbsp;content&nbsp;12.3,&nbsp;but&nbsp;it&nbsp;is&nbsp;stale. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" !&lt;&gt;?A</code </pre A&nbsp;is&nbsp;explicitly&nbsp;null&nbsp;(no-data),&nbsp;but&nbsp;that&nbsp;null&nbsp;state&nbsp;is&nbsp;stale. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" !&gt;?A</code </pre A&nbsp;represents&nbsp;positive&nbsp;infinity&nbsp;(beyond&nbsp;measurable&nbsp;range),&nbsp;but&nbsp;that&nbsp;infinity&nbsp;state&nbsp;is&nbsp;stale. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" !17&lt;&gt;A</code </pre A&nbsp;is&nbsp;signaling&nbsp;NaN&nbsp;with&nbsp;diagnostic&nbsp;code&nbsp;17,&nbsp;but&nbsp;that&nbsp;diagnostic&nbsp;is&nbsp;stale. This design preserves semantic clarity: freshness is independent of validity. In telemetry systems, this is a common reality窶敗ometimes the last known value remains useful, but you must know it窶冱 old. Encoding staleness inline avoids time-coupled schemas like A age ms that require extra coordination and timing logic. ------------------------------------------------------------------------ 8.10 Bounds (< and without ?) 窶・not hard values Syntax Syntax Meaning --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" &lt;100A&#10;;value is less than stated (upper bound)</code </pre A&nbsp;has&nbsp;the&nbsp;numeric&nbsp;content&nbsp;100. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" &gt;100A&#10;;value is greater than stated (lower bound)</code </pre A&nbsp;has&nbsp;the&nbsp;numeric&nbsp;content&nbsp;100. Bounds indicate inequality relationships rather than exact values. They are not 窶徨eal numbers窶・in the hard numeric sense; they are statements about intervals. This distinction is crucial: accessors that promise hard numeric values should reject < or unless the caller explicitly requests a bound/interval type. Bounds are especially useful for control intent. Rather than forcing the host to compute an exact target that the device cannot represent cleanly, the host can declare constraints and let the device resolve policy. This is one of the places BCODe feels 窶廨CODE-like窶・ you express intent with compact tokens, and the machine decides the exact actuation details. ------------------------------------------------------------------------ 8.11 Composite qualifier logic 窶・classes emerge from combinations BCODe窶冱 base qualifiers combine into standardized classes. Interpretation layers classify based on the presence of <, , ?, and -, with ! modifying freshness orthogonally. The value class emerges from the combination rather than any single symbol. This deterministic mapping ensures interoperability across implementations. It also enables reducers to summarize line quality efficiently, which is critical for stream tooling and embedded logic. ------------------------------------------------------------------------ Payloads Without Gymnastics BCODe supports three payload forms: Table 9.1 窶・Payload and comment tokens recognized in normal mode Token Meaning Parsed where? Notes --- --- --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" 0x20, TAB, CR, LF</code </pre Whitespace Everywhere except 窶徙paque regions窶・TAB/LF/CR are treated the same as spaces. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" ;</code </pre Line comment Normal mode Runs until LF. If LF never occurs, the comment continues indefinitely (streaming model). <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" (...)</code </pre Parentheses comment Normal mode Runs until the next ). Unterminated comment continues indefinitely. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" $</code </pre String payload Normal mode Ends only at LF or NUL. Within a string payload, comment and terminator tokens are not recognized. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" %</code </pre Hex-byte payload Normal mode Payload content is 2-digit hex bytes; whitespace is allowed; comments are allowed inside. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" &</code </pre Raw-binary payload Normal mode Consumes an integer length (defaults to 0) then reads that many raw bytes (opaque region). <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" #...#</code </pre Hex number literal Inside number spelling Hex digits MUST be uppercase. While # is open, PARAM/CMD bytes are not terminators; only closing # ends the literal. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" . or ,</code </pre Pair separator Normal mode (number spelling) Separates value1 and value2. . indicates non-negative value2; , indicates negative value2 (digits encode magnitude). The width of value2 is preserved. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" / /</code </pre Exponent suffix marker Normal mode (after mantissa) is positive exponent, / is negative exponent. If no digits follow, exponent magnitude defaults to 1. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" - < ? !</code </pre Qualifiers / modifiers Normal mode (field prefix) Any combination of - < ? may appear; ! is orthogonal staleness. Table 9.1 is a practical reminder that payloads are part of the syntax layer: the parser knows exactly when it is in an opaque region and exactly what terminates that region, which is why stream recovery stays deterministic. $... for string payloads (ends at LF or NUL; body is opaque) %...% for hexadecimal byte payloads (whitespace/comments allowed inside) & for raw binary payloads (length derived from the numeric accumulator/value1; body is opaque) Binary payloads do not require base64 encoding. This reduces overhead and preserves exact byte structure. In firmware distribution, diagnostic dumps, or binary sensor frames, this capability simplifies pipelines and reduces computational cost. It also keeps 窶彙inary transport窶・in the protocol itself instead of pushing it into ad-hoc encoding layers. A practical best practice is to keep generation trivial. If your application layer requires complicated escaping or mandatory binary-to-text encodings, you are eroding the advantage of a stream-native format. BCODe is meant to be emit-able with printf-style code and modest discipline. ------------------------------------------------------------------------ Multiline Atomic Packets Multiline grouping is not part of 窶彡ore窶・BCODe. Core BCODe merely defines [ as a legal parameter terminator (one of the 32 identities), but it does not assign special meaning to it. BCODe.meta is the convention that does assign meaning: it uses the [ parameter to tag a set of lines as a packet that receivers should buffer and deliver atomically as a group . Table 10.1 窶・Multiline packet enumeration forms Encoding Meaning Receiver behavior --- --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" i.t[</code </pre Fixed-bound packet line Buffer until line t.t[ arrives, then deliver the whole packet atomically <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" n[</code </pre Open-ended packet line (unknown total) Buffer until a closing n.t[ arrives (no ), then deliver atomically Table 10.1 is referenced in the examples below to clarify why BCODe packets are stream-safe: the receiver never has to guess where a group ends. Lines are buffered until the final index is received. Only then are they delivered as a group. This enables batch updates without sacrificing stream determinism. Fixed-bound packet example Syntax Meaning --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" 1.3[ 10A 1B 0.0a</code </pre Assigns&nbsp;[=1.3,&nbsp;A=10,&nbsp;B=1&nbsp;and&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;atomically&nbsp;on&nbsp;command&nbsp;a. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" 2.3[ 11A 2B 3C 0.0a</code </pre Assigns&nbsp;[=2.3,&nbsp;A=11,&nbsp;B=2,&nbsp;C=3&nbsp;and&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;atomically&nbsp;on&nbsp;command&nbsp;a. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" 3.3[ 1A 2B 3C 0.0a</code </pre Assigns&nbsp;[=3.3,&nbsp;A=1,&nbsp;B=2,&nbsp;C=3&nbsp;and&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;atomically&nbsp;on&nbsp;command&nbsp;a. Open-ended packet example (unknown length at start) Syntax Meaning --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" &gt;1[ 10A 1B 0.0a</code </pre Assigns&nbsp;[=1,&nbsp;A=10,&nbsp;B=1&nbsp;and&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;atomically&nbsp;on&nbsp;command&nbsp;a. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" &gt;2[ 11A 2B 3C 0.0a</code </pre Assigns&nbsp;[=2,&nbsp;A=11,&nbsp;B=2,&nbsp;C=3&nbsp;and&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;atomically&nbsp;on&nbsp;command&nbsp;a. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" 3.3[ 1A 2B 3C 0.0a</code </pre Assigns&nbsp;[=3.3,&nbsp;A=1,&nbsp;B=2,&nbsp;C=3&nbsp;and&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;atomically&nbsp;on&nbsp;command&nbsp;a. Unlike JSON streaming APIs, which often require external framing protocols or 窶彡hunked document窶・rules, BCODe.meta integrates grouping into the stream itself without requiring an external framing protocol. The narrative reason this matters is simple: packets are a common reality in stream systems (multi-line responses, batched telemetry, state snapshots), and BCODe gives you a built-in way to treat them atomically. ------------------------------------------------------------------------ Command and Response Narrative (BCODe.meta) BCODe.meta defines command-response semantics using response tags Table 11.1 窶・BCODe.meta structural tokens Token Meaning (convention) --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" ^</code </pre affirmative response tag (optional timestamp value) <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" \\</code </pre negative response tag (optional error/reason code value) <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" ^\\</code </pre unsolicited statement tag (sent without a request) <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" [</code </pre multiline packet/batch tag <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" ]</code </pre sequence counter <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" -N[</code </pre header-prefix lines that attach metadata to the next deliverable unit Table 11.2 窶・Negative-response error codes: General errors (group = -1) Subcode Symbol Code Meaning -------: -------- ------ --------- 0 BCODEREST ERRGEN CMD UNKNOWN -1.0\\ The command is unknown 1 BCODEREST ERRGEN RES UNKNOWN -1.1\\ The resource id is unknown 2 BCODEREST ERRGEN SEQ MISSING -1.2\\ The command sequence is missing 3 BCODEREST ERRGEN SEQ UNKNOWN -1.3\\ The command sequence is unknown 4 BCODEREST ERRGEN PAYLOAD MISSING -1.4\\ Expected payload but was missing 5 BCODEREST ERRGEN PAYLOAD OVERFLOW -1.5\\ Buffer reserved for payload overflowed 6 BCODEREST ERRGEN PAYLOAD INVALID -1.6\\ Error in the payload data 7 BCODEREST ERRGEN INDEX MISSING -1.7\\ Resource index (@) missing from command 8 BCODEREST ERRGEN INDEX UNKNOWN -1.8\\ Resource index does not exist 9 BCODEREST ERRGEN PARAM MISSING -1.9\\ Required parameter missing from command 10 BCODEREST ERRGEN PARAM OVERRANGE -1.10\\ Parameter exceeds acceptable range 11 BCODEREST ERRGEN PARAM UNDERRANGE -1.11\\ Parameter is less than acceptable 12 BCODEREST ERRGEN PARAM BADQUAL -1.12\\ Parameter has bad qualifier 13 BCODEREST ERRGEN PARAM INVALID -1.13\\ Parameter value was invalid 14 BCODEREST ERRGEN RESP OVERFLOW -1.14\\ Multiline response messages exceed buffer 15 BCODEREST ERRGEN RANGE MISSING -1.15\\ Expected a range specification 16 BCODEREST ERRGEN RANGE OVERFLOW -1.16\\ Expected range extent is too high 17 BCODEREST ERRGEN LINE MISSING -1.17\\ Expected more BCODe lines in input Table 11.3 窶・Negative-response error codes: Multiline errors (group = -2) Subcode Symbol Code Meaning -------: -------- ------ --------- 0 BCODEREST ERRML EXPECTED -2.0\\ Missing multiline parameter [ in a sequence 1 BCODEREST ERRML LAST MISSING -2.1\\ Multiline command missing last value 2 BCODEREST ERRML LAST OVERFLOW -2.2\\ Multiline command exceeds parser buffer 3 BCODEREST ERRML LAST ALTERED -2.3\\ 窶廰ast element窶・did not remain constant in sequence 4 BCODEREST ERRML CNTR START -2.4\\ Counter did not start at 1 5 BCODEREST ERRML CNTR OVERRANGE -2.5\\ Counter is greater than last 6 BCODEREST ERRML CNTR SEQUENCE -2.6\\ Counter did not match expected sequence Table 11.4 窶・Command-specific error groups (group = -ASCII(command)) Group Command Notes ------: :------: ------ -97 a Read dynamic -98 b Write configuration (provisional) -99 c Control operation -100 d (reserved / TBD) -101 e Read static -102 f Manage feeds -105 i Allocate / deallocate that remain parseable and stream-friendly: ^ 窶・affirmative response (may carry a timestamp) \\ 窶・negative response (may carry a reason code) ^\\ 窶・unsolicited statement (sent without a request; ^ may carry a timestamp) Example: affirmative response with timestamp Syntax Meaning --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" 11B 2.0c</code </pre Assigns&nbsp;B=11&nbsp;and&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;atomically&nbsp;on&nbsp;command&nbsp;c. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" 192873121^ 2.0c</code </pre Assigns&nbsp;^=192873121&nbsp;and&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;atomically&nbsp;on&nbsp;command&nbsp;c. Example: negative response with reason (group.subcode) Syntax Meaning --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" 11B 2.0c</code </pre Assigns&nbsp;B=11&nbsp;and&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;atomically&nbsp;on&nbsp;command&nbsp;c. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" -1.13\\ 2.0c</code </pre Assigns&nbsp;\\=-1.13&nbsp;and&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;atomically&nbsp;on&nbsp;command&nbsp;c. A key best practice here is that negative response codes should be decoded as integer pairs , not floats. The distinction between -1.1 (subcode 1) and -1.10 (subcode 10) can be important. Treating the value as a float would erase that difference. The narrative advantage is cohesion: response state, error code, and associated parameters remain within the same atomic line. This keeps the protocol debuggable in plain logs while still supporting structured error handling. ------------------------------------------------------------------------ Resource-Oriented Streams (BCODe.rest) BCODe.rest is a higher-level construction built on top of core BCODe (syntax + interpretation) and the framing patterns of BCODe.meta . It窶冱 intended for larger ecosystems where you want to talk about resources (things with identities and instances) instead of only 窶彗 fixed letter map per command.窶・It窶冱 also the layer that can feel like a mind-bender when encountered too early. For an introductory narrative like this, the goal is not to memorize BCODe.rest窶琶t's to recognize the shape and understand why it exists. If you only need ad-hoc reporting or simple request/response streams, you can happily stop at core BCODe + BCODe.meta and come back to BCODe.rest when you actually need a resource model. The rest of this section therefore keeps the framing simple: it shows the idea (resource id + instance index + command intent) and points you to the dedicated BCODe.rest material for full details. Table 12.1 窶・Operational command categories (telemetry complexity guide) Category Typical meaning Idempotent? Atomic update? Stale allowed? --- --- ---: ---: ---: a dynamic read yes n/a yes (parameter fields) e static read yes n/a no b stored update/readback yes yes (updates) generally no d delta update no yes generally no c control action no request validation is atomic n/a f feeds/logs mixed release is atomic special command-field rules i allocate/deallocate mixed yes n/a Table 12.1 is referenced in later examples to explain why some commands naturally produce synchronous responses while others produce delayed follow-ons. The upper 32 bits map to an IANA PEN namespace. The lower 32 bits identify a specific resource within that namespace. The result is a compact but globally namespaced key that supports scalable ecosystems. This structure enables interoperability without increasing parser complexity. A device can publish many resources (thermostats, valves, sensors, configuration blocks) while keeping the wire format stable. Consumers can decode meanings through published resource maps, or treat unknown resources as 窶彗d-hoc窶・when the PEN is zero. The discovery story (PEN 竊・domain 竊・lookup document) is not about forcing HTTP into streams. It is about providing a path for third-party tooling to interpret streams without out-of-band knowledge, while still keeping the stream format minimal. ------------------------------------------------------------------------ Sequence Tracking and Resilience The ] parameter allows sequence numbering. Discontinuities reveal dropped lines or resets. The DEL byte provides the parser-level resynchronization mechanism (syntax v12). In unstable transports such as serial buses or wireless telemetry links, these features are crucial. Sequence counters help you answer pragmatic questions: Did we miss an update? Did the remote reboot? Did two streams interleave incorrectly? Did our buffering logic drop a packet? BCODe窶冱 philosophy is that these are not 窶從ice to have.窶・In stream systems, they are essential for confidence. ------------------------------------------------------------------------ Extended Telemetry Case Study 窶・Industrial Furnace Imagine a furnace control system: Syntax Meaning --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" &gt;1200T</code </pre T&nbsp;has&nbsp;the&nbsp;numeric&nbsp;content&nbsp;1200. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" !1198T</code </pre T&nbsp;has&nbsp;the&nbsp;numeric&nbsp;content&nbsp;1198,&nbsp;but&nbsp;it&nbsp;is&nbsp;stale. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" &gt;1200T</code </pre T&nbsp;has&nbsp;the&nbsp;numeric&nbsp;content&nbsp;1200. The host requests a lower bound of 1200 degrees. The device reports a stale reading of 1198. The bound remains active. Each line is atomic. Each state is explicit. No schema mutation occurs. The system remains deterministic. And because each statement is only accepted on the explicit command latch, a torn transmission cannot partially update a setpoint or a measurement frame. Notice what is not happening: there is no separate 窶忻alid窶・field, no separate 窶徭tale窶・field, and no implicit coupling rule that says 窶彿f staleFlag then interpret temperature differently.窶・The meaning is localized inside each field. That locality is what keeps stream systems robust when logs are filtered, lines are dropped, or messages are replayed. ------------------------------------------------------------------------ Extended Case Study 窶・Scientific Instrumentation A sensor network might report: Syntax Meaning --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" ?A</code </pre A&nbsp;represents&nbsp;present&nbsp;but&nbsp;unknown/pending. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" -?A</code </pre A&nbsp;represents&nbsp;present&nbsp;but&nbsp;unstable/noisy. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" &lt;&gt;?A</code </pre A&nbsp;represents&nbsp;explicitly&nbsp;null&nbsp;(no-data). Each state conveys distinct meaning: pending measurement, unstable reading, explicit null. Embedding this directly in telemetry reduces application-level ambiguity and simplifies post-processing. In scientific contexts, these distinctions are not cosmetic窶杯hey determine whether you interpolate, discard, repeat measurement, or halt an experiment. ------------------------------------------------------------------------ Reducers and Masks The interpretation layer may reduce field states into bitmasks summarizing: Table 16.1 窶・Typed accessor return modes (interpretation layer, v10) Return Meaning Out params written? --- --- --- BC OK success (fresh) yes BC OK STALE success (stale) yes BC ERR ABSENT parameter not present no BC ERR EMPTY present but empty (C0) no BC ERR SHAPE wrong syntactic form for accessor no BC ERR QUALITY wrong qualifier/ValueKind for accessor no BC ERR OVERFLOW conversion overflow/underflow no Table 16.2 窶・Value variants and what data is considered 窶彗vailable窶・(v10) Variant Condition Available data --- --- --- Absent numeric Shape C0 (empty field) Qualifiers, stale flag only Single integer mantissa Shape C1, no second value value1 Fixed-point mantissa Shape C2 (two integers) value1, value2, value2 neg, frac width Exponent-decorated mantissa exp present==true exp10 plus either single or fixed-point mantissa Integer triplet view (three integers) Shape C1 or C2 (any exponent state) value1, signed value2 (derived from value2 + value2 neg; 0 if absent), exp10 (0 if exponent absent; see exp present) Tables 16.1 and 16.2 connect directly to the reducer story: reducers summarize what the stream said, while typed accessors define what your application is allowed to treat as a hard numeric. Exact values Bounds Diagnostics Staleness Missing fields These reducer masks enable policy logic without schema coupling. Applications can apply rules declaratively based on mask state rather than parameter combinations. In practice, this becomes a clean pipeline: This pipeline is a best-practices recommendation because it keeps parsing deterministic and pushes policy decisions into explicit layers. In other words: don窶冲 bake semantic rules into the parser; let reducers and policy logic handle it. ------------------------------------------------------------------------ Layered Architecture Recap BCODe is layered intentionally: Syntax 窶・deterministic parsing Interpretation 窶・typed accessors and quality classes Meta 窶・request/response and sequencing Rest 窶・resource-oriented control Each layer builds upon the previous without modifying it. This modularity supports scalability and long-term evolution. It also keeps the core promise intact: a basic parser can remain stable even as conventions evolve. ------------------------------------------------------------------------ Closing Narrative BCODe is intentionally constrained. Those constraints are not limitations; they are design decisions aligned with streaming telemetry realities, where data is never 窶彭one,窶・and correctness is measured in how gracefully a system behaves when something inevitably goes wrong. In the same way that a good instrument enclosure is designed for vibration, heat, and dust rather than showroom lighting, BCODe is designed for byte streams that may arrive late, arrive broken, or arrive forever. The architecture treats the stream as the primary habitat, and then builds meaning on top of the stream in layers that remain mechanically reliable even when the environment is noisy. At the wire level, the most important promise is the latch: nothing commits until a command byte is read. That single idea is what makes the format behave predictably over serial lines and long-running sockets. It is why attaching mid-stream can be made safe: you can discard partial accumulation until you see an explicit line terminator, and then you know you have a full atomic statement. In instrumentation terms, the command byte is the 窶徼rigger edge窶・that defines when a measurement frame becomes real. If you lose the edge, you lose the frame窶巴ut you do not accidentally accept half a frame as truth. You can feel this in small examples that mirror common lab and field workflows. Imagine a DAQ-like device reporting three channels窶杯emperature, pressure, and flow窶蚤t a fixed cadence: Syntax Meaning --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" 21.37A 101.8B 3.5C 0.0f</code </pre Assigns&nbsp;A=21.37,&nbsp;B=101.8,&nbsp;C=3.5&nbsp;and&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;atomically&nbsp;on&nbsp;command&nbsp;f. If the stream glitches mid-line, the receiver does not need a recovery heuristic or a brace counter; it simply keeps scanning until the command latch arrives again. The next good line is still parseable, and the device窶冱 telemetry cadence can remain uninterrupted. In many scientific and industrial contexts窶覇specially when the link is a USB-serial adapter, a noisy RS-485 run, or a radio tunnel窶杯his 窶徨ecover without renegotiation窶・behavior is the difference between a log that stays interpretable and a log that becomes an archaeology project. BCODe窶冱 second promise is that quality travels with the value . A sensor does not merely 窶徂ave a number.窶・It also has a reality: sometimes it is settling, sometimes it is saturated, sometimes it is disabled, sometimes it is derived from a computation that failed. BCODe窶冱 qualifier classes turn those realities into first-class wire states. Instead of adding secondary keys, flags, and cross-field dependency rules, the field itself declares what it is. For example, a radiation detector might report a count rate that is temporarily unknown during HV ramp-up: Syntax Meaning --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" ?12A 0.0f</code </pre Assigns&nbsp;A=12&nbsp;(unknown)&nbsp;and&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;atomically&nbsp;on&nbsp;command&nbsp;f. A vibration accelerometer might report a noisy value during mechanical resonance: Syntax Meaning --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" -?3B 0.0f</code </pre Assigns&nbsp;B=3&nbsp;(noisy)&nbsp;and&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;atomically&nbsp;on&nbsp;command&nbsp;f. A humidity probe might explicitly declare no-data because it is unplugged or intentionally disabled: Syntax Meaning --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" &lt;&gt;?H 0.0f</code </pre Assigns&nbsp;H=(empty)&nbsp;(null)&nbsp;and&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;atomically&nbsp;on&nbsp;command&nbsp;f. And a computed 窶彭ew point窶・channel might return invalid because its prerequisite signals produced an undefined intermediate result: Syntax Meaning --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" -&lt;&gt;?D 0.0f</code </pre Assigns&nbsp;D=(empty)&nbsp;(null)&nbsp;and&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;atomically&nbsp;on&nbsp;command&nbsp;f. These are not just pretty syntactic tricks. They are operational shortcuts that reduce integration friction: dashboards can display 窶廸O DATA窶・without a schema lookup; control loops can refuse to act on unstable signals without needing extra bits; logging systems can remain compact while still preserving meaning. In other words, BCODe makes the common telemetry reality窶廃artial trust, conditional validity窶罵ook like a normal part of the protocol rather than an exception bolted on later. The third promise is that control intent can be expressed in a way that respects real devices. In many control problems, the host is tempted to compute an 窶彳xact窶・setpoint, but the device窶冱 actuator is quantized, rate-limited, or constrained by safety policy. BCODe gives you a way to communicate constraints and let the device choose the closest safe representable action. Bounds are the simplest example: Syntax Meaning --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" &gt;1200T 0.0c</code </pre Assigns&nbsp;T=1200&nbsp;and&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;atomically&nbsp;on&nbsp;command&nbsp;c. This expresses 窶彗t least 1200,窶・which is often more faithful to engineering intent than 窶彳xactly 1200.000.窶・When the device responds, it can report what it actually applied窶敗till in one atomic line, still stream-safe. Epsilon is the 窶徭mallest step窶・expression of the same philosophy. In scientific instrumentation, this maps cleanly to stepper-driven stages, tunable laser offsets, or DAC trim values where a 窶徙ne step窶・adjustment is meaningful but the step size depends on calibration tables or dynamic configuration: Syntax Meaning --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" &lt;?G 0.0c</code </pre Assigns&nbsp;G=(empty)&nbsp;(ﾂｱepsilon)&nbsp;and&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;atomically&nbsp;on&nbsp;command&nbsp;c. The host asks for the minimal increment without embedding the device窶冱 quantization into the host窶冱 logic. This reduces coupling, and coupling is what causes field upgrades to break toolchains. BCODe also acknowledges a blunt truth: real systems ship strings and binary. They ship calibration blobs, firmware fragments, waveform snapshots, and diagnostic dumps. Making binary 窶徑ook like text窶・is sometimes useful, but forcing all binary into base64 is frequently overhead you pay forever. BCODe窶冱 payload model keeps strings and bytes as first-class stream elements: Syntax Meaning --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" 256&amp;&lt;256 raw bytes&gt; 0.0f</code </pre Consumes 256 raw payload bytes, then latches atomically on command f. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" %48 65 6C 6C 6F% 0.0f</code </pre Consumes hex payload bytes (48 65 6C 6C 6F), then latches atomically on command f. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" $CAL:OK&lt;LF&gt;0.0f</code </pre Consumes a string payload terminated by LF (or NUL), then latches atomically on command f. The important part is not merely that payloads exist, but that their termination is explicit and deterministic in a stream context. A receiver always knows when it has entered an opaque region and exactly what ends it. That is why the protocol stays debuggable with commodity tools without turning into a format that is 窶徙nly safe if you parse it with the full stack.窶・As systems scale, multiline responses become unavoidable窶播evice inventories, structured diagnostic readouts, large datasets. BCODe窶冱 packet grouping (with [ indices) is the stream-native way to say 窶徼his set of lines is one atomic answer.窶・In scientific terms, it is closer to 窶彭eliver the whole measurement sweep or don窶冲 deliver it at all窶・than to 窶徭tream partial frames and hope the client reassembles them correctly.窶・A fixed-bound packet makes that intention explicit: Syntax Meaning --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" 1.3[ 10A 1B 0.0a</code </pre Assigns&nbsp;[=1.3,&nbsp;A=10,&nbsp;B=1&nbsp;and&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;atomically&nbsp;on&nbsp;command&nbsp;a. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" 2.3[ 11A 2B 3C 0.0a</code </pre Assigns&nbsp;[=2.3,&nbsp;A=11,&nbsp;B=2,&nbsp;C=3&nbsp;and&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;atomically&nbsp;on&nbsp;command&nbsp;a. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" 3.3[ 1A 2B 3C 0.0a</code </pre Assigns&nbsp;[=3.3,&nbsp;A=1,&nbsp;B=2,&nbsp;C=3&nbsp;and&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;atomically&nbsp;on&nbsp;command&nbsp;a. An open-ended packet handles cases where the final line count cannot be known up front窶把ommon in live listings or streamed enumerations窶背hile still preserving atomic delivery once the closing line arrives. Finally, BCODe窶冱 conventions (meta + rest) give you a disciplined story for command/response and resource addressing without turning the stream into a document protocol. Responses remain small and legible, but still structured enough to be reliable. A negative response can carry a code that is stable under parsing rules (integer-pair, not float), and unsolicited follow-ons can be clearly marked without ambiguity: Syntax Meaning --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" -1.13\\ 0.0c</code </pre Assigns&nbsp;\\=-1.13&nbsp;and&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;atomically&nbsp;on&nbsp;command&nbsp;c. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" 192873121^\\ 10A 0.0f</code </pre Assigns&nbsp;\\=(non-int),&nbsp;A=10&nbsp;and&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;atomically&nbsp;on&nbsp;command&nbsp;f. Taken together, these design choices build a format that behaves like a good instrument: A short instrumentation-flavored example makes this concrete without turning the document into a catalog of demos: Example: spectrometer scan frame (stream-safe, line-atomic) Definitions: W = wavelength (nm), I = intensity (counts), ] = sequence counter, f = feed/telemetry command. Syntax Meaning --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" 501.2W 18342I 991] 0.0f</code </pre Assigns&nbsp;W=501.2,&nbsp;I=18342,&nbsp;]=991&nbsp;and&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;atomically&nbsp;on&nbsp;command&nbsp;f. Narrative: A single atomic line carries both the numeric state and a sequence marker. If the stream drops bytes, the next valid f-terminated line reestablishes framing immediately窶馬o external 窶徘acket mode窶・required. (Citations: Syntax latch + 32-parameter masks; Meta sequencing; Interpretation v10 numeric shapes) predictable under stress, easy to inspect, and honest about uncertainty. BCODe is not trying to replace JSON窶冱 strengths. JSON remains excellent for hierarchical documents and web APIs, and its ecosystem is a major advantage when your data looks like a tree and your transport looks like a request/response exchange. BCODe is instead aimed at the places where telemetry is a timeline, not a document; where updates are frequent, not occasional; where parsing must be deterministic in small devices; and where measurement quality must travel with the number, not in an auxiliary schema. If those are your realities窶覇mbedded controllers, lab instruments, industrial control loops, stream-based monitoring tools窶韮CODe offers clarity through constraint and reliability through structure. ------------------------------------------------------------------------ 18.1 Next steps (choose your path) Different readers reach for BCODe for different reasons. Instead of forcing everyone through the same depth all at once, here are a few 窶徘aths窶・you can follow: Getting started (ad窶蘇oc reporting): start with Sections 3窶・ and the Example Gallery. Treat letters as an application-defined map, emit a few lines, and build confidence with the atomic latch model. 窶弩hat do all these letters/symbols mean?窶・ read Sections 5, 10, and 11, then jump to the BCODe.meta convention document. BCODe.meta is the most approachable place to learn structured BCODe thinking (requests vs responses, unsolicited lines, sequence counters, and multi窶鼠ine atomic packets). 窶廬 need interoperable resource semantics窶・ skim Section 12 for the big picture, then switch to the dedicated BCODe.rest material. BCODe.rest is intentionally more structured窶巴est tackled once core syntax + BCODe.meta feel natural. 窶廬窶冦 building tooling窶・ focus on Sections 7, 8, 16, and the reducer/mask discussions, then validate against the syntax test cases. This is where determinism pays dividends. The key idea is that BCODe is intentionally layered: you can adopt it progressively, and you can keep early prototypes deliberately 窶徭loppy窶・while still remaining syntactically valid. End of publication-depth narrative document. Example Gallery 窶・Optional Patterns to Copy-Paste This section is intentionally 窶彳xample-first.窶・Each mini-pattern is optional, but together they form a quick mental library of what BCODe feels like on the wire. The goal isn窶冲 to prescribe one true schema; it窶冱 to show how BCODe窶冱 stream-latched lines , bounded parameters , inline quality , and payload realism can be combined in practical telemetry and control systems. --- 19.1 Atomic latching: why the final command byte matters Syntax Meaning --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" 72A 18B 5C 0.0a</code </pre Assigns&nbsp;A=72,&nbsp;B=18,&nbsp;C=5,&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;when&nbsp;command&nbsp;a&nbsp;arrives. A receiver can ignore partial lines until the final CMD byte arrives. That makes 窶徇id-stream noise窶・far less catastrophic than formats that depend on balanced punctuation. --- 19.2 Minimal 窶徭ingle measurement窶・telemetry Syntax Meaning --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" 12.3T 0.0f</code </pre Assigns&nbsp;T=12.3,&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;on&nbsp;command&nbsp;f. This is the smallest 窶徨eal窶・telemetry statement: one value plus a command that commits it. It stays grep-friendly, and it does not require a schema registry to be useful. --- 19.3 Multi-sensor readout (flat, fast, and still human) Syntax Meaning --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" 101.3P 23.8T 45.1H 0.0f</code </pre Assigns&nbsp;H=45.1,&nbsp;P=101.3,&nbsp;T=23.8,&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;on&nbsp;command&nbsp;f. This kind of line is common in instrumentation: pressure, temperature, and humidity arrive together as a single atomic state update. --- 19.4 Qualifier quick sampler (value-class states without extra 窶徭tatus fields窶・ Syntax Meaning --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" ?T</code </pre T&nbsp;is&nbsp;present&nbsp;but&nbsp;unknown/pending. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" -?T</code </pre T&nbsp;is&nbsp;present&nbsp;but&nbsp;unstable/noisy&nbsp;(do&nbsp;not&nbsp;treat&nbsp;as&nbsp;hard&nbsp;numeric). <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" &lt;&gt;?T</code </pre T&nbsp;is&nbsp;explicitly&nbsp;null&nbsp;(no-data). <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" &gt;?T</code </pre T&nbsp;represents&nbsp;positive&nbsp;infinity&nbsp;(beyond&nbsp;measurable&nbsp;range). <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" -&lt;&gt;?T</code </pre T&nbsp;is&nbsp;NaN/invalid&nbsp;result&nbsp;(not&nbsp;a&nbsp;hard&nbsp;numeric). <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" 17&lt;&gt;T</code </pre T&nbsp;is&nbsp;signaling&nbsp;NaN&nbsp;with&nbsp;diagnostic&nbsp;code&nbsp;17. These are the 窶徼elemetry honesty窶・states you usually end up inventing in ad-hoc JSON schemas. In BCODe they窶决e compact, standardized, and travel with the value itself. --- 19.5 Stale-but-useful: freshness is orthogonal (!) Syntax Meaning --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" !12.3T</code </pre T&nbsp;has&nbsp;the&nbsp;numeric&nbsp;content&nbsp;12.3,&nbsp;but&nbsp;it&nbsp;is&nbsp;stale. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" !&lt;&gt;?T</code </pre T&nbsp;is&nbsp;explicitly&nbsp;null&nbsp;(no-data),&nbsp;but&nbsp;that&nbsp;null&nbsp;state&nbsp;is&nbsp;stale. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" !&gt;?T</code </pre T&nbsp;represents&nbsp;positive&nbsp;infinity&nbsp;(beyond&nbsp;measurable&nbsp;range),&nbsp;but&nbsp;that&nbsp;infinity&nbsp;state&nbsp;is&nbsp;stale. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" !17&lt;&gt;T</code </pre T&nbsp;is&nbsp;signaling&nbsp;NaN&nbsp;with&nbsp;diagnostic&nbsp;code&nbsp;17,&nbsp;but&nbsp;that&nbsp;diagnostic&nbsp;is&nbsp;stale. Staleness is a modifier, not a replacement. This helps decoders distinguish 窶彙ad value窶・from 窶徃ood value, old,窶・which matters in control loops and data logging. --- 19.6 Bounds as intent: delegating resolution to the device Syntax Meaning --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" &gt;1200T 0.0c</code </pre Assigns&nbsp;T&nbsp;as&nbsp;a&nbsp;lower&nbsp;bound&nbsp;( 1200),&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;on&nbsp;command&nbsp;c. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" &lt;0.5V 0.0c</code </pre Assigns&nbsp;V&nbsp;as&nbsp;an&nbsp;upper&nbsp;bound&nbsp;(<0.5),&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;on&nbsp;command&nbsp;c. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" &gt;1000X 1g</code </pre Assigns&nbsp;X&nbsp;as&nbsp;a&nbsp;lower&nbsp;bound&nbsp;( 1000),&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;on&nbsp;command&nbsp;g&nbsp;with&nbsp;value&nbsp;1. A CNC-style 窶徇ove to a safe place窶・command can use this same bound pattern. For example, 1000X 1g expresses 窶彳nsure X is at least 1000窶・rather than demanding a single exact setpoint. That lets the machine choose its own deceleration profile and settle at a point past 1000, which can enable faster motion while still honoring the safety constraint. Bounds let a host express constraints instead of pretending it knows the device窶冱 perfect representable setpoint. It窶冱 a clean way to avoid host竊播evice quantization coupling. --- 19.7 窶彜mallest step窶・control with epsilon (<?) Syntax Meaning --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" &lt;?G 0.0c</code </pre G&nbsp;represents&nbsp;positive&nbsp;epsilon&nbsp;(smallest&nbsp;step),&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;on&nbsp;command&nbsp;c. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" -&lt;?G 0.0c</code </pre G&nbsp;represents&nbsp;negative&nbsp;epsilon&nbsp;(smallest&nbsp;step),&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;on&nbsp;command&nbsp;c. This pattern is surprisingly powerful in lab gear and motion systems: 窶從udge up/down by one device step窶・is expressive without requiring the host to know the step size. --- 19.8 Diagnostics without extra parameters (codes embedded inline) Syntax Meaning --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" ?12E 0.0f</code </pre E&nbsp;is&nbsp;present&nbsp;but&nbsp;unknown/pending&nbsp;with&nbsp;advisory&nbsp;code&nbsp;12,&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;on&nbsp;f. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" -?3E 0.0f</code </pre E&nbsp;is&nbsp;present&nbsp;but&nbsp;unstable/noisy&nbsp;with&nbsp;advisory&nbsp;code&nbsp;3,&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;on&nbsp;f. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" 42&lt;&gt;E 0.0f</code </pre E&nbsp;is&nbsp;signaling&nbsp;NaN&nbsp;with&nbsp;diagnostic&nbsp;code&nbsp;42,&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;on&nbsp;f. In many telemetry stacks you end up creating error code, valid, status, and reason keys. BCODe encourages you to keep the meaning attached to the same field. --- 19.9 Command/response tags (BCODe.meta 窶徘lumbing窶・stays flat) Syntax Meaning --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" ^ 0.0c</code </pre Affirmative&nbsp;response&nbsp;(ack),&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;on&nbsp;command&nbsp;c. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" \\ 0.0c</code </pre Negative&nbsp;response&nbsp;(no&nbsp;reason),&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;on&nbsp;command&nbsp;c. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" -1.13\\ 2.0c</code </pre Assigns&nbsp;\\=-1.13;&nbsp;command&nbsp;is&nbsp;c&nbsp;with&nbsp;value&nbsp;2.0,&nbsp;and&nbsp;the&nbsp;line&nbsp;latches&nbsp;when&nbsp;the&nbsp;command&nbsp;byte&nbsp;is&nbsp;read. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" ^\\ 10A 0.0f</code </pre Unsolicited&nbsp;statement&nbsp;marker&nbsp;(sent&nbsp;without&nbsp;a&nbsp;request),&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;on&nbsp;f. The tags are just parameters. That窶冱 the point: the 窶徇eta窶・framing lives in the same deterministic syntax as everything else. --- 19.10 Multiline packet: fixed-bound (i.t[) Syntax Meaning --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" 1.3[ 10A 0.0a</code </pre Assigns&nbsp;[=1.3&nbsp;as&nbsp;packet&nbsp;index/total,&nbsp;assigns&nbsp;A=10,&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;on&nbsp;a. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" 2.3[ 11A 0.0a</code </pre Assigns&nbsp;[=2.3&nbsp;as&nbsp;packet&nbsp;index/total,&nbsp;assigns&nbsp;A=11,&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;on&nbsp;a. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" 3.3[ 12A 0.0a</code </pre Assigns&nbsp;[=3.3&nbsp;as&nbsp;packet&nbsp;index/total,&nbsp;assigns&nbsp;A=12,&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;on&nbsp;a. Receivers buffer packet lines and deliver them as an atomic group. This is a stream-native way to do 窶彙atch semantics窶・without inventing external framing. --- 19.11 Multiline packet: open-ended ( n[ 窶ｦ closed by n.t[) Syntax Meaning --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" &gt;1[ 10A 0.0a</code </pre Assigns&nbsp;[&nbsp;as&nbsp;open-ended&nbsp;packet&nbsp;index&nbsp; 1,&nbsp;assigns&nbsp;A=10,&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;on&nbsp;a. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" &gt;2[ 11A 0.0a</code </pre Assigns&nbsp;[&nbsp;as&nbsp;open-ended&nbsp;packet&nbsp;index&nbsp; 2,&nbsp;assigns&nbsp;A=11,&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;on&nbsp;a. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" 3.3[ 12A 0.0a</code </pre Assigns&nbsp;[=3.3&nbsp;as&nbsp;the&nbsp;closing&nbsp;bound,&nbsp;assigns&nbsp;A=12,&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;on&nbsp;a. Open-ended packets are great when you can窶冲 know the line count up front (e.g., directory listings, table dumps, streamed results). The close line makes the end unambiguous. --- 19.12 Sequence counter (]) for dropout detection Syntax Meaning --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" 100] 10A 0.0f</code </pre Assigns&nbsp;]=100&nbsp;as&nbsp;a&nbsp;sequence&nbsp;counter,&nbsp;assigns&nbsp;A=10,&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;on&nbsp;f. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" 101] 11A 0.0f</code </pre Assigns&nbsp;]=101&nbsp;as&nbsp;a&nbsp;sequence&nbsp;counter,&nbsp;assigns&nbsp;A=11,&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;on&nbsp;f. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" 0] 12A 0.0f</code </pre Assigns&nbsp;]=0&nbsp;as&nbsp;a&nbsp;reset/discontinuity&nbsp;signal,&nbsp;assigns&nbsp;A=12,&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;on&nbsp;f. Sequence discontinuities let tooling say 窶徭omething happened窶・(drop, reset, reconnect) without guessing. That窶冱 invaluable on flaky serial links. --- 19.13 Payload realism: string payloads ($窶ｦ) A $ payload is an opaque string body terminated by newline (or NUL). It窶冱 useful for human-visible text, firmware identifiers, or log messages without JSON escaping rituals. --- 19.14 Hex payloads (%窶ｦ%): readable binary snapshots Hex payloads are a practical 窶彙ridge form窶・when you want to carry bytes but still keep logs inspectable. Whitespace and comments can live inside the %窶ｦ% block in many tooling contexts. --- 19.15 Raw binary payloads (&): exact bytes, no base64 Syntax Meaning --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" 16&amp; 0.0u</code </pre Command&nbsp;expects&nbsp;a&nbsp;raw-binary&nbsp;payload&nbsp;of&nbsp;length&nbsp;16&nbsp;bytes,&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;on&nbsp;u&nbsp;after&nbsp;payload&nbsp;receipt. This is the 窶從o-gymnastics窶・payload path: bytes are bytes. It窶冱 especially attractive for calibration blobs, waveform fragments, and device snapshots. --- 19.16 Scientific notation: large/small without changing the wire feel Syntax Meaning --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" 123 3A 0.0f</code </pre Assigns&nbsp;A&nbsp;with&nbsp;exponent-scaled&nbsp;numeric&nbsp;spelling&nbsp;(ﾃ・0^3),&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;on&nbsp;f. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" 45/2B 0.0f</code </pre Assigns&nbsp;B&nbsp;with&nbsp;exponent-scaled&nbsp;numeric&nbsp;spelling&nbsp;(ﾃ・0^-2),&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;on&nbsp;f. This keeps values compact in a way engineers recognize immediately, while still letting parsers treat the exponent as structured metadata. --- 19.17 Resource-oriented streams (BCODe.rest): ID + index + command Syntax Meaning --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" 0@ 12345.7a</code </pre Assigns&nbsp;@=0&nbsp;as&nbsp;resource&nbsp;index,&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;on&nbsp;command&nbsp;a&nbsp;for&nbsp;resource&nbsp;12345&nbsp;with&nbsp;sequence&nbsp;7. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" 2@ 12345.7e</code </pre Assigns&nbsp;@=2&nbsp;as&nbsp;resource&nbsp;index,&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;on&nbsp;command&nbsp;e&nbsp;for&nbsp;resource&nbsp;12345&nbsp;with&nbsp;sequence&nbsp;7. This pattern scales well: the command number is the resource key, @ selects the instance, and the command letter expresses intent (read/write/control/feed/allocate). --- 19.18 Ordinals ( R) as response 窶徑anes窶・(direct vs delayed) Syntax Meaning --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" ^ 0@ 12345.7 0a</code </pre Affirmative&nbsp;ack&nbsp;for&nbsp;sequence&nbsp;7&nbsp;at&nbsp;ordinal&nbsp;0,&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;on&nbsp;a. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" ^\\ 0@ 10A 12345.7 1a</code </pre Unsolicited&nbsp;follow-on&nbsp;result&nbsp;at&nbsp;ordinal&nbsp;1,&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;on&nbsp;a. Ordinals let one request evolve into multi-stage reporting without renumbering the command sequence. It窶冱 a clean way to handle 窶彗ck now, results later.窶・--- 19.19 Engineering use case: temperature controller (constraint + stale readback) Syntax Meaning --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" &gt;1200T 0.0c</code </pre Assigns&nbsp;T&nbsp;as&nbsp;a&nbsp;lower&nbsp;bound&nbsp;( 1200)&nbsp;set&nbsp;intent,&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;on&nbsp;c. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" ^ 0.0c</code </pre Affirmative&nbsp;response&nbsp;(ack),&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;on&nbsp;c. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" !1198T 0.0f</code </pre T&nbsp;has&nbsp;the&nbsp;numeric&nbsp;content&nbsp;1198,&nbsp;but&nbsp;it&nbsp;is&nbsp;stale,&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;on&nbsp;f. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" 1203T 0.0f</code </pre Assigns&nbsp;T=1203&nbsp;as&nbsp;a&nbsp;fresh&nbsp;readback,&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;on&nbsp;f. This shows three core ideas at once: intent via bounds, atomic ack via meta tags, and the ability to explicitly distinguish 窶徙ld but still informative窶・from 窶彷resh.窶・--- 19.20 Scientific instrumentation: saturation and diagnostics (spectrometer-style) Syntax Meaning --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" &gt;?I 0.0f</code </pre I&nbsp;represents&nbsp;positive&nbsp;infinity&nbsp;(sensor&nbsp;saturated),&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;on&nbsp;f. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" 42&lt;&gt;I 0.0f</code </pre I&nbsp;is&nbsp;signaling&nbsp;NaN&nbsp;with&nbsp;diagnostic&nbsp;code&nbsp;42&nbsp;(structured&nbsp;fault),&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;on&nbsp;f. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" -?I 0.0f</code </pre I&nbsp;is&nbsp;present&nbsp;but&nbsp;unstable/noisy&nbsp;(transient),&nbsp;then&nbsp;latches&nbsp;on&nbsp;f. A lot of lab gear needs to say 窶從ot a number, and here窶冱 why.窶・Inline value classes make that honest, compact, and machine-checkable. --- 19.21 One last 窶彭ebugger窶冱 trick窶・ grep patterns that stay meaningful BCODe examples are designed to remain readable under commodity tools. When you can search logs effectively, you debug faster窶蚤nd a stream protocol lives or dies by debuggability. References JSON (background context used for narrative framing): JSON.org 窶・JSON syntax overview: https://www.json.org/json-en.html Eloquent JavaScript (JSON chapter/section): https://eloquentjavascript.net/04 data.html Douglas Crockford 窶・窶弋he Application/JSON Media Type窶・/ related writings & McKeeman form discussion: https://www.crockford.com/mckeeman.html Online JSON Parser (example-style reference): http://json.parser.online.fr/beta/ BCODe companion documents (normative sources for the concepts described here): bcode-syntax-with-tests-v12.md (syntax, terminators, payload tokens, latch rules) bcode-interpretation-v10.md (qualifier classes, freshness, typed accessors, variants) BCODe meta Convention.updated6.md (command/response tags, packets, sequencing conventions) BCODe Best Practices and Conventions Draft v13.md (design principles, interoperability guidance) BCODe telemetry scalable complexity guide plus.md` (telemetry/control scaling patterns)"}, {"slug": "syntax", "display_title": "Syntax (v13)", "preview_title": "bcode-syntax-with-tests-v13 窶・Preview", "description": "BCODe Syntax Specification (Draft v13) BCODe (lowercase e ) is a streaming ASCII protocol for numeric data with payloads and comments. This document defines syntax and streaming parsing rules only . Companion ?", "corpus_text": "BCODe Syntax Specification (Draft v13) BCODe (lowercase e ) is a streaming ASCII protocol for numeric data with payloads and comments. This document defines syntax and streaming parsing rules only . Companion document: BCODe Value Interpretation (Draft) Status: Draft Document date: 2026-02-22 Syntax version: v13 Audience: implementers Companion document: bcode-interpretation-v13.html defines standard interpretations, transforms, reducers, and reference accessors. This document (syntax) does not assign meaning to commands or parameters. Normative keywords 窶廴UST窶・ 窶廴UST NOT窶・ 窶彜HOULD窶・ 窶彜HOULD NOT窶・ and 窶廴AY窶・are to be interpreted as in RFC 2119. Contents Scope Metanotation and Abstract Symbols Streaming model ASCII column grammar Line structure & latching Whitespace Comments Payloads Fields Numbers & fractional width Scientific exponent suffix Implementation limits Interleaving Opaque regions & precedence Conformance Error handling & resynchronization Appendix A 窶・ABNF Appendix B 窶・Streaming state machine Appendix C 窶・State machine diagram Appendix D 窶・Canonical C parser Appendix E 窶・Design notes Appendix F 窶・Conformance tests Appendix G 窶・Streaming conformance Appendix H 窶・Code generation reference Scope This document defines the core syntax and streaming parsing model of BCODe: ASCII-column token classes, lines and latching, fields (qualifiers + numbers), payloads, comments, whitespace, interleaving rules, deterministic recognition precedence, and a canonical streaming parser reference. This document does not assign semantic meaning to any particular parameter character or command character, except where a character is reserved for parser-level resynchronization. The command byte DEL (0x7F) is reserved for parser reset/resynchronization and MUST NOT be assigned higher-layer meaning (see Section 16.1). Interpretation of qualifier combinations and numeric types is defined separately. Metanotation and Abstract Symbols (Informative) This section defines the metanotation used in this document when describing BCODe syntax abstractly. These symbols are used only in specification prose and formal derivations. They do not appear on the wire and do not alter the grammar defined elsewhere in this document. Greek letters represent abstract roles within a BCODe line. Literal ASCII punctuation (such as ., ,, , /) is shown explicitly and always represents actual on-wire characters. 2.1 Terminators Command Terminator ﾎｺ竄・Represents a command terminator character (ASCII 0x60窶・x7F). The subscript n provides local numbering within a given derivation or example. It has no semantic meaning beyond distinguishing occurrences in the text. If identity is relevant, the actual ASCII character is stated explicitly, for example: ﾎｺ竄・= 'b' --- Parameter Terminator ﾎ竄・Represents a parameter terminator character (ASCII 0x40窶・x5F). The subscript n provides local numbering within a given derivation or example. It does not imply any absolute indexing or bit position. If identity matters, the specific ASCII character is given explicitly, for example: ﾎ竄・= 'A' --- 2.2 Field Values Abstract Field Value ﾎｦ Represents a complete numeric field value, independent of its internal structure. This abstraction is used when the internal decomposition of the field value is not relevant to the discussion. --- Numeric Decomposition When the internal structure of a field value matters, it is decomposed as: ﾎｦ ::= ﾎ・[ . , ﾎ・] [ ( /) ﾎ・] Where: ﾎ・represents the first numeric value (value1). ﾎ・represents the second numeric value (value2), if present. ﾎ・represents the exponent magnitude, if present. . or , are literal on-wire pair separators. or / are literal on-wire exponent operators. The comma separator indicates a negative ﾎ・ as defined in the syntax rules. The exponent magnitude ﾎ・corresponds to the integer value following or /. Subscripts MAY be used when multiple values appear in the same derivation: ﾎ凪ａ, ﾎ披ａ, ﾎ樞ａ --- 2.3 Payload Structure Abstract Payload ﾎｩ Represents an abstract payload body (string, hex-byte, or raw binary payload). When a payload is preceded by a numeric length hint, the abstract form is written: ﾎ・ﾎｩ where ﾎ・represents the length hint value and ﾎｩ represents the payload body. --- 2.4 Abstract Line Structure A BCODe line is abstractly represented as: ( ﾎｦ ﾎ竄・) ﾎｦ ﾎｺ竄・Meaning: Zero or more parameter-terminated fields Followed by one command-terminated field The line is latched upon reading ﾎｺ竄・ as defined by the command termination rules elsewhere in this document. --- 2.5 Notes Greek symbols are used only for specification clarity and never appear in the transmitted byte stream. ASCII punctuation shown in this section (., ,, , /) always represents literal on-wire characters. Subscripts provide local disambiguation within a derivation and have no independent protocol meaning. This metanotation is layered: discussions may operate at the ﾎｦ level (entire field value) or at the ﾎ・ﾎ・ﾎ・level (numeric decomposition) as appropriate. Streaming model BCODe is parsed from a potentially unbounded byte stream. There is no concept of end-of-file . The consumer decides where the stream starts and ends. A BCODe 窶徑ine窶・is a logical unit that ends when a command character is read in normal mode. All parsed state (fields, payloads) is latched atomically at that moment. 3.1 Stream start, session boundaries, and transport open events (Normative) Because BCODe has no end-of-file and command bytes are only recognized in normal mode (see Section 14 and Appendix B), a receiver cannot assume it is synchronized unless the transport or a higher-layer convention provides an explicit stream start. An implementation MUST reset its parser to the baseline state ( S\\ NORMAL with an empty pending line) whenever it begins consuming a new logical stream. Transports with a distinct open event. On session-oriented transports with a reliable 窶徙pen窶・event (for example: TCP connection establishment and WebSocket open), a receiver MUST reset its parser at the open event, and MUST NOT carry parser state across sessions. Transports without a distinct open event. On channels where a receiver may begin observing bytes at an arbitrary time, or where peers may reset independently while the channel remains 窶忖p窶・(for example: UART links, named FIFOs, and UDP), higher layers MUST provide an explicit resynchronization mechanism. This specification reserves the command byte DEL (0x7F) as an in-band parser reset/resynchronization command (Section 16.1). ASCII column grammar (Normative) Metanotation reference. In abstract descriptions, a parameter terminator is denoted ﾎ竄・and a command terminator is denoted ﾎｺ竄・ Thus a field is terminated by either ﾎ竄・(PARAM) or ﾎｺ竄・(CMD). These symbols are descriptive only; on-wire classification remains defined by ASCII range (Section 4). BCODe assigns grammatical meaning by ASCII 窶彡olumn窶・ i.e., by the upper three bits of the byte (c & 0xE0). Token identity within a class can be derived from the lower five bits (c & 0x1F). 4.1 ASCII columns used ASCII range Column Typical chars BCODe role --- --- --- --- 0x20窶・x3F 2 <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" SP ! \" ## %% && ' (;) + / 0窶・ : < = ? , - . $$</code </pre Field content, qualifiers, numeric punctuation, payload/comment markers, exponent markers 0x40窶・x5F 3 <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" @ A窶纏 [ \\ ] ^ </code </pre Parameter characters (terminate intermediate fields) 0x60窶・x7F 4 <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" a窶奴 DEL {} </code </pre Command characters (terminate line and latch). The byte DEL (0x7F) is reserved for parser reset/resynchronization (Section 15.1). Line structure & latching (Normative) Abstract line form. Using the metanotation defined in Section 2, a BCODe line has the abstract structure: ( ﾎｦ ﾎ竄・) ﾎｦ ﾎｺ竄・This expression captures the structural rule that zero or more parameter-terminated fields precede exactly one command-terminated field, and that latching occurs upon reading ﾎｺ竄・ A BCODe line is any sequence of fields, payloads, and whitespace/comments that ends with a command character. Newlines are not line terminators in BCODe. All fields and payloads parsed since the previous command character are latched when the next command character is read. No semantic action is taken prior to latching. Payloads SHOULD precede fields for readability, but this is not required. Whitespace (Normative) Outside opaque regions, the following are treated identically as ignorable whitespace: SP (0x20), HTAB (0x09), CR (0x0D), LF (0x0A) Outside opaque regions and comments, whitespace MAY appear anywhere (including inside numbers, exponents, and between qualifiers) and MUST NOT affect syntax-level values. Comments (Normative) Comments are treated as ignorable whitespace with opaque content: the parser MUST NOT interpret comment contents as syntax, and comment contents are not part of the latched semantic record. 7.1 Semicolon comment A semicolon comment begins with ; and ends at the next LF (0x0A). 7.2 Parenthesized comment A parenthesized comment begins with ( and ends at the next ). Comments are not nestable. 7.3 Where comments are recognized Comments are recognized in normal mode. Comments are not recognized inside opaque regions (string payload bodies and raw binary bodies). Comments are recognized inside %...% hex payload bodies and removed before decoding. Payloads (Normative) A line may include zero or more payloads, appearing anywhere before the command character. Payloads are latched along with fields when the command character is read. 8.1 String payload (opaque) A string payload begins with $ and ends at LF (0x0A) or NUL (0x00). The body is opaque: no comments or other syntax are recognized inside. Optional length hint An optional unsigned integer length hint MAY precede the $. It provides a receiver a head窶爽p for buffer sizing and an extra end窶奏o窶粗nd verification signal. The hint indicates the number of payload bytes excluding the terminating LF/NUL. The length hint uses the normal integer literal syntax: decimal digits or uppercase hex #...#. Whitespace (SP/HTAB/CR/LF) is ignored, and comments MAY appear between digits and before $. Qualifiers have no meaning for payload length and SHOULD NOT be used on a length hint. If a length hint is present, the string payload length (bytes before LF/NUL) MUST match it exactly. If the terminator occurs early, or if more bytes arrive than hinted, this is a parse error. 8.2 Hex-byte binary payload (comment-friendly) A hex-byte payload is bounded by % characters and encodes bytes as pairs of uppercase hex digits. Whitespace is allowed and ignored. Comments are allowed inside and removed prior to decoding. Optional decoded-length hint An optional unsigned integer length hint MAY precede the opening %. The hint indicates the number of decoded bytes carried inside %...% (i.e., after removing whitespace/comments and converting hex digit pairs to bytes). After removing whitespace and comments from %...%, the remaining hex digit count MUST be even (two digits per byte), and digits MUST be uppercase 0窶・ or A窶擢. If a decoded-length hint is present, the decoded byte count MUST match it exactly; otherwise this is a parse error. 8.3 Length-prefixed raw binary payload (opaque body) A length-prefixed raw binary payload begins with an & delimiter and consumes exactly payload\\ length raw bytes. A numeric length MAY appear immediately before & (allowing intervening whitespace), otherwise length defaults to 0. Raw payload length derivation (updated) The payload length MUST be derived from the field窶冱 first numeric value (value1) only. If value1 has already been committed, payload length = value1. Otherwise, if a first-number accumulator exists, payload length is the current accumulator value. Otherwise, payload length = 0. Decimal fractions and exponent suffixes MUST NOT affect payload length. Including them is safe but discouraged. After determining payload length, the parser MUST consume/reset the numeric accumulator and then consume exactly payload length raw bytes. If & appears while a hex number is open (i.e., between the opening and closing #), parsing resumes in that same 窶徂ex-open窶・mode after the raw payload is consumed. This is permitted but strongly discouraged. 8.4 Qualifiers do not apply to payloads Qualifier characters (-, <, , ?, !) apply only to fields. If qualifiers appear adjacent to payloads, they MUST NOT be interpreted as modifying that payload. Fields (Normative) Fields carry numeric data and are terminated by either a parameter character (intermediate fields) or a command character (final field). 9.1 Field termination A parameter character (ASCII 0x40窶・x5F) terminates a field and identifies a parameter. A command character (ASCII 0x60窶・x7F) terminates the final field and latches the entire line. Terminators are not part of the field value. 9.2 Qualifiers (syntax only) Each field may contain any combination of the following qualifier characters: This document defines only the syntax of qualifier presence. The standard interpretation of qualifier combinations and the meaning of ! (freshness modifier) are defined separately. 9.3 Empty fields (Normative) Empty fields are permitted. An empty field is a field terminator (parameter or command character) that occurs when no numeric value has been provided for the current field. A parser MUST treat an empty field as having: value1 = 0, value2 = 0, frac width = 0, and qualifier flags as accumulated (if any qualifiers appeared). 9.4 Enumeration of field forms (Normative) Decimal vs hex encoding, pair separator choice (. for positive value2, , for negative value2), and optional exponent suffix do not create distinct field forms. The terminator class (PARAM vs CMD) does create distinct field forms. 8.4.1 Content shapes Shape ID Canonical spelling Description --- --- --- C0 <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" Q T</code </pre Empty field (no numeric content) C1 <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" Q N [EXP] T</code </pre Single-number field with optional exponent suffix C2 <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" Q N S M [EXP] T</code </pre Two-number field (fixed-point pair) with optional exponent suffix 8.4.2 Distinct field forms by terminator class Each content shape has two terminator-class variants: 窶ｦP for parameter terminators (0x40窶・x5F) and 窶ｦC for command terminators (0x60窶・x7F). Form ID Shape Terminator Canonical spelling --- --- --- --- F0P C0 PARAM <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" Q PARAM</code </pre F1P C1 PARAM <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" Q N [EXP] PARAM</code </pre F2P C2 PARAM <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" Q N S M [EXP] PARAM</code </pre F0C C0 CMD <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" Q CMD</code </pre F1C C1 CMD <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" Q N [EXP] CMD</code </pre F2C C2 CMD <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" Q N S M [EXP] CMD</code </pre Whitespace/comments and interleaved payloads (outside opaque regions) do not change the field form classification (C0/C1/C2, PARAM/CMD). Numbers & fractional width (Normative) 10.1 One or two numeric values A field contains one or two numeric values. If two values are present, they are separated by either . or ,. The separator indicates the sign of the second value: . indicates a non-negative value2, and , indicates a negative value2. The digits of value2 encode the magnitude; the sign MUST be derived solely from the separator and MUST be recorded by the parser. Note: In BCODe syntax, . and , are pair separators, not locale-dependent decimal separators. This specification records the sign and digits; numeric interpretation is defined separately. 10.2 Decimal vs hex Each numeric value is either decimal digits (0窶・) or hex digits bounded by #: 10.3 Uppercase-only hex digits (safety constraint) Hex digits MUST be uppercase only: 0窶・ and A窶擢. Lowercase a窶吐 are forbidden. A hex value MUST be terminated by a closing #, and MUST contain at least one hex digit. Hex literals are opaque to field terminators: while inside an open #...# sequence, PARAM and CMD characters MUST NOT terminate the field. Only the closing # ends the hex literal. If a terminator is encountered before the closing #, the construct is malformed and a parser SHOULD resynchronize. 10.4 Leading zeros Leading zeros in value1 are permitted and MUST NOT affect syntax-level numeric parsing. Leading zeros in value2 are permitted; the digit count in value2 is recorded as frac width. 10.5 Fractional width recording For every field, the parser MUST record frac width as follows: if a second numeric value is absent, frac width = 0; otherwise, frac width is the number of digits in value2 as encoded (whitespace/comments ignored; # delimiters excluded). Scientific exponent suffix (Normative) BCODe supports a compact scientific notation suffix on the mantissa. The exponent is an integer and is encoded using a column-2 marker character to avoid reusing the - qualifier. 11.1 Syntax Marker Meaning Exponent value if digits omitted --- --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" </code </pre Positive exponent +1 (discouraged) <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" /</code </pre Negative exponent -1 (discouraged) The exponent marker MUST occur after the mantissa (value1 or value1.value2) and before the field terminator. The pair separator (. or ,) MUST NOT occur after an exponent marker. The exponent digits (if present) MUST be decimal digits 0窶・ (whitespace/comments may appear between digits). If an exponent marker is present with no digits, the exponent magnitude defaults to 1 (safe but discouraged). Only one exponent marker is allowed per field. 11.2 Parser output A conforming parser MUST record the exponent suffix as: exp present (boolean) and exp10 (signed integer base-10 exponent; 0 if absent). This document defines how the exponent is parsed and recorded. How typed accessors apply the exponent is defined in the interpretation document. 11.3 Examples Implementation limits (Normative) The BCODe language does not impose fixed numeric size limits. Implementations MAY impose bounds on numeric magnitude, digit count, fractional width, exponent magnitude, and payload lengths for practical reasons. If an implementation cannot represent a value (overflow, excessive length, etc.), it MUST treat the construct as malformed and apply its resynchronization strategy. Interleaving (Normative) BCODe permits comments and payloads to appear between tokens, including within fields and within numeric spellings, subject to opaque-region rules. Interleaving of payloads and comments is permitted in normal mode, including between digits of a numeric spelling or exponent. Comments and payload markers are not recognized inside opaque regions (string payload bodies and raw-binary bodies). Comments are recognized inside %...% and removed prior to hex decoding. Opaque regions & recognition precedence (Normative) 14.1 Opaque regions String payload body: after $ until LF or NUL terminator (terminator consumed) Raw binary payload body: after & until exactly payload\\ length bytes are consumed 14.2 Recognition precedence outside opaque regions ; begins a semicolon comment (ends at LF) ( begins a parenthesized comment (ends at )) $ begins a string payload (opaque) % begins a hex-byte payload (comments allowed inside) & begins a raw binary payload (length derived from value1 as in Section 8.3) Parameter character (0x40窶・x5F) terminates a field Command character (0x60窶・x7F) terminates the final field and latches the line Otherwise, bytes contribute to the current field (qualifiers/numbers/exponent), ignoring whitespace This precedence yields a single deterministic parse of the stream. Conformance (Normative) MUST classify PARAM as 0x40窶・x5F and CMD as 0x60窶・x7F. MUST latch line state only on CMD encountered outside opaque regions and comments. MUST treat the command byte DEL (0x7F) as a reserved parser reset/resynchronization token in normal mode (Section 16.1), and MUST NOT deliver it as an application-visible command. MUST treat SP/HTAB/CR/LF as ignorable whitespace outside opaque regions/comments. MUST accept both pair separators . and ,; . indicates a non-negative value2, and , indicates a negative value2 (digits encode magnitude). MUST enforce uppercase-only hex digits (0窶・A窶擢) in #...# and in %...%. MUST require at least one hex digit inside #...# (no empty hex values). MUST record frac width per Section 10.5. MUST record exponent suffix as exp present and exp10 per Section 11. MUST treat string payload body and raw binary body as opaque; no comments/syntax recognized inside. MUST allow comments inside %...% and remove them before hex decoding. MUST start a raw binary payload on & with length defaulting to 0 when absent. MUST derive raw payload length from value1 only; fraction/exponent MUST NOT affect length. MUST permit empty fields and treat them as zeros per Section 9.3. MUST accept the qualifier character set - < ? ! syntactically. Error handling & resynchronization Recommended strategy: on detecting a malformed construct in normal mode (invalid hex digit, malformed #...#, odd digit count in %...%, malformed exponent, etc.), an implementation SHOULD discard the pending line state and resynchronize by scanning until the next command character encountered in normal mode. 16.1 Reserved parser reset / resynchronization command (DEL) The command byte DEL (ASCII 0x7F) is reserved for parser reset / resynchronization and MUST NOT be assigned meaning by higher-layer schemas, conventions, or applications. The reset byte is recognized only when encountered as a command terminator in S\\ NORMAL (see Appendix B.2). It is not recognized inside comment bodies, or inside opaque regions such as $...LF/NUL string bodies or &...raw bytes... bodies. When DEL is read in S\\ NORMAL , a conforming parser MUST discard any pending (not-yet-latched) line state and MUST report a parser reset event to the host (implementation-defined API; see Appendix D for one reference). The parser MUST NOT report any normal 窶徑ine latched窶・event for DEL, and MUST NOT deliver the reset byte upward as an application-visible command. 15.1.1 Reset acknowledgement token A reset acknowledgement is encoded as the two-byte sequence 0x3E 0x7F (ASCII followed by DEL). In this document we write this token as <DEL , where <DEL denotes the single byte 0x7F. It consists of a line containing only the qualifier (no numeric content) terminated by the reserved reset command byte. Parsers MAY classify reset events as either 窶徨eset request窶・or 窶徨eset acknowledgement窶・based on whether the pending line state matches this acknowledgement shape. A receiver that implements the reset mechanism MUST transmit the reset acknowledgement token (0x3E 0x7F) after receiving a reset request. A receiver MUST NOT transmit a reset acknowledgement in response to a reset acknowledgement. Diagnostics: Implementations MAY render the 0x7F byte as 窶廛EL窶・ 窶弯?窶・ or 窶・DEL 窶・in logs and UIs. The on-wire acknowledgement is always exactly two bytes. 16.2 Recommended serial resynchronization procedure (Informative) Because command bytes are not recognized inside opaque regions and comments, a peer may be 窶徭tuck窶・consuming an unknown number of bytes in a parenthesized comment body (until )), a semicolon comment (until LF), a $ string payload body (until LF/NUL), or a raw & payload body (until N bytes are consumed). The following byte sequence is commonly used on serial/terminal links to regain synchronization. After each step, the sender MUST check RX for the reset acknowledgement token (0x3E 0x7F, written <DEL ; Section 16.1.1). If the acknowledgement is observed, the sender MUST stop transmitting further resynchronization bytes. Send a single ) byte (0x29) to terminate any parenthesized comment. Send a single DEL byte (0x7F) as a reset request. Send a single LF byte (0x0A, \\n) to terminate any semicolon comment and to terminate any $...LF string payload body. Send DEL (0x7F) repeatedly (checking RX for <DEL after each transmitted byte) until the peer responds with the reset acknowledgement token <DEL . If a bare DEL (0x7F) is observed on RX before any byte is observed, abort and fail (probable serial loopback/echo). Because DEL (0x7F) is non-printing and may be intercepted by TTY line editing, 窶徇anual reset窶・typically requires a tool, macro, or device-specific UI that can emit the byte explicitly on the wire (raw/binary mode). When raw binary payloads are used, such tooling may also need to transmit enough bytes to exhaust a known maximum raw payload length before a reset can be recognized. Appendix A 窶・ABNF (RFC 5234 style) ABNF cannot fully express streaming state (opaque regions and byte-counted raw binary). The ABNF below describes token shapes; normative state behavior is defined in Appendix B. Appendix B 窶・Streaming parser state machine (Normative) B.1 States S\\ NORMAL : normal recognition mode S\\ SEMI\\ COMMENT : inside ;...LF S\\ PAREN\\ COMMENT : inside (...) S\\ STRING\\ PAYLOAD : inside $...LF/NUL (opaque) S\\ HEX\\ PAYLOAD : inside %...% (comments allowed) S\\ RAWBIN\\ PAYLOAD : consuming payload\\ length raw bytes after & (opaque) B.2 Latching rule A command character (ASCII 0x60窶・x7F) latches the pending line state only when encountered in S\\ NORMAL . Command characters in any other state are treated as literal data and MUST NOT latch. The reserved command byte DEL (0x7F) is handled specially in S\\ NORMAL : it triggers a parser reset/resynchronization event and discards pending line state rather than producing a normal line latch (Section 16.1). B.3 Key transitions Length hint recognition: For $ and opening %, a length hint is recognized only when the parser has accumulated a standalone, unqualified integer immediately before the payload start. If recognized, that integer is consumed as the payload窶冱 length hint and is not part of any field. Appendix C 窶・State machine diagram (Informative) Copy into any Mermaid renderer (this HTML does not load external scripts). Appendix D 窶・Canonical C parser (Reference) This is a canonical streaming parser for the syntax rules in this document. It reports fields/payloads as they are parsed; an application that wants a 窶忤hole latched line窶・can buffer events until on line latched. Show canonical C parser (single-file reference) Appendix E 窶・Design notes (Informative) E.1 ASCII-column partitioning Using ASCII range classes (column 3 for parameters and column 4 for commands) creates a hard boundary between 窶彭ata characters窶・and 窶徭tructural terminators窶・ Parsers can classify bytes via range checks or bit masks. E.2 Latching on command The 窶彡ommit on command character窶・model provides atomic updates and avoids partial application of streamed data. It also provides a natural resynchronization boundary in noisy links. E.3 Uppercase-only hex is a safety feature Lowercase a窶吐 live in the command-column ASCII range. Forbidding them reduces the chance that malformed or truncated hex sequences could accidentally resemble command characters or otherwise destabilize parsing. E.4 Scientific exponent suffix The exponent suffix ( and /) adds scale expressiveness while keeping the base qualifier set unchanged. The suffix is intentionally constrained (integer decimal exponent, default magnitude 1 if digits omitted) to preserve streaming determinism. E.5 Reserved reset byte choice (DEL) BCODe reserves exactly one command byte for parser-level resynchronization. Earlier drafts reserved the printable backtick character ( , 0x60); this draft instead reserves DEL (0x7F). Opportunity cost. Many applications want to use human-readable command characters in the CMD range. Reserving a commonly typed printable character has a higher long-term cost than reserving a non-printing control code. Reserving DEL preserves the rest of the command set (including backtick) for higher-layer meaning. Reset is a special case. Parser reset is primarily required to establish synchronization on communication channels without a distinct 窶徙pen窶・event (see Section 3.1) and as a programmatic recovery mechanism after corruption. It is not a common 窶彙usiness-level窶・command. Human/manual operation is environment-specific. Some terminal and TTY stacks treat 0x7F as an erase/backspace key and may intercept it unless the link is in raw/binary mode. Implementations that expose a 窶徇anual reset窶・workflow should provide a tool, macro, or UI affordance to emit 0x7F explicitly. E.6 Reset cannot preempt opaque payloads The reset command is recognized only in S\\ NORMAL . Inside opaque payload bodies ($...LF/NUL and raw &...bytes...), all bytes窶琶ncluding CMD bytes窶蚤re treated as literal payload data. As a result, resynchronization may require draining or terminating the current opaque region (for example by sending LF to end a string payload), or by sending enough bytes to exhaust a known maximum raw payload length before the reset byte can be recognized. Appendix F 窶・Conformance tests (Recommended) This appendix provides reference test vectors for BCODe syntax parsers. A conforming implementation SHOULD parse these inputs into the same sequence of events (fields, payload bytes, and line latches). The event log format used below matches the reference implementation in bcode parser with lenprefix v7.c. Implementations may buffer differently internally, but the observable results at field termination and payload decoding SHOULD match. F.1 Canonical event log format Note: In this log format, v2 is rendered as a signed integer: it is negative iff the pair separator was , (see Section 10.1). F.2 Test vectors T01 窶・basic two fields Two numeric fields: one PARAM, one CMD. Input Expected events T02 窶・empty fields Empty fields allowed for both PARAM and CMD. Input Expected events T03 窶・pair frac\\ width Dot separator; leading zeros in fractional contribute to frac\\ width. Input Expected events T04 窶・pair comma (negative value2) Comma separator indicates negative value2; digit spelling encodes magnitude. Input Expected events T05 窶・hex single Uppercase hex literal in #...#. Input Expected events T06 窶・hex with whitespace Whitespace inside hex digits is ignored. Input Expected events T07 窶・comments inside numbers Paren comment inside number; semicolon comment ends at LF. Input Expected events T08 窶・string payload semicolon not comment Semicolon is literal inside $...LF string payload. Input Expected events T09 窶・string payload null $ followed immediately by NUL encodes a NULL string payload. Input Expected events T10 窶・hex payload basic %...% hex bytes decode (whitespace ignored). Input Expected events T11 窶・hex payload with comments Comments allowed inside %...% and removed prior to decoding. Input Expected events T12 窶・hex payload interleaved in number A payload may appear between digits; digits concatenate around it. Input Expected events T13 窶・raw payload length from accumulator Length-prefixed raw payload uses digits before & (when value1 not committed). Input Expected events T14 窶・raw payload default length 0 & with no preceding number has length 0 (NULL binary payload). Input Expected events T15 窶・raw length ignores fraction and exponent Length derives from value1 only; fraction/exponent do not affect length. Input Expected events T16 窶・exponent after value1 Scientific suffix on single-number field. Input Expected events T17 窶・exponent negative default '/' with no digits defaults magnitude to 1, i.e., exp10=-1. Input Expected events T18 窶・exponent after value2 Exponent may follow the second number in a pair. Input Expected events T19 窶・illegal separator after exponent triggers resync A separator after exponent is malformed; parser resyncs to next CMD. Input Expected events T20 窶・hex-open raw payload restore If & occurs in open hex (#... not closed), parser restores hex-open mode after payload. Input Expected events T21 窶・whitespace in exponent digits Whitespace between exponent marker and digits is ignored. Input Expected events T22 窶・default exponent magnitude +1 ' ' with no digits defaults to exp10=+1. Input Expected events T23 窶・negative pair frac\\ width Comma separator indicates negative value2; leading zeros contribute to frac width. Input Expected events T24 窶・negative pair hex value2 Hex spelling for value2 with a comma separator produces a negative second value; frac width is the hex digit count (excluding #). Input Expected events T25 窶・negative pair with exponent after value2 Exponent may follow the second number in a pair; comma separator still indicates negative value2. Input Expected events T26 窶・reserved reset command (request) The single byte 0x7F (DEL) is reserved as a parser reset/resynchronization token. It does not produce a normal latch. Input Expected events T27 窶・reset acknowledgement token The reset acknowledgement token is encoded as bytes 0x3E 0x7F (ASCII followed by DEL). Input Expected events Appendix H 窶・Code generation reference This appendix is informative . It is a compact, implementation-oriented summary intended to help generate correct parser and consumer code from the specification. H.1 Reference files produced alongside this spec bcode parser with lenprefix v7.c 窶・canonical streaming syntax parser (reference implementation). bcode streaming conformance tests v7.c 窶・chunking/stress tests for streaming invariance. bcode interp v3.h / bcode interp v3.c 窶・reference interpretation API (transforms, reducer, accessors). bcode-interpretation-v13.html 窶・companion specification for interpretations and API behavior. See also: Section 12.6 of bcode-interpretation-v13.html for canonical field normalization pseudocode (parser adapters). H.2 Token class quick table Token Meaning Parsed where? Notes --- --- --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" 0x20, TAB, CR, LF</code </pre Whitespace Everywhere except 窶徙paque regions窶・TAB/LF/CR are treated the same as spaces. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" ;</code </pre Line comment Normal mode Runs until LF. If LF never occurs, the comment continues indefinitely (streaming model). <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" (...)</code </pre Parentheses comment Normal mode Runs until the next ). Unterminated comment continues indefinitely. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" $</code </pre String payload Normal mode Ends only at LF or NUL. Within a string payload, comment and terminator tokens are not recognized. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" %</code </pre Hex-byte payload Normal mode Payload content is 2-digit hex bytes; whitespace is allowed; comments are allowed inside. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" &amp;</code </pre Raw-binary payload Normal mode Consumes an integer length (defaults to 0) then reads that many raw bytes (opaque region). <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" #...#</code </pre Hex number literal Inside number spelling Hex digits MUST be uppercase. While # is open, PARAM/CMD bytes are not terminators; only closing # ends the literal. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" . or ,</code </pre Pair separator Normal mode (number spelling) Separates value1 and value2. . indicates non-negative value2; , indicates negative value2 (digits encode magnitude). The width of value2 is preserved. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" / /</code </pre Exponent suffix marker Normal mode (after mantissa) is positive exponent, / is negative exponent. If no digits follow, exponent magnitude defaults to 1. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" - &lt; &gt; ? !</code </pre Qualifiers / modifiers Normal mode (field prefix) Any combination of - < ? may appear; ! is orthogonal staleness. H.3 Parameter & command terminators Terminators are organized by ASCII column (low 5 bits). Column 3 is the parameter terminator range and column 4 is the command terminator range: PARAM : 0x40..0x5F 窶・ends a field, continues the line. CMD : 0x60..0x7F 窶・ends the final field and latches the entire line. Parameter identity is defined by the low 5 bits : H.4 Opaque-region precedence rules (common pitfalls) Implementations MUST treat certain regions as opaque (tokens inside do not act as comments/terminators): String payload ($...LF/NUL): opaque; comments and terminators are literal bytes. Raw payload (&...raw bytes...): payload bytes are opaque; comments and terminators are literal bytes. Hex-byte payload (%...%) is not opaque to whitespace/comments (whitespace/comments may appear between hex digits). Hex number literal (#...#) is special: while open, PARAM/CMD bytes MUST NOT terminate the field; only closing # ends the literal. H.5 & length derivation (mandatory rule) Requirement (Normative): The raw payload length for & is derived only from the field窶冱 first numeric value (value1). Fractional (value2) and exponent metadata MUST NOT affect payload length. H.6 Implementation checklist for generated parsers Empty fields are allowed (a terminator may occur with no number content). Whitespace and comments behave like whitespace in normal mode (including inside number spelling), except inside opaque regions. Hex digits in #...# MUST be uppercase (A窶擢 only). Lowercase is invalid and should trigger resynchronization. Allow whitespace between qualifiers and numbers, and between numbers and terminators. Allow payloads to interleave with number spelling; payloads do not alter numeric accumulation (except & consumes the accumulator). Exponent marker // may appear with no digits; default magnitude is 1 (discouraged but allowed). No decimal separator may appear after an exponent marker. Streaming model: there is no EOF; unterminated comments/strings continue indefinitely. Reserved reset: the command byte 0x7F (DEL) discards pending line state and reports a parser reset event; it MUST NOT be delivered as an application-visible command (Section 16.1). H.7 Parse error reporting (optional) The syntax specification defines error behavior by requiring the parser to discard the current line and resynchronize on the next command terminator byte (0x60..0x7F). The canonical reference parser (bcode parser with lenprefix v7.c) exposes this via an optional callback. H.8 Parse error codes (bc\\ parse\\ error\\ t) The reference parser reports a stable, small set of error codes when it enters resynchronization. All parse errors are treated uniformly: the current line is dropped and input is discarded until the next CMD byte is seen in normal mode. The numeric values below are stable for this reference implementation. Code (name) Value Meaning Typical trigger --- --- --- --- BC PE SYNTAX 0 Generic syntax error Invalid character for the current parsing context; malformed field structure BC PE OVERFLOW 1 Numeric overflow Decimal/hex accumulator would exceed 64-bit range; exponent magnitude overflow BC PE HEX PAYLOAD ODD NIBBLE 2 Odd nibble in %...% payload Closing % encountered with exactly one hex digit buffered BC PE HEX PAYLOAD BAD HEX 3 Invalid hex digit in %...% payload Non-hex (or lowercase) where a hex digit is required BC PE PAYLOAD HINT MISMATCH 4 Length hint mismatch LEN$ string body length != LEN, or LEN% decoded bytes != LEN BC PE HEX LITERAL BAD HEX 5 Invalid hex digit inside #...# literal Lowercase a..f or other invalid character inside an open hex literal Tip for robust callback wiring in C: use a zero-initialized struct and assign the field explicitly to avoid any ordering issues: Recommended consumer behavior: Drop any partially buffered payload and parsed-but-not-latched fields for the current line. Do not attempt to interpret payload contents; payload bytes are opaque even when used for diagnostics. Wait for the next CMD byte to resume normal parsing. End of document. --- Appendix G 窶・Streaming Conformance Tests BCODe is defined as a streaming protocol; therefore, implementations MUST produce identical parse results regardless of how the incoming byte stream is chunked (e.g., packet boundaries, serial read sizes, etc.). G.1 Chunking invariance requirement Requirement (Normative): For any finite byte sequence B and any partition of B into contiguous chunks C0..Cn, feeding the parser with B in a single call MUST produce the same sequence of parser events as feeding the parser with C0..Cn across multiple calls, assuming identical initial state. G.2 Reference conformance harness The canonical test harness provided with this specification is: bcode streaming conformance tests v7.c 窶・executes each test vector under multiple chunking strategies. bcode parser with lenprefix v7.c 窶・canonical streaming syntax parser used by the harness. bcode-conformance-vectors-v7.md 窶・human-readable description of the streaming stress vectors. G.3 Included stress vectors The v3 suite includes additional 窶從asty窶・vectors beyond the deterministic v2 set, including: Commands occurring inside unterminated ; comments, (...) comments, and $ strings. Malformed %...% payloads (odd nibble / invalid digit) and the resynchronization behavior. Lowercase hex digits in #...# numbers (forbidden) and recovery. Exponent markers and digits split across chunk boundaries, and payloads interrupting exponent digits. Raw & payload bodies split across chunk boundaries; payload length derivation remains invariant. Note: These tests validate syntax-level behavior and parser state machine correctness; they do not assign semantic meaning to any specific CMD or PARAM values."}, {"slug": "interpretation", "display_title": "Interpretation", "preview_title": "bcode-interpretation-v10 窶・Local Preview", "description": "BCODe Value Interpretation (Draft v10) Status: Draft Interpretation version: v10 Document date: 2026-02-04 Audience: API designers & implementers This companion document defines standard interpretations of BCO?", "corpus_text": "BCODe Value Interpretation (Draft v10) Status: Draft Interpretation version: v10 Document date: 2026-02-04 Audience: API designers & implementers This companion document defines standard interpretations of BCODe fields: how to reason about data quality, special values, and typed accessors. Syntax is defined separately: BCODe Syntax Specification (Draft v10) Scope This document defines standard ways to interpret parsed BCODe syntax. It does not assign meaning to specific parameter characters or command characters (those are application-defined), but it does define: how qualifier combinations communicate value class and data quality how 窶徭tale窶・is represented without breaking other value classes (e.g., infinity) what numeric shapes exist and how typed accessors should behave Parsed field model A syntax parser produces, for each field, a record containing: qual mask for - < ? stale for ! shape: empty / single / pair value1, value2, value2 neg, frac width exp present, exp10 (scientific exponent suffix) Note: For interoperability, applications should treat these as the 窶徨aw parsed truth窶・and avoid inferring type until the command (line terminator) is known. Quality-first telemetry model In telemetry, the first question is often 窶彿s the monitoring system healthy?窶・ followed by 窶彿s the data usable?窶・ and only then 窶忤hat is the numeric value?窶・ Requirement: A typed accessor MUST be able to refuse to provide a hard numeric value when the field indicates: unknown/pending, null/no-data, invalid (NaN), infinity, epsilon-only, or other non-finite/non-hard states. To support both 窶徭trict hard-number窶・users and 窶徭imple systems窶・ a single accessor contract is recommended: Note: Recommended accessor contract: The caller initializes an output variable and passes a pointer to it. If the field is not compatible with the requested type or quality, the accessor returns false and MUST NOT assign the output. Otherwise it returns true and assigns the output. Staleness (orthogonal modifier) A stale value is not automatically invalid: it may be a previously valid value that has not been refreshed or is sourced from a released event/log entry. Requirement: The ! qualifier is an orthogonal freshness modifier that may be combined with any base value class, including infinity and NaN. Staleness does not change the base value class. Implementations may choose to treat stale as 窶徘ropagate like NaN窶・ or as 窶徇onitoring system fault窶・ or as 窶忖se last known value窶・ depending on context (real-time vs event-log). Base qualifier truth table (- < ?) The four base qualifiers (-, <, , ?) define the base value class. The ! stale modifier is handled separately (Section 4). Requirement: Reservation: the combinations < and -< are reserved for signaling NaN (sNaN) and MUST be used only with a single-number field shape (C1). The numeric value1 conveys the signaling-NaN payload/code (application-defined). Table 8.1 窶・Base qualifier combinations and standardized value classes (symbols show which base qualifiers are present) - < ? Base interpretation Notes --- --- --- --- --- --- Normal positive finite value Hard numeric value - Negative finite value Hard numeric value; sign preserved < Value less than stated Upper bound; not a hard value - < Negative value less than stated Upper bound on negative value Value greater than stated Lower bound; not a hard value - Negative value greater than stated Lower bound on negative value ? Unknown or pending calculation No numeric value should be used - ? Excessive noise / unstable signal Quality failure; numeric may be present but SHOULD NOT be treated as hard < ? Positive epsilon (smallest measurable +) Special finite sentinel - < ? Negative epsilon (smallest measurable -) Special finite sentinel ? Positive infinity Beyond measurable range - ? Negative infinity Below measurable range < Signaling NaN (sNaN) Reserved; only valid as C1; value1 encodes sNaN payload - < Signaling NaN (sNaN), sign preserved Reserved; only valid as C1; value1 encodes sNaN payload < ? Null value (no data available) Distinct from empty field; numeric digits MAY be 0 - < ? NaN (invalid computational result) Quiet/invalid; sign preserved; not a hard value Note: The table describes the base class only. If ! is also present, the value is stale but remains in the same base class. For example, ? is 窶徘ositive infinity窶・ ! ? is 窶徭tale positive infinity窶・ Field numeric variants & accessors These are the syntactic numeric variants that can arise in a field, independent of the command/parameter meaning. 6.1 Syntactic numeric variants Variant Condition Available data --- --- --- Absent numeric Shape C0 (empty field) Qualifiers, stale flag only Single integer mantissa Shape C1, no second value value1 Fixed-point mantissa Shape C2 (two integers) value1, value2, value2 neg, frac width Exponent-decorated mantissa exp present==true exp10 plus either single or fixed-point mantissa Integer triplet view (three integers) Shape C1 or C2 (any exponent state) value1, signed value2 (derived from value2 + value2 neg; 0 if absent), exp10 (0 if exponent absent; see exp present) Note: A numeric field may also be treated as a three-integer tuple (窶徼riplet窶・ for application-defined purposes: (value1, signed value2, exp10), where signed value2 = value2 neg ? -value2 : value2. When the second value is absent (C1), treat signed value2 as 0 and frac width as 0. When the exponent suffix is absent, treat exp10 as 0; exp present records whether an exponent was explicitly encoded. 6.2 Typed accessor philosophy Requirement: A typed accessor chooses a target type (e.g., bool, int64, double, fixed-point) and either: (a) succeeds and assigns a well-defined value, or (b) fails and does not assign. 6.3 Suggested accessors (informative) try get i64: succeeds only for finite hard numeric values representable as signed 64-bit integer try get u64: succeeds only for finite hard numeric values representable as unsigned 64-bit integer try get fixed: returns (sign, value1, value2, value2 neg, frac width, exp10) as a structured fixed-point+exponent tuple try get double / try get float: converts fixed-point+exponent to IEEE-754, failing on NaN/Null/Unknown if desired quality class: returns an enum (HardFinite, Bound, Unknown, Noise, Epsilon, Infinity, Null, sNaN, NaN, 窶ｦ) Warning: 窶廝ounds窶・(< or ) are not hard values. Accessors that return hard numerics SHOULD reject bounds unless the API explicitly provides an interval/bound type. Exponent semantics If exp present is true, the mantissa is scaled by a power of ten: 7.1 Mantissa construction If the field is C1, mantissa is based on value1. If the field is C2, the mantissa is a fixed-point value: In syntax v10, the sign of the second component is encoded by the pair separator: . implies value2 neg=false, , implies value2 neg=true. Define signed value2 = value2 neg ? -value2 : value2. Overall sign handling and special value classes (NaN, Infinity, etc.) are controlled by qualifiers and are handled by the accessor logic; the sign of value2 (if present) is controlled by the pair separator in syntax v10. 7.2 Integer accessors and exponent Note: Implementations may choose one of two strategies: (a) reject any exponent for integer accessors (simpler), or (b) allow exponent where the result is an integer and is representable (more flexible). BCODe does not mandate either choice. Recommendations for API consumers Prefer checking a quality classifier (or accessor return values) before using numeric results. Treat ! as context-dependent: stale is not invalid, but may require propagation or alarms. Keep command-to-parameter meaning mapping separate from syntax parsing. Use %...% payloads when you want to embed comments alongside binary. Transform stage & cookbook BCODe interpretation MAY include one or more transforms that operate on an already-latched line record (fields + qualifiers), before reducers or typed accessors are applied. Transforms operate on an in-memory representation; they do not change the on-wire syntax rules and they are not tied to any particular device lifecycle process. 9.1 Transform invariants Requirement (Normative): A transform MUST maintain internal consistency of each field: C0 (empty): MUST set value1=value2=0, value2 neg=0, and frac width=0 (and SHOULD clear exponent metadata). C1 (single): MUST set value2=0, value2 neg=0, and frac width=0. C2 (pair): MUST ensure frac width = 1 and define value2 (may be 0) and value2 neg (may be 0). 9.2 Bitmask selection Since there are exactly 32 parameter identities, transforms SHOULD select which fields to act on using a uint32 t mask where bit i corresponds to parameter index i (low 5 bits). 9.3 Transform cookbook The following cookbook lists common generic transforms. These are illustrative building blocks and can be used in any multi-stage processing pipeline. Transform pattern Operation Typical effect Notes --- --- --- --- Drop selected fields Clear present bit; zero field record Field disappears for downstream layers Good for filtering or masking at different software layers. Force stale Set stale=1 Downstream sees OK STALE for successful accessors Stale is orthogonal; does not change ValueKind. Clear stale Set stale=0 Downstream treats values as fresh Useful when a layer externalizes freshness tracking elsewhere. Rewrite qualifier class Map one qual mask to another Converts ValueKind buckets without changing numeric payload Example: map VK NULL to VK UNKNOWN while preserving diagnostic codes (D1/D2/D3). Normalize empty to explicit NULL If shape=C0, set qual mask to the NULL combination Turns 窶徘resent but empty窶・into 窶徘resent and explicitly NULL窶・Only a convention; wire format still allows empty fields. Enforce sNaN shape If qual mask is sNaN and shape!=C1, coerce to C1 Makes standardized get snan() usable Recommended but not required. Clamp exponent magnitude Limit exp10 to a safe range Avoids extreme scaling during float conversion Protects consumers from accidental or malicious huge exponents. Inject default diagnostics If diagnostic ValueKind and C0, set C1 and value1=0 Guarantees a code slot exists Pairs well with bcode field get diag(), which already supports D0. 9.4 Reference C API A reference transform + reducer API is provided in bcode interp v3.h / bcode interp v3.c. It defines field-local transforms selected by a 32-bit mask and an optional whole-line transform hook. Line reduction (bitmask reducer) A line reducer summarizes a latched line by folding per-field status into bitmasks. This provides a policy-light mechanism for software layers to decide how to handle data quality without assigning semantic meaning to any specific parameter or command. 10.1 Inputs check mask: which parameter indices to evaluate. require mask: subset of check mask that must be 窶徂ard-number OK窶・(optional). 10.2 Outputs The reducer SHOULD produce at least the following masks (intersection with check mask implied): missing mask 窶・checked but absent empty mask 窶・present but C0 stale mask 窶・present and stale exact mask, bound mask diag mask 窶・union of diagnostic buckets (unknown/noise/epsilon/null/qnan/snan/inf) hard ok mask 窶・present, non-empty, and exact hard ok all required 窶・derived boolean indicating require mask is satisfied 10.3 Reference pseudocode The reducer itself does not decide whether UNKNOWN is 窶彙ad窶・or 窶彗cceptable窶・ layers can apply their own policy to the output masks. Policy examples using masks This section is informative . It illustrates how different software layers can use the same reducer output masks (missing mask, diag mask, stale mask, etc.) while applying different local policy. No specific device lifecycle process is assumed. 11.1 Display / UI layer (best-effort) Goal: show the operator as much as possible, including bounds and diagnostic codes. check mask: the set of fields you want to render (often 窶彗ll present窶・. require mask: 0 (UI does not require hard numbers). Suggested rules: If a field is in exact mask, show the value (and a stale badge if in stale mask). If a field is in bound mask, show 窶・窶・or 窶・窶・plus the stated bound value. If a field is in diag mask, show the qualifier state and extract codes using bcode field get diag(). 11.2 Control loop layer (strict hard-number gating) Goal: use only hard numeric data for actuation or control updates. check mask: parameters used by the control law. require mask: usually equal to check mask. Suggested rules: If hard ok all required is false, skip the update (or enter a hold/fallback mode). If any required bit is set in stale mask, either reject the update or apply a dedicated stale policy. If any required bit is set in diag mask, do not attempt typed numeric accessors for those fields. 11.3 Alarm / health monitoring layer (mask-based triage) Goal: detect and report exceptional states quickly, while still recording diagnostic payload codes. check mask: subset of parameters representing health indicators and critical telemetry. require mask: optional; for alarms it is often 0 (alarms look at qualifiers first). Example triage policy (informative): If snan mask intersects the check set, raise a high-severity fault (extract sNaN code). If qnan mask intersects the check set, raise a computation fault. If null mask intersects the check set, raise a missing-data alert (severity is local policy). If noise mask intersects the check set, raise a degraded-signal alert. Use bcode field get diag() to extract any D1/D2/D3 codes for logging/diagnostics. 11.4 Logging layer (preserve + annotate) Goal: preserve the original line (raw bytes and/or parsed fields) and optionally add machine-readable annotations. A common strategy is: Store the raw line bytes (or event stream boundaries) separately. Store the parsed latched line record (presence + field structs). Optionally apply transforms to normalize representation for indexing/search (without modifying the stored raw record). Store reducer masks alongside the record to support queries (e.g., 窶徭how lines where any checked field was NULL窶・. 11.5 Transform usage in policy pipelines Transforms can be used as generic pre-processing steps before the reducer. Examples: Clear stale on selected parameters (if freshness is tracked externally). Rewrite qualifier buckets to a local convention (e.g., treating a specific bucket as UNKNOWN for downstream compatibility). Clamp exponent magnitude before float conversion. C API quick reference This section is informative . It provides a compact reference intended to support correct auto-generation of consumer code. The normative behavior remains the tables and requirements in this document. 12.1 Recommended processing pipeline Syntax parsing rules are defined in the companion document bcode-syntax-with-tests-v10.html. 12.2 Core record types (from bcode interp v3.h) 12.3 Return-code conventions Return Meaning Out params written? --- --- --- BC OK success (fresh) yes BC OK STALE success (stale) yes BC ERR ABSENT parameter not present no BC ERR EMPTY present but empty (C0) no BC ERR SHAPE wrong syntactic form for accessor no BC ERR QUALITY wrong qualifier/ValueKind for accessor no BC ERR OVERFLOW conversion overflow/underflow no 12.4 Key functions (grouped) Classification bcode classify kind(qual mask) bcode field get kind(present, field, &kind, &stale) Diagnostics bcode field get diag(present, field, &diag) 窶・returns D0/D1/D2/D3-style codes (always succeeds for present fields). bcode field get snan(present, field, &code, &sign) 窶・standardized sNaN code (C1 only). Bounds bcode field get bound scalar parts(present, field, &rel, &parts) Tuples (suffix integer) bcode field get triplet u(present, field, &a, &b, &b width, &c) Strict numeric measurements (exact-only) bcode field get scalar parts exact(present, field, &parts) bcode field get i64(present, field, &out) bcode field get u64(present, field, &out) bcode field get bool(present, field, &out) bcode field get double(present, field, &out) Fixed-point helpers (exact-only) bcode field get coeff scale10 exact(present, field, &sign, &coeff, &scale10) bcode field get i64 scale10(present, field, out scale10, &out) bcode field get u64 scale10(present, field, out scale10, &out) Transforms bcode apply field transform(&line, selection mask, fn, user) bcode apply line transform(&line, fn, user) Reducer bcode reduce line(&line, check mask, require mask, &out) 12.5 Parameter bit mapping Parameter identity is defined by the low 5 bits. For a PARAM terminator byte t (0x40..0x5F): 12.6 Canonical field normalization (for parser adapters) Many streaming parsers represent numeric accumulation using internal state (decimal vs hex mode, digit counters, etc.). This specification defines a compact bcode field t record for consumers. The adapter between a parser and bcode field t SHOULD apply a small normalization pass so that downstream code never sees inconsistent field states. 12.6.1 Normalize a single field record Goal: enforce the invariants of C0/C1/C2 and exponent metadata. 12.6.2 Canonical line assembly from parser events A common parser API emits events like FIELD(term, is cmd, field record) and LATCH(cmd). The following adapter pattern is recommended. It is chunking-invariant and requires no inter-parameter dependencies. 12.7 Payload latching adapter (reference) Payloads ($ string, % hex, & raw) are line-scoped and are latched at the same time as fields: they belong to the buffered line record that becomes visible to the application when the command character is read. Payload contents are opaque to the syntax parser; interpretation is up to the application. In bcode-syntax-with-tests-v10.html, $ and % MAY be preceded by an optional integer length hint . The canonical parser surfaces these hints at payload-begin time so receivers can size buffers and optionally validate transmission integrity. A length-hint mismatch is a syntax error and the line MUST be treated as invalid (no latch). Design note: the reducer and numeric accessors in this interpretation API operate solely on fields + qualifiers. If your application needs payloads, latch them alongside the line as shown above, and handle them in your own layer. 12.6.3 Canonical payload capture (opaque, line-associated) Payloads are associated with the line , but their contents are opaque to the syntax parser. The consumer (API user) decides how to interpret payload bytes. The following adapter pattern buffers at most one payload per line (policy: last payload wins ). Other policies (first wins, error on multiple) are valid local choices. With the canonical parser rules, a payload窶冱 bytes are complete before the command terminator that latches the line. If a payload is unterminated (e.g., missing LF for a string), the line never latches. 12.6.4 Handling syntax errors (resync) On any parse error, the canonical parser enters resynchronization mode and discards bytes until the next CMD. When using a buffered line/payload adapter, this means discarding the current line buffer. The parse error code is a bc parse error t value (stable in the reference parser). Code Value Notes --- --- --- BC PE SYNTAX 0 Generic malformed input BC PE OVERFLOW 1 Numeric accumulator overflow BC PE HEX PAYLOAD ODD NIBBLE 2 %...% ended mid-byte BC PE HEX PAYLOAD BAD HEX 3 Bad hex digit in %...% (incl lowercase) BC PE PAYLOAD HINT MISMATCH 4 Hinted length mismatch (string or hex) BC PE HEX LITERAL BAD HEX 5 Bad hex digit in #...# (lowercase) End of document."}, {"slug": "meta-v9", "display_title": "BCODe.meta (v9)", "preview_title": "BCODe_meta_Convention.updated7 (1) 窶・Local Preview", "description": "BCODe.meta 窶・Convention for Command/Response, Batching, Sequencing, Parser Reset Handling (Draft v7) Document date: 2026-02-13 Document version: 7 Status: Draft convention (built on top of BCODe syntax) BCODe.?", "corpus_text": "BCODe.meta 窶・Convention for Command/Response, Batching, Sequencing, Parser Reset Handling (Draft v7) Document date: 2026-02-13 Document version: 7 Status: Draft convention (built on top of BCODe syntax) BCODe.meta is a convention for stream-friendly command/response messaging: affirmative (^) and negative (\\) responses, unsolicited statements (^\\), multiline batching ([), sequence numbers (]), header-prefix delivery (-N[), asynchronous followup sessions encoded in ] fractional parts, and required behavior when the BCODe parser reports a parser-level reset event. Policy knobs (implementation configuration) BCODe.meta is normative about on窶層ire meaning , but allows implementations to choose certain receiver policies . This document standardizes knob names so behavior is predictable across implementations. 1.1 session idle timeout (ﾎ煩・ Type: duration (implementation-defined units) Default: implementation-defined (MAY be disabled) If enabled, an active session ﾎ・MAY be ended locally after ﾎ煩・of inactivity (see ﾂｧ2.4.6). 1.2 nonexistent session policy Controls what happens when an unsolicited statement references an inactive session (event E NON EXISTENT SESSION). Values: DROP (default): the deliverable unit is not delivered to the application . PASS THROUGH: the unit is delivered as sessionless unsolicited (still emits E NON EXISTENT SESSION). 1.3 drop sink (diagnostic tap) Type: callback/hook (or 窶彭isabled窶・ When a deliverable unit is dropped by policy (e.g., nonexistent session policy=DROP), the implementation MAY still export the decoded unit and/or raw bytes to drop sink for logging, tracing, quarantine storage, or debugging. Normative constraint: dropping MUST prevent the unit from reaching normal application delivery paths, but MUST NOT prevent diagnostic capture via drop sink. 1.4 allow ephemeral interjection Type: boolean Default: enabled Controls whether the receiver accepts ephemeral interjection requests (see ﾂｧ4.3). When disabled: Ephemeral interjection requests (?S] 窶ｦ ﾎｺ) MUST be refused as described in ﾂｧ4.3.6. Sessionless unsolicited statements marked ephemeral (?] ^\\ 窶ｦ ﾎｺ) are handled by ephemeral sessionless policy (ﾂｧ1.5). Endpoints configured for or detecting persistent multi-writer operation on a channel SHOULD disable this knob. 1.5 ephemeral sessionless policy Controls what happens when a sessionless unsolicited statement is received that is marked ephemeral (i.e., carries ? on its ] field, including ?]). Values: DROP (default): the unit is not delivered to the application (it MAY still be exported to drop sink). PASS THROUGH: the unit is delivered as a sessionless unsolicited statement. This knob is primarily relevant when allow ephemeral interjection is disabled (ﾂｧ1.4). 1.6 seq mismatch policy Controls what happens when E SEQ MISMATCH is triggered (ﾂｧ6.1). Values: LOG ONLY (default): deliver the unit and emit the event. DROP: do not deliver the unit to normal application callbacks/handlers, but the unit is still observed for sequence tracking (ﾂｧ6.1) and MAY be exported to drop sink (ﾂｧ1.3). BCODe.meta does not change BCODe syntax; it assigns conventional meaning to specific parameters and specifies how meta-convention state reacts to parser-level reset events. --- Reserved meta parameters Token Meaning (convention) --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" ^</code </pre affirmative response tag (optional timestamp value) <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" \\</code </pre negative response tag (optional error/reason code value) <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" ^\\</code </pre unsolicited statement tag (sent without a request) <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" [</code </pre multiline packet/batch tag <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" ]</code </pre sequence counter <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" -N[</code </pre header-prefix lines that attach metadata to the next deliverable unit Note on staleness: BCODe's ! stale qualifier (a field-level modifier, not a parameter) is used by this convention only when attached to the ] field with a fractional session discriminator (a sequence number pair). It is reserved for two purposes: 1) End-of-session marker on the final in-session followup: !ﾎ.ﾎ拆 ^\\ 窶ｦ ﾎｺ (see ﾂｧ2.4.4). 2) Ephemeral busy refusal indicator : !0.T] \\ 窶ｦ ﾎｺ (see ﾂｧ4.3.6). The ! indicates the busy report may be stale by the time it is received. Using ! on an integer-only ] value (!ﾎ]) is an invalid session termination (see E INVALID SESSION TERMINATION in ﾂｧ6). --- Command/response and unsolicited rules 2.1 Commands A command is a line sent by a requester. Commands MUST NOT include ^, \\, or ^\\. If a command carries a sequence counter ], its ] value MUST be an integer (no fractional part). (The ] fractional part is reserved for responder-side session labeling; see ﾂｧ2.4.) If a command is received with a fractional ] value (i.e., ﾎ.ﾎ拆), the BCODe.meta layer MUST emit E INVALID SESSION DECL (see ﾂｧ6) and SHOULD ignore the fractional component for session purposes. 2.2 Direct response A line transmitted as the direct response to a command is a response and MUST be tagged: ^ for affirmative acknowledgement \\ for negative acknowledgement (MAY include an error/reason code) A direct response MAY also start an asynchronous followup session (ﾂｧ2.4). If a direct response carries a fractional ] value, it MUST be either: 1) an affirmative response (^) whose fractional component matches the integer sequence number of the command it is directly responding to (see ﾂｧ2.4.2), or 2) the reserved ephemeral busy refusal form !0.T] \\ 窶ｦ ﾎｺ (see ﾂｧ4.3.6). Any other use of a fractional ] value in a direct response MUST emit E INVALID SESSION DECL (see ﾂｧ6). 2.3 Unsolicited statements (two kinds) A line transmitted without a preceding request as its direct response MUST be tagged as unsolicited: It MUST contain both ^ and \\ (written as ^\\ in examples). Unsolicited statements are divided into: 1) Sessionless unsolicited statements Unsolicited statements that are not asynchronous followups to a command session. 2) In-session unsolicited statements (asynchronous followups) Unsolicited statements that belong to a session started by a command窶冱 affirmative direct response (ﾂｧ2.4). The distinction is determined by the session rules in ﾂｧ2.4 (and the receiver窶冱 active-session state). If an unsolicited statement carries a fractional ] value (ﾎ.ﾎ拆), the receiver MUST treat it as an in-session followup only if session ﾎ・is currently active; otherwise it MUST emit E NON EXISTENT SESSION(ﾎ・ (see ﾂｧ6) and, by default, MUST drop the line (do not deliver it to application/user logic). Receivers MUST apply nonexistent session policy (ﾂｧ1.2). The default is DROP, which prevents delivery to application/user logic but still allows diagnostic capture via drop sink (ﾂｧ1.3). 2.4 Asynchronous followup sessions encoded in ] This section defines how a responder can emit additional unsolicited followup statements that are logically tied to a previously acknowledged command. 2.4.1 Abstract notation (Greek letters) Let: ﾎ・be the integer sequence number in the requester窶冱 command ﾎ拆 ... ﾎｺ ﾎ be the responder窶冱 primary sequence number (integer part of its outbound ]) ﾎｺ be a command character (lowercase ASCII; application-defined) A response uses a sequence number pair by writing a fractional part: ﾎ.ﾎ拆 Here ﾎ is the primary sequence number, and the fractional component ﾎ・is the session discriminator . 2.4.2 Session start (normative) A session MAY start only when the direct response to a command is affirmative (^). A responder indicates that an affirmative direct response starts a session by: including a ] field whose fractional component equals the command窶冱 integer ] value. Concretely: Command: ﾎ拆 ... ﾎｺ (no fractional part permitted on the command) Direct affirmative response that starts session ﾎ・ ﾎ.ﾎ拆 ^ ... ﾎｺ On reception of such a direct affirmative response, the BCODe.meta layer MUST emit Start of session event E SESSION START(ﾎ・ and record session ﾎ・as active . If the direct response is negative (\\), or the response does not carry ] with fractional component ﾎ・ then no session starts . 2.4.3 In-session followups (normative) While session ﾎ・is active, any subsequent unsolicited statement that: is tagged ^\\, and carries a ] value whose fractional component equals ﾎ・is an in-session unsolicited followup for session ﾎ・ In-session followups: MUST maintain the same fractional component ﾎ・in their ] field, and SHOULD use a primary sequence number ﾎ that increases monotonically. 2.4.4 End of session (normative) The final in-session unsolicited followup for session ﾎ・MUST: set the ! stale flag on its ] field, and maintain the same fractional component ﾎ・ Concretely: !ﾎ.ﾎ拆 ^\\ ... ﾎｺ On reception, the BCODe.meta layer MUST emit End of session event E SESSION END(ﾎ・ and mark session ﾎ・inactive. After E SESSION END(ﾎ・, any later ^\\ line labeled with fractional ﾎ・refers to an inactive session and MUST emit E NON EXISTENT SESSION(ﾎ・. By default, such lines MUST be dropped (not delivered) and MUST NOT be treated as in-session followups. Implementations MAY support a non-default 窶徘ass-through窶・policy that delivers the line as a sessionless unsolicited statement. 2.4.5 Session error conditions (normative) BCODe.meta defines the following session-related protocol errors: Invalid session declaration : a fractional ] value (ﾎ.ﾎ拆) appears on a line that is neither: the affirmative direct response that starts session ﾎ・(ﾂｧ2.4.2), nor an unsolicited statement (^\\) (ﾂｧ2.4.3), nor the reserved ephemeral busy refusal !0.T] \\ 窶ｦ ﾎｺ (ﾂｧ4.3.6). On detection, the BCODe.meta layer MUST emit E INVALID SESSION DECL. Nonexistent session : an unsolicited statement (^\\) carries a fractional ] value (ﾎ.ﾎ拆) but session ﾎ・is not active. On detection, the BCODe.meta layer MUST emit E NON EXISTENT SESSION(ﾎ・ and, by default, MUST drop the line (do not deliver it). Implementations MAY expose a non-default 窶徘ass-through窶・policy that delivers the line as sessionless unsolicited. Invalid session termination : a ] field is marked stale (!) but has no fractional component (i.e., !ﾎ]). On detection, the BCODe.meta layer MUST emit E INVALID SESSION TERMINATION. These events SHOULD notify/log, but MUST NOT automatically reset parser or meta state. E NON EXISTENT SESSION is additionally a delivery condition: by default the associated line is dropped (not delivered), per ﾂｧ6.7. 2.4.6 Receiver-side session timeout (optional) BCODe.meta defines an explicit, on窶層ire end-of-session marker (!ﾎ.ﾎ拆 on the final followup). However, receivers MAY also end sessions locally to bound resource usage. Let ﾎ煩・be a receiver-configured idle timeout . A receiver MAY mark an active session ﾎ・inactive if no in-session activity for ﾎ・is observed for at least ﾎ煩・ In-session activity includes the session-starting direct response ﾎ.ﾎ拆 ^ ... ﾎｺ and any subsequent in-session followups ﾎ.ﾎ拆 ^\\ ... ﾎｺ. On timeout, the receiver SHOULD emit E SESSION END(ﾎ・ cause=timeout) (or E SESSION END(ﾎ・ if causes are not supported) and mark the session inactive. Once timed out, any later followup labeled with fractional ﾎ・MUST be treated as a reference to an inactive session and MUST raise E NON EXISTENT SESSION(ﾎ・; by default it will be dropped. Because this is a local policy, timeouts have no on-wire representation . Senders that require reliable delivery of followups SHOULD send the explicit stale termination marker (!ﾎ.ﾎ拆). --- Multiline batching with [ 3.0 Header-prefix lines using negative [ values The [ parameter MAY also appear with a negative integer value, written as -N[ where N 竕･ 1. In this form, the line is a header-prefix line that modifies delivery of the following unit. Delivery rule: a contiguous run of one or more header-prefix lines immediately preceding a deliverable unit attaches to that unit. The unit is either: the next single (non-header) line, or the next multiline packet/batch formed with [ (fixed-bound or open-ended), treated atomically. Ordering rule (stack form): if multiple header-prefix lines are present, their [ values MUST be: -K[, -(K-1)[, 窶ｦ, -2[, -1[ with -1[ adjacent to the content unit. This yields a stack that higher layers may interpret hop-by-hop (e.g., a routing layer may peel one header per hop). Meta-layer behavior: Header-prefix lines MUST NOT be delivered to the application as independent statements. Instead, the implementation SHOULD deliver the following unit together with the collected header-prefix lines (e.g., as an array of header lines or as an opaque 窶徂eaders窶・blob). BCODe.meta does not assign semantics to the header content beyond the attachment and ordering rules above. 3.1 Purpose: atomic delivery The [ parameter is reserved for batching multiple lines into a single atomic group . Requirement: a receiver SHOULD NOT expose packet lines to the application as independent statements. Instead, it SHOULD buffer until the packet completes, then deliver the set as one unit (atomically). This is the core reason [ exists: batching changes delivery , not field semantics. 3.2 Fixed-bound packets (known length) In the fixed-bound form, each line carries a [ field whose numeric value is i.t: i = 1-based line index within the packet t = total line count Example (3-line packet): 3.3 Open-ended packets (unknown length) Open-ended packets are permitted without an end bound when: 1) the [ field carries the qualifier on each non-final line, 2) the numeric value of the [ field monotonically increases , and 3) the final line closes the packet with a fixed-bound i.t[ terminator exactly as if the bounds had been known initially. Example (unknown length until end): Notes: The receiver buffers i[ lines until it receives the closing i.t[ line. Monotonicity SHOULD be interpreted as contiguous increment by 1 (otherwise it is likely an error). 3.4 Header/sequence counter coupling (normative) If a header-prefix line is immediately followed by a line that carries a sequence counter ], the header-prefix line MUST carry the same ] value. This rule applies recursively through a header run: For a header stack -K[ 窶ｦ -1[ preceding a unit, each header line MUST copy the ] value of the line immediately following it (e.g., -2[ copies from -1[, and -1[ copies from the first content line of the delivered unit). If the immediately following line has no ], the header-prefix line MUST NOT invent a ] value (i.e., omit ]). Rationale: this preserves the sequence identity of the delivered unit while allowing intermediate layers to strip headers without losing sequence correlation. --- Sequence counters with ] The ] parameter is reserved for sequence counters. 4.0 Shapes and reserved modifiers BCODe.meta interprets ] values as follows: The primary sequence number is the integer part of the numeric value in the ] field. The fractional component (if present) is reserved for the session discriminator described in ﾂｧ2.4. Because ] is a reserved meta parameter, BCODe.meta also assigns special meaning to certain qualifiers on ]: ! on ] is reserved (see the staleness note in ﾂｧ1): it MUST only appear when ] has a fractional component. ? on ] is reserved for the optional ephemeral interjection convention (ﾂｧ4.3). < on ] is reserved for the rollover marker (ﾂｧ4.1). Other qualifier meanings (such as 窶從umeric bounds窶・ from generic value-interpretation rules do not apply to ]. 4.1 Rollover marker (expected wrap to 0) Senders that use a bounded sequence space (e.g., 16-bit counters) MAY indicate an expected rollover to 0 by marking the ] field with the < qualifier. Form: <ﾎ] or <ﾎ.ﾎ拆 Semantics: The marked unit carries primary sequence ﾎ as normal. The next expected primary sequence number from that peer is 0 (rather than ﾎ+1). If a fractional session discriminator .ﾎ・is present, it is unchanged; the rollover marker applies to the primary sequence only. Example (16-bit wrap): 4.2 Recommendations for rollover design (informative) BCODe.meta does not mandate a sequence modulus. However, rollover design impacts interoperability, especially when strict mismatch policies are enabled. Unsolicited / telemetry channels (^\\): For channels intended to emit long-running unsolicited data, SEQ MAX SHOULD be the maximum representable integer value for the deployed implementation (窶廬NTMAX/UINTMAX窶・. Rollover then becomes extremely rare in practice. Synchronous / control channels (command/response): For channels intended for synchronous communication or controls, SEQ MAX MAY be much smaller. A useful heuristic is to choose a modulus on the order of: SEQ MOD 竕・10 ﾃ・TX MAX UNITS where TX MAX UNITS is the maximum number of deliverable units (direct response + any expected followups) in the longest expected transaction. A smaller rollover interval increases the chance of 窶從atural resync窶・if strict mismatch policies are configured poorly. Session discriminator safety: If asynchronous followup sessions (ﾂｧ2.4) are used, the requester窶冱 command sequence ﾎ・is reused as the session discriminator in ﾎ.ﾎ拆. Channels using small moduli SHOULD ensure that a discriminator ﾎ・will not be reused (due to rollover) while a prior session ﾎ・could still be active (via explicit termination !ﾎ.ﾎ拆 or local timeout). 4.3 Ephemeral interjection stream (?-qualified ]) (optional) This subsection defines an optional convention that allows an ephemeral non-default writer to interject a request/response exchange without consuming or perturbing the receiver窶冱 default-writer outbound sequence stream. This convention is activated only when a delivered unit carries a ] field with the ? qualifier. Units without ? follow the rules above unchanged. 4.3.1 Meaning of ? on ] When ] is qualified with ?, its numeric content is correlation-only and MUST NOT: participate in, or advance, the receiver窶冱 default-writer outbound sequence counter, nor modify the receiver窶冱 recorded peer last primary sequence used for E SEQ MISMATCH (ﾂｧ6.1). Implementations MAY maintain separate bookkeeping for ephemeral streams if desired. 4.3.2 Sessionless unsolicited from an ephemeral writer A sessionless unsolicited message from an ephemeral writer MAY carry ?] (no numeric value). Example: If allow ephemeral interjection is disabled, delivery is controlled by ephemeral sessionless policy (ﾂｧ1.5). 4.3.3 Ephemeral request and direct response (no session) An ephemeral writer sending a request MUST include an integer sequence number S qualified with ?: A single direct response from the receiver MUST respond using sequence number (S + 1) also qualified with ?: A negative direct response is analogous: This ensures the receiver窶冱 default-writer outbound sequence counter does not advance as a result of the interjection. 4.3.4 Ephemeral request and direct response that starts a session If the receiver窶冱 direct affirmative response starts an asynchronous followup session (see ﾂｧ2.4), it MUST do so using the existing session rule, but maintaining the ? qualifier: 4.3.5 Routing responsibility BCODe.meta does not define how the response reaches the ephemeral writer. Implementations MUST surface enough information (via transport context and/or higher-layer header conventions) for the application to route the receiver窶冱 response back to the appropriate ephemeral writer. 4.3.6 Policy disable, concurrency rule, and refusal forms Policy disable: When allow ephemeral interjection is disabled, an incoming ephemeral interjection request (?S] 窶ｦ ﾎｺ) MUST be refused with a negative direct response (\\) that preserves the command field ﾎｺ. The response SHOULD use ?(S+1)] for correlation. Concurrency (recommended): To keep receiver behavior simple, receivers SHOULD permit at most one pending ephemeral interjection/session at a time. If a new ephemeral request arrives while an earlier ephemeral request/session with discriminator T is pending, the receiver MUST refuse immediately using: !0.T] \\ 窶ｦ ﾎｺ The ! indicates the busy report may be stale by the time it is received. The !0.T] form is reserved for this refusal and MUST NOT be interpreted as participating in any sequence stream (and MUST NOT affect E SEQ MISMATCH bookkeeping). Example (pending T=10): --- Parser reset event BCODe.meta does not define the on窶層ire reset/resynchronization token, receiver acknowledgements, or any transmitter synchronization strategy. Those are specified at the BCODe syntax / parser level. This document specifies only how the BCODe.meta convention state MUST react when the underlying parser reports a reset-related event. 5.1 Required meta-layer reaction When the parser reports a reset event (including a reset acknowledgement, if the parser distinguishes them), a BCODe.meta endpoint MUST: Discard any partially buffered packet/batch state started with [ (both fixed-bound and open-ended forms). Discard any partially collected header-prefix state (-N[ lines) not yet attached to a delivered unit. Reset any sequence counters it transmits using ] back to 0 . Clear any internal bookkeeping used to decide whether the next outbound line is a direct response (^ / \\) vs an unsolicited statement (^\\). Clear any active-session tracking state (both local and peer-visible) created under ﾂｧ2.4. 5.2 Optional exposure to the application Implementations MAY surface the parser窶冱 reset classification (e.g., 窶徨eset request窶・vs 窶徨eset acknowledgement窶・ to the application layer for diagnostics, but BCODe.meta assigns no additional meaning beyond the required state reset above. --- Meta events emitted during analysis This section defines standard events a BCODe.meta implementation MAY/SHOULD emit while analyzing the stream. Events are emitted as a result of analyzing latched BCODe lines and/or completing atomic delivery units (headers + content, packets). 6.1 E SEQ MISMATCH 窶・expected sequence number mismatch Trigger: A deliverable unit (a single line, or a completed packet, after header-prefix attachment rules) is observed carrying a ] field with primary sequence ﾎ that: is not qualified with ?, and is not the reserved ephemeral-busy refusal form !0.T] \\ 窶ｦ ﾎｺ (ﾂｧ4.3.6), and the implementation previously recorded the peer窶冱 last primary sequence as ﾎ・ and ﾎ 竕 expected next, where: expected next = 0 if the previously observed (tracked) peer ] carried the rollover marker < (ﾂｧ4.1), otherwise expected next = ﾎ・+ 1. Effect: Emit E SEQ MISMATCH(expected=expected next, observed=ﾎ). Update the recorded peer last primary sequence to ﾎ. If seq mismatch policy=DROP, the unit MUST NOT be delivered to normal application callbacks/handlers, but it MAY still be exported to drop sink (ﾂｧ1.3). This is a cautionary event: it SHOULD notify and log, but MUST NOT automatically reset or otherwise modify meta state (beyond updating the peer last primary sequence number). Notes: If no prior tracked peer sequence number has been recorded, the first observed tracked ] establishes it and MUST NOT trigger E SEQ MISMATCH. Header-prefix lines do not form deliverable units by themselves and SHOULD NOT be sequence-checked independently. Units that are later dropped due to meta-level validation (e.g., E NON EXISTENT SESSION) are still 窶徙bserved窶・for sequence tracking purposes (and update ﾎ・ unless excluded by the rules above. 6.2 E SESSION START 窶・start of session detected Trigger: While processing a direct response to a command with integer sequence ﾎ拆, the response is affirmative (^) and carries a ] field whose fractional component equals ﾎ・(i.e., ﾎ.ﾎ拆). Effect: Emit E SESSION START(ﾎ・. Record session ﾎ・as active. Session start is an observation . Application/user logic decides what 窶彙eing in a session窶・means. 6.3 E SESSION END 窶・end of session detected Trigger: On窶層ire termination: While session ﾎ・is active, an in-session unsolicited followup is received whose ] field is marked stale (!ﾎ.ﾎ拆). Optional local termination: The receiver expires session ﾎ・due to a local policy such as an idle timeout ﾎ煩・(ﾂｧ2.4.6). Effect: Emit E SESSION END(ﾎ・ cause=stale) for on窶層ire termination, or E SESSION END(ﾎ・ cause=timeout) for local termination (implementations MAY omit the cause argument if they do not support it). Mark session ﾎ・inactive. 6.4 E HEADER START 窶・start of header-prefix run detected Trigger: A header-prefix line (a line containing a negative -N[ field with N 竕･ 1) is received while not already collecting a header-prefix run. Effect: Emit E HEADER START. 6.5 E HEADER TO CONTENT 窶・transition from header to content Trigger: A header-prefix line containing -1[ is received. Effect: Emit E HEADER TO CONTENT, indicating that the next delivered unit line (or the next packet start) is the content to which the accumulated header-prefix run will attach. 6.6 E INVALID SESSION DECL 窶・invalid session declaration Trigger: A latched line carries a fractional sequence number pair ﾎ.ﾎ拆, but the line is neither: an unsolicited statement (^\\), nor the affirmative direct response that starts session ﾎ・for a command ﾎ拆 ... ﾎｺ (see ﾂｧ2.4.2), nor the reserved ephemeral busy refusal !0.T] \\ 窶ｦ ﾎｺ (see ﾂｧ4.3.6). This includes (non-exhaustive), except for the reserved ephemeral-busy refusal !0.T] \\ 窶ｦ ﾎｺ (ﾂｧ4.3.6): a command line that carries ﾎ.ﾎ拆, a negative direct response (\\) that carries ﾎ.ﾎ拆, an affirmative direct response (^) whose fractional component does not match the command窶冱 integer sequence. Effect: Emit E INVALID SESSION DECL(observed primary=ﾎ, observed session=ﾎ・. Do not start or end any session as a result of this line. E INVALID SESSION DECL is diagnostic . Implementations SHOULD notify/log, but MUST NOT automatically reset parser or meta state. 6.7 E NON EXISTENT SESSION 窶・in-session reference to inactive session Trigger: An unsolicited statement (^\\) carries a fractional ] value ﾎ.ﾎ拆, but session ﾎ・is not currently active (never started, already ended, expired by timeout, or otherwise unknown to the receiver). Effect: Emit E NON EXISTENT SESSION(ﾎ・. Apply nonexistent session policy (ﾂｧ1.2): DROP (default): do not deliver the unit to normal application callbacks / handlers. The unit MAY still be exported to drop sink (ﾂｧ1.3). PASS THROUGH: deliver the unit as a sessionless unsolicited statement (it still emits E NON EXISTENT SESSION and MUST NOT be treated as in-session). Sequence tracking MUST still observe the unit窶冱 primary sequence number ﾎ (if present) and update the recorded peer last primary sequence accordingly (so that subsequent sequence expectations track the peer窶冱 stream). E NON EXISTENT SESSION is diagnostic: it SHOULD notify/log, but MUST NOT automatically reset the parser or meta state. 6.8 E INVALID SESSION TERMINATION 窶・stale ] without session discriminator Trigger: A line窶冱 sequence counter field is marked stale (!) but does not carry a fractional session discriminator (i.e., !ﾎ] rather than !ﾎ.ﾎ拆). Effect: Emit E INVALID SESSION TERMINATION(observed primary=ﾎ). The line MUST NOT be interpreted as an end-of-session marker. E INVALID SESSION TERMINATION is diagnostic . Implementations SHOULD notify/log, but MUST NOT automatically reset parser or meta state. --- Appendix A 窶・Concrete BCODe examples (valid, terminated by a command char) A.1 Session start and followups (command carries integer ]) Command from requester (no ^, \\, or ^\\; integer ]): Direct affirmative response starts a session by labeling ] with fractional .17: Asynchronous followups are unsolicited (^\\) and keep fractional .17 while primary increases: Final followup ends the session by setting the stale flag on ]: A.2 Sessionless unsolicited statement A.3 Header-prefix run and transition to content Header-prefix lines are not delivered alone; they attach to the next unit. A.4 Session error examples (still syntactically valid BCODe) A.4.1 Invalid session declaration (fractional ] on a non-allowed line) Command request (integer ]): Direct response is affirmative, but the fractional component does not match the command窶冱 integer sequence (.19 vs 18): This MUST emit E INVALID SESSION DECL. A command line carrying a fractional ] is also an invalid session declaration: A.4.2 Nonexistent session (fractional reference to an inactive session) Session 17 is started and then ended: A later unsolicited line still labeled with .17 refers to an inactive session: This MUST emit E NON EXISTENT SESSION(17) and (by default) the unit MUST be dropped (not delivered). An unsolicited line referencing a session that never started is also nonexistent: This MUST emit E NON EXISTENT SESSION(99) and (by default) the unit MUST be dropped (not delivered). A.4.3 Invalid session termination (! on integer-only ]) Stale-marked integer-only sequence counters are not valid session terminations: This MUST emit E INVALID SESSION TERMINATION. --- End of document."}, {"slug": "meta-v7", "display_title": "BCODe.meta (v7)", "preview_title": "BCODe_meta_Convention.v9 窶・Preview", "description": "BCODe.meta 窶・Convention for Command/Response, Batching, Sequencing, Parser Reset Handling (Draft v9) Document date: 2026-02-22 Document version: 9 Status: Draft convention (built on top of BCODe syntax) BCODe.?", "corpus_text": "BCODe.meta 窶・Convention for Command/Response, Batching, Sequencing, Parser Reset Handling (Draft v9) Document date: 2026-02-22 Document version: 9 Status: Draft convention (built on top of BCODe syntax) BCODe.meta is a convention for stream-friendly command/response messaging: affirmative (^) and negative (\\) responses, unsolicited statements (^\\), multiline batching ([), sequence numbers (]), header-prefix delivery (-N[), asynchronous followup sessions encoded in ] fractional parts, and required behavior when the BCODe parser reports a parser-level reset event. Policy knobs (implementation configuration) BCODe.meta is normative about on窶層ire meaning , but allows implementations to choose certain receiver policies . This document standardizes knob names so behavior is predictable across implementations. 1.1 session idle timeout (ﾎ煩・ Type: duration (implementation-defined units) Default: implementation-defined (MAY be disabled) If enabled, an active session ﾎ・MAY be ended locally after ﾎ煩・of inactivity (see ﾂｧ2.4.6). 1.2 nonexistent session policy Controls what happens when an unsolicited statement references an inactive session (event E NON EXISTENT SESSION). Values: DROP (default): the deliverable unit is not delivered to the application . PASS THROUGH: the unit is delivered as sessionless unsolicited (still emits E NON EXISTENT SESSION). 1.3 drop sink (diagnostic tap) Type: callback/hook (or 窶彭isabled窶・ When a deliverable unit is dropped by policy (e.g., nonexistent session policy=DROP), the implementation MAY still export the decoded unit and/or raw bytes to drop sink for logging, tracing, quarantine storage, or debugging. Normative constraint: dropping MUST prevent the unit from reaching normal application delivery paths, but MUST NOT prevent diagnostic capture via drop sink. 1.4 allow ephemeral interjection Type: boolean Default: enabled Controls whether the receiver accepts ephemeral interjection requests (see ﾂｧ4.3). When disabled: Ephemeral interjection requests (?S] 窶ｦ ﾎｺ) MUST be refused as described in ﾂｧ4.3.6. Sessionless unsolicited statements marked ephemeral (?] ^\\ 窶ｦ ﾎｺ) are handled by ephemeral sessionless policy (ﾂｧ1.5). Endpoints configured for or detecting persistent multi-writer operation on a channel SHOULD disable this knob. 1.5 ephemeral sessionless policy Controls what happens when a sessionless unsolicited statement is received that is marked ephemeral (i.e., carries ? on its ] field, including ?]). Values: DROP (default): the unit is not delivered to the application (it MAY still be exported to drop sink). PASS THROUGH: the unit is delivered as a sessionless unsolicited statement. This knob is primarily relevant when allow ephemeral interjection is disabled (ﾂｧ1.4). 1.6 seq mismatch policy Controls what happens when E SEQ MISMATCH is triggered (ﾂｧ6.1). Values: LOG ONLY (default): deliver the unit and emit the event. DROP: do not deliver the unit to normal application callbacks/handlers, but the unit is still observed for sequence tracking (ﾂｧ6.1) and MAY be exported to drop sink (ﾂｧ1.3). BCODe.meta does not change BCODe syntax; it assigns conventional meaning to specific parameters and specifies how meta-convention state reacts to parser-level reset events. --- Reserved meta parameters Token Meaning (convention) --- --- ^ affirmative response tag (optional timestamp value) \\ negative response tag (optional error/reason code value) ^\\ unsolicited statement tag (sent without a request) [ multiline packet/batch tag ] sequence counter -N[ header-prefix lines that attach metadata to the next deliverable unit Note on staleness: BCODe's ! stale qualifier (a field-level modifier, not a parameter) is used by this convention only when attached to the ] field with a fractional session discriminator (a sequence number pair). It is reserved for two purposes: 1) End-of-session marker on the final in-session followup: !ﾎ.ﾎ拆 ^\\ 窶ｦ ﾎｺ (see ﾂｧ2.4.4). 2) Ephemeral busy refusal indicator : !0.T] \\ 窶ｦ ﾎｺ (see ﾂｧ4.3.6). The ! indicates the busy report may be stale by the time it is received. Using ! on an integer-only ] value (!ﾎ]) is an invalid session termination (see E INVALID SESSION TERMINATION in ﾂｧ6). --- Command/response and unsolicited rules Metanotation binding. In this section, a BCODe line is abstractly denoted as ﾎｦ ﾎｺ for a command-terminated line. The symbol ﾎｦ denotes the complete field value (possibly decomposed as ﾎ・[ . , ﾎ・] [ ( /) ﾎ・]). Unless otherwise stated, statements about 窶徼he ] value窶・refer abstractly to ﾎｦ in the ] field. 2.1 Commands A command is a line sent by a requester. Commands MUST NOT include ^, \\, or ^\\. If a command carries a sequence counter ], its ] value MUST be an integer (no fractional part). (The ] fractional part is reserved for responder-side session labeling; see ﾂｧ2.4.) If a command is received with a fractional ] value (i.e., ﾎ.ﾎ拆), the BCODe.meta layer MUST emit E INVALID SESSION DECL (see ﾂｧ6) and SHOULD ignore the fractional component for session purposes. 2.2 Direct response A line transmitted as the direct response to a command is a response and MUST be tagged: ^ for affirmative acknowledgement \\ for negative acknowledgement (MAY include an error/reason code) A direct response MAY also start an asynchronous followup session (ﾂｧ2.4). If a direct response carries a fractional ] value, it MUST be either: 1) an affirmative response (^) whose fractional component matches the integer sequence number of the command it is directly responding to (see ﾂｧ2.4.2), or 2) the reserved ephemeral busy refusal form !0.T] \\ 窶ｦ ﾎｺ (see ﾂｧ4.3.6). Any other use of a fractional ] value in a direct response MUST emit E INVALID SESSION DECL (see ﾂｧ6). 2.3 Unsolicited statements (two kinds) A line transmitted without a preceding request as its direct response MUST be tagged as unsolicited: It MUST contain both ^ and \\ (written as ^\\ in examples). Unsolicited statements are divided into: 1) Sessionless unsolicited statements Unsolicited statements that are not asynchronous followups to a command session. 2) In-session unsolicited statements (asynchronous followups) Unsolicited statements that belong to a session started by a command窶冱 affirmative direct response (ﾂｧ2.4). The distinction is determined by the session rules in ﾂｧ2.4 (and the receiver窶冱 active-session state). If an unsolicited statement carries a fractional ] value (ﾎ.ﾎ拆), the receiver MUST treat it as an in-session followup only if session ﾎ・is currently active; otherwise it MUST emit E NON EXISTENT SESSION(ﾎ・ (see ﾂｧ6) and, by default, MUST drop the line (do not deliver it to application/user logic). Receivers MUST apply nonexistent session policy (ﾂｧ1.2). The default is DROP, which prevents delivery to application/user logic but still allows diagnostic capture via drop sink (ﾂｧ1.3). 2.4 Asynchronous followup sessions encoded in ] Metanotation binding. The session discriminator is denoted ﾎ・ Where multiple lines are discussed, they may be written as 邃乍ｵ｢, each containing a ] field whose abstract value is ﾎｦ盞｢. Session consistency constraints apply to ﾎ・邃乍ｵ｢) across all lines in a unit. This section defines how a responder can emit additional unsolicited followup statements that are logically tied to a previously acknowledged command. 2.4.1 Abstract notation (Greek letters) Let: ﾎ・be the integer sequence number in the requester窶冱 command ﾎ拆 ... ﾎｺ ﾎ be the responder窶冱 primary sequence number (integer part of its outbound ]) ﾎｺ be a command character (lowercase ASCII; application-defined) A response uses a sequence number pair by writing a fractional part: ﾎ.ﾎ拆 Here ﾎ is the primary sequence number, and the fractional component ﾎ・is the session discriminator . 2.4.2 Session start (normative) A session MAY start only when the direct response to a command is affirmative (^). A responder indicates that an affirmative direct response starts a session by: including a ] field whose fractional component equals the command窶冱 integer ] value. Concretely: Command: ﾎ拆 ... ﾎｺ (no fractional part permitted on the command) Direct affirmative response that starts session ﾎ・ ﾎ.ﾎ拆 ^ ... ﾎｺ On reception of such a direct affirmative response, the BCODe.meta layer MUST emit Start of session event E SESSION START(ﾎ・ and record session ﾎ・as active . If the direct response is negative (\\), or the response does not carry ] with fractional component ﾎ・ then no session starts . 2.4.3 In-session followups (normative) While session ﾎ・is active, any subsequent unsolicited statement that: is tagged ^\\, and carries a ] value whose fractional component equals ﾎ・is an in-session unsolicited followup for session ﾎ・ In-session followups: MUST maintain the same fractional component ﾎ・in their ] field, and SHOULD use a primary sequence number ﾎ that increases monotonically. 2.4.4 End of session (normative) The final in-session unsolicited followup for session ﾎ・MUST: set the ! stale flag on its ] field, and maintain the same fractional component ﾎ・ Concretely: !ﾎ.ﾎ拆 ^\\ ... ﾎｺ On reception, the BCODe.meta layer MUST emit End of session event E SESSION END(ﾎ・ and mark session ﾎ・inactive. After E SESSION END(ﾎ・, any later ^\\ line labeled with fractional ﾎ・refers to an inactive session and MUST emit E NON EXISTENT SESSION(ﾎ・. By default, such lines MUST be dropped (not delivered) and MUST NOT be treated as in-session followups. Implementations MAY support a non-default 窶徘ass-through窶・policy that delivers the line as a sessionless unsolicited statement. 2.4.5 Session error conditions (normative) BCODe.meta defines the following session-related protocol errors: Invalid session declaration : a fractional ] value (ﾎ.ﾎ拆) appears on a line that is neither: the affirmative direct response that starts session ﾎ・(ﾂｧ2.4.2), nor an unsolicited statement (^\\) (ﾂｧ2.4.3), nor the reserved ephemeral busy refusal !0.T] \\ 窶ｦ ﾎｺ (ﾂｧ4.3.6). On detection, the BCODe.meta layer MUST emit E INVALID SESSION DECL. Nonexistent session : an unsolicited statement (^\\) carries a fractional ] value (ﾎ.ﾎ拆) but session ﾎ・is not active. On detection, the BCODe.meta layer MUST emit E NON EXISTENT SESSION(ﾎ・ and, by default, MUST drop the line (do not deliver it). Implementations MAY expose a non-default 窶徘ass-through窶・policy that delivers the line as sessionless unsolicited. Invalid session termination : a ] field is marked stale (!) but has no fractional component (i.e., !ﾎ]). On detection, the BCODe.meta layer MUST emit E INVALID SESSION TERMINATION. These events SHOULD notify/log, but MUST NOT automatically reset parser or meta state. E NON EXISTENT SESSION is additionally a delivery condition: by default the associated line is dropped (not delivered), per ﾂｧ6.7. 2.4.6 Receiver-side session timeout (optional) BCODe.meta defines an explicit, on窶層ire end-of-session marker (!ﾎ.ﾎ拆 on the final followup). However, receivers MAY also end sessions locally to bound resource usage. Let ﾎ煩・be a receiver-configured idle timeout . A receiver MAY mark an active session ﾎ・inactive if no in-session activity for ﾎ・is observed for at least ﾎ煩・ In-session activity includes the session-starting direct response ﾎ.ﾎ拆 ^ ... ﾎｺ and any subsequent in-session followups ﾎ.ﾎ拆 ^\\ ... ﾎｺ. On timeout, the receiver SHOULD emit E SESSION END(ﾎ・ cause=timeout) (or E SESSION END(ﾎ・ if causes are not supported) and mark the session inactive. Once timed out, any later followup labeled with fractional ﾎ・MUST be treated as a reference to an inactive session and MUST raise E NON EXISTENT SESSION(ﾎ・; by default it will be dropped. Because this is a local policy, timeouts have no on-wire representation . Senders that require reliable delivery of followups SHOULD send the explicit stale termination marker (!ﾎ.ﾎ拆). --- Multiline batching with [ 3.0 Header-prefix lines using negative [ values The [ parameter MAY also appear with a negative integer value, written as -N[ where N 竕･ 1. In this form, the line is a header-prefix line that modifies delivery of the following unit. Delivery rule: a contiguous run of one or more header-prefix lines immediately preceding a deliverable unit attaches to that unit. The unit is either: the next single (non-header) line, or the next multiline packet/batch formed with [ (fixed-bound or open-ended), treated atomically. Ordering rule (stack form): if multiple header-prefix lines are present, their [ values MUST be: -K[, -(K-1)[, 窶ｦ, -2[, -1[ with -1[ adjacent to the content unit. This yields a stack that higher layers may interpret hop-by-hop (e.g., a routing layer may peel one header per hop). Meta-layer behavior: Header-prefix lines MUST NOT be delivered to the application as independent statements. Instead, the implementation SHOULD deliver the following unit together with the collected header-prefix lines (e.g., as an array of header lines or as an opaque 窶徂eaders窶・blob). BCODe.meta does not assign semantics to the header content beyond the attachment and ordering rules above. 3.1 Purpose: atomic delivery 3.1.1 Multiline consistency (Normative) For a delivered multiline unit {邃凪・, 邃凪ａ, 窶ｦ, 邃凪ｙ}, each line 邃乍ｵ｢ has an abstract form ﾎｦ盞｢ ﾎｺ盞｢. Multiline consistency requires that: kind(邃乍ｵ｢) = kind(邃凪・) for all i If in-session unsolicited: ﾎ・邃乍ｵ｢) = ﾎ・邃凪・) for all i Here ﾎｦ盞｢ denotes the complete field value of each line窶冱 relevant field, and ﾎ・denotes the session discriminator defined in ﾂｧ2.4. A completed multiline packet/batch (formed using [ and delivered atomically as a unit) MUST be internally consistent in its meta kind : All lines in the delivered unit MUST have the same kind: command , direct response , or unsolicited . If the unit kind is unsolicited , then all lines in the unit MUST be either: 1) sessionless unsolicited , or 2) in-session unsolicited followups for the same session discriminator ﾎ・ This rule prevents ambiguous mixtures such as a packet that combines command semantics with unsolicited semantics, or mixes multiple followup sessions in a single delivered unit. Implementation requirement: once a unit is complete (single-line or multiline), the meta layer MUST classify the kind of each line and enforce: kind(line[i]) == kind(line[0]) for all i If kind == in-session unsolicited: session ﾎ・line[i]) == session ﾎ・line[0]) for all i On violation, the implementation MUST drop the unit and emit an error as defined in ﾂｧ6 (BC META ERR BATCH MIXED KIND and/or BC META ERR BATCH MIXED SESSION). The [ parameter is reserved for batching multiple lines into a single atomic group . Requirement: a receiver SHOULD NOT expose packet lines to the application as independent statements. Instead, it SHOULD buffer until the packet completes, then deliver the set as one unit (atomically). This is the core reason [ exists: batching changes delivery , not field semantics. 3.2 Fixed-bound packets (known length) In the fixed-bound form, each line carries a [ field whose numeric value is i.t: i = 1-based line index within the packet t = total line count Example (3-line packet): 3.3 Open-ended packets (unknown length) Open-ended packets are permitted without an end bound when: 1) the [ field carries the qualifier on each non-final line, 2) the numeric value of the [ field monotonically increases , and 3) the final line closes the packet with a fixed-bound i.t[ terminator exactly as if the bounds had been known initially. Example (unknown length until end): Notes: The receiver buffers i[ lines until it receives the closing i.t[ line. Monotonicity SHOULD be interpreted as contiguous increment by 1 (otherwise it is likely an error). 3.4 Header/sequence counter coupling (normative) If a header-prefix line is immediately followed by a line that carries a sequence counter ], the header-prefix line MUST carry the same ] value. This rule applies recursively through a header run: For a header stack -K[ 窶ｦ -1[ preceding a unit, each header line MUST copy the ] value of the line immediately following it (e.g., -2[ copies from -1[, and -1[ copies from the first content line of the delivered unit). If the immediately following line has no ], the header-prefix line MUST NOT invent a ] value (i.e., omit ]). Rationale: this preserves the sequence identity of the delivered unit while allowing intermediate layers to strip headers without losing sequence correlation. --- Sequence counters with ] Metanotation binding. In this section, the ] field value is denoted abstractly as ﾎｦ. When rollover or ordering behavior is discussed, it refers to the numeric component ﾎ・of ﾎｦ unless explicitly stated otherwise. The ] parameter is reserved for sequence counters. 4.0 Shapes and reserved modifiers BCODe.meta interprets ] values as follows: The primary sequence number is the integer part of the numeric value in the ] field. The fractional component (if present) is reserved for the session discriminator described in ﾂｧ2.4. Because ] is a reserved meta parameter, BCODe.meta also assigns special meaning to certain qualifiers on ]: ! on ] is reserved (see the staleness note in ﾂｧ1): it MUST only appear when ] has a fractional component. ? on ] is reserved for the optional ephemeral interjection convention (ﾂｧ4.3). < on ] is reserved for the rollover marker (ﾂｧ4.1). Other qualifier meanings (such as 窶從umeric bounds窶・ from generic value-interpretation rules do not apply to ]. 4.1 Rollover marker (expected wrap to 0) Senders that use a bounded sequence space (e.g., 16-bit counters) MAY indicate an expected rollover to 0 by marking the ] field with the < qualifier. Form: <ﾎ] or <ﾎ.ﾎ拆 Semantics: The marked unit carries primary sequence ﾎ as normal. The next expected primary sequence number from that peer is 0 (rather than ﾎ+1). If a fractional session discriminator .ﾎ・is present, it is unchanged; the rollover marker applies to the primary sequence only. Example (16-bit wrap): 4.2 Recommendations for rollover design (informative) BCODe.meta does not mandate a sequence modulus. However, rollover design impacts interoperability, especially when strict mismatch policies are enabled. Unsolicited / telemetry channels (^\\): For channels intended to emit long-running unsolicited data, SEQ MAX SHOULD be the maximum representable integer value for the deployed implementation (窶廬NTMAX/UINTMAX窶・. Rollover then becomes extremely rare in practice. Synchronous / control channels (command/response): For channels intended for synchronous communication or controls, SEQ MAX MAY be much smaller. A useful heuristic is to choose a modulus on the order of: SEQ MOD 竕・10 ﾃ・TX MAX UNITS where TX MAX UNITS is the maximum number of deliverable units (direct response + any expected followups) in the longest expected transaction. A smaller rollover interval increases the chance of 窶從atural resync窶・if strict mismatch policies are configured poorly. Session discriminator safety: If asynchronous followup sessions (ﾂｧ2.4) are used, the requester窶冱 command sequence ﾎ・is reused as the session discriminator in ﾎ.ﾎ拆. Channels using small moduli SHOULD ensure that a discriminator ﾎ・will not be reused (due to rollover) while a prior session ﾎ・could still be active (via explicit termination !ﾎ.ﾎ拆 or local timeout). 4.3 Ephemeral interjection stream (?-qualified ]) (optional) This subsection defines an optional convention that allows an ephemeral non-default writer to interject a request/response exchange without consuming or perturbing the receiver窶冱 default-writer outbound sequence stream. This convention is activated only when a delivered unit carries a ] field with the ? qualifier. Units without ? follow the rules above unchanged. 4.3.1 Meaning of ? on ] When ] is qualified with ?, its numeric content is correlation-only and MUST NOT: participate in, or advance, the receiver窶冱 default-writer outbound sequence counter, nor modify the receiver窶冱 recorded peer last primary sequence used for E SEQ MISMATCH (ﾂｧ6.1). Implementations MAY maintain separate bookkeeping for ephemeral streams if desired. 4.3.2 Sessionless unsolicited from an ephemeral writer A sessionless unsolicited message from an ephemeral writer MAY carry ?] (no numeric value). Example: If allow ephemeral interjection is disabled, delivery is controlled by ephemeral sessionless policy (ﾂｧ1.5). 4.3.3 Ephemeral request and direct response (no session) An ephemeral writer sending a request MUST include an integer sequence number S qualified with ?: A single direct response from the receiver MUST respond using sequence number (S + 1) also qualified with ?: A negative direct response is analogous: This ensures the receiver窶冱 default-writer outbound sequence counter does not advance as a result of the interjection. 4.3.4 Ephemeral request and direct response that starts a session If the receiver窶冱 direct affirmative response starts an asynchronous followup session (see ﾂｧ2.4), it MUST do so using the existing session rule, but maintaining the ? qualifier: 4.3.5 Routing responsibility BCODe.meta does not define how the response reaches the ephemeral writer. Implementations MUST surface enough information (via transport context and/or higher-layer header conventions) for the application to route the receiver窶冱 response back to the appropriate ephemeral writer. 4.3.6 Policy disable, concurrency rule, and refusal forms Policy disable: When allow ephemeral interjection is disabled, an incoming ephemeral interjection request (?S] 窶ｦ ﾎｺ) MUST be refused with a negative direct response (\\) that preserves the command field ﾎｺ. The response SHOULD use ?(S+1)] for correlation. Concurrency (recommended): To keep receiver behavior simple, receivers SHOULD permit at most one pending ephemeral interjection/session at a time. If a new ephemeral request arrives while an earlier ephemeral request/session with discriminator T is pending, the receiver MUST refuse immediately using: !0.T] \\ 窶ｦ ﾎｺ The ! indicates the busy report may be stale by the time it is received. The !0.T] form is reserved for this refusal and MUST NOT be interpreted as participating in any sequence stream (and MUST NOT affect E SEQ MISMATCH bookkeeping). Example (pending T=10): --- Parser reset event BCODe.meta does not define the on窶層ire reset/resynchronization token, receiver acknowledgements, or any transmitter synchronization strategy. Those are specified at the BCODe syntax / parser level. This document specifies only how the BCODe.meta convention state MUST react when the underlying parser reports a reset-related event. 5.1 Required meta-layer reaction When the parser reports a reset event (including a reset acknowledgement, if the parser distinguishes them), a BCODe.meta endpoint MUST: Discard any partially buffered packet/batch state started with [ (both fixed-bound and open-ended forms). Discard any partially collected header-prefix state (-N[ lines) not yet attached to a delivered unit. Reset any sequence counters it transmits using ] back to 0 . Clear any internal bookkeeping used to decide whether the next outbound line is a direct response (^ / \\) vs an unsolicited statement (^\\). Clear any active-session tracking state (both local and peer-visible) created under ﾂｧ2.4. 5.2 Optional exposure to the application Implementations MAY surface the parser窶冱 reset classification (e.g., 窶徨eset request窶・vs 窶徨eset acknowledgement窶・ to the application layer for diagnostics, but BCODe.meta assigns no additional meaning beyond the required state reset above. --- Meta events emitted during analysis This section defines standard events a BCODe.meta implementation MAY/SHOULD emit while analyzing the stream. Events are emitted as a result of analyzing latched BCODe lines and/or completing atomic delivery units (headers + content, packets). 6.1 E SEQ MISMATCH 窶・expected sequence number mismatch Trigger: A deliverable unit (a single line, or a completed packet, after header-prefix attachment rules) is observed carrying a ] field with primary sequence ﾎ that: is not qualified with ?, and is not the reserved ephemeral-busy refusal form !0.T] \\ 窶ｦ ﾎｺ (ﾂｧ4.3.6), and the implementation previously recorded the peer窶冱 last primary sequence as ﾎ・ and ﾎ 竕 expected next, where: expected next = 0 if the previously observed (tracked) peer ] carried the rollover marker < (ﾂｧ4.1), otherwise expected next = ﾎ・+ 1. Effect: Emit E SEQ MISMATCH(expected=expected next, observed=ﾎ). Update the recorded peer last primary sequence to ﾎ. If seq mismatch policy=DROP, the unit MUST NOT be delivered to normal application callbacks/handlers, but it MAY still be exported to drop sink (ﾂｧ1.3). This is a cautionary event: it SHOULD notify and log, but MUST NOT automatically reset or otherwise modify meta state (beyond updating the peer last primary sequence number). Notes: If no prior tracked peer sequence number has been recorded, the first observed tracked ] establishes it and MUST NOT trigger E SEQ MISMATCH. Header-prefix lines do not form deliverable units by themselves and SHOULD NOT be sequence-checked independently. Units that are later dropped due to meta-level validation (e.g., E NON EXISTENT SESSION) are still 窶徙bserved窶・for sequence tracking purposes (and update ﾎ・ unless excluded by the rules above. 6.2 E SESSION START 窶・start of session detected Trigger: While processing a direct response to a command with integer sequence ﾎ拆, the response is affirmative (^) and carries a ] field whose fractional component equals ﾎ・(i.e., ﾎ.ﾎ拆). Effect: Emit E SESSION START(ﾎ・. Record session ﾎ・as active. Session start is an observation . Application/user logic decides what 窶彙eing in a session窶・means. 6.3 E SESSION END 窶・end of session detected Trigger: On窶層ire termination: While session ﾎ・is active, an in-session unsolicited followup is received whose ] field is marked stale (!ﾎ.ﾎ拆). Optional local termination: The receiver expires session ﾎ・due to a local policy such as an idle timeout ﾎ煩・(ﾂｧ2.4.6). Effect: Emit E SESSION END(ﾎ・ cause=stale) for on窶層ire termination, or E SESSION END(ﾎ・ cause=timeout) for local termination (implementations MAY omit the cause argument if they do not support it). Mark session ﾎ・inactive. 6.4 E HEADER START 窶・start of header-prefix run detected Trigger: A header-prefix line (a line containing a negative -N[ field with N 竕･ 1) is received while not already collecting a header-prefix run. Effect: Emit E HEADER START. 6.5 E HEADER TO CONTENT 窶・transition from header to content Trigger: A header-prefix line containing -1[ is received. Effect: Emit E HEADER TO CONTENT, indicating that the next delivered unit line (or the next packet start) is the content to which the accumulated header-prefix run will attach. 6.6 E INVALID SESSION DECL 窶・invalid session declaration Trigger: A latched line carries a fractional sequence number pair ﾎ.ﾎ拆, but the line is neither: an unsolicited statement (^\\), nor the affirmative direct response that starts session ﾎ・for a command ﾎ拆 ... ﾎｺ (see ﾂｧ2.4.2), nor the reserved ephemeral busy refusal !0.T] \\ 窶ｦ ﾎｺ (see ﾂｧ4.3.6). This includes (non-exhaustive), except for the reserved ephemeral-busy refusal !0.T] \\ 窶ｦ ﾎｺ (ﾂｧ4.3.6): a command line that carries ﾎ.ﾎ拆, a negative direct response (\\) that carries ﾎ.ﾎ拆, an affirmative direct response (^) whose fractional component does not match the command窶冱 integer sequence. Effect: Emit E INVALID SESSION DECL(observed primary=ﾎ, observed session=ﾎ・. Do not start or end any session as a result of this line. E INVALID SESSION DECL is diagnostic . Implementations SHOULD notify/log, but MUST NOT automatically reset parser or meta state. 6.7 E NON EXISTENT SESSION 窶・in-session reference to inactive session Trigger: An unsolicited statement (^\\) carries a fractional ] value ﾎ.ﾎ拆, but session ﾎ・is not currently active (never started, already ended, expired by timeout, or otherwise unknown to the receiver). Effect: Emit E NON EXISTENT SESSION(ﾎ・. Apply nonexistent session policy (ﾂｧ1.2): DROP (default): do not deliver the unit to normal application callbacks / handlers. The unit MAY still be exported to drop sink (ﾂｧ1.3). PASS THROUGH: deliver the unit as a sessionless unsolicited statement (it still emits E NON EXISTENT SESSION and MUST NOT be treated as in-session). Sequence tracking MUST still observe the unit窶冱 primary sequence number ﾎ (if present) and update the recorded peer last primary sequence accordingly (so that subsequent sequence expectations track the peer窶冱 stream). E NON EXISTENT SESSION is diagnostic: it SHOULD notify/log, but MUST NOT automatically reset the parser or meta state. 6.8 E INVALID SESSION TERMINATION 窶・stale ] without session discriminator Trigger: A line窶冱 sequence counter field is marked stale (!) but does not carry a fractional session discriminator (i.e., !ﾎ] rather than !ﾎ.ﾎ拆). Effect: Emit E INVALID SESSION TERMINATION(observed primary=ﾎ). The line MUST NOT be interpreted as an end-of-session marker. E INVALID SESSION TERMINATION is diagnostic . Implementations SHOULD notify/log, but MUST NOT automatically reset parser or meta state. --- Appendix A 窶・Concrete BCODe examples (valid, terminated by a command char) A.1 Session start and followups (command carries integer ]) Command from requester (no ^, \\, or ^\\; integer ]): Direct affirmative response starts a session by labeling ] with fractional .17: Asynchronous followups are unsolicited (^\\) and keep fractional .17 while primary increases: Final followup ends the session by setting the stale flag on ]: A.2 Sessionless unsolicited statement A.3 Header-prefix run and transition to content Header-prefix lines are not delivered alone; they attach to the next unit. A.4 Session error examples (still syntactically valid BCODe) A.4.1 Invalid session declaration (fractional ] on a non-allowed line) Command request (integer ]): Direct response is affirmative, but the fractional component does not match the command窶冱 integer sequence (.19 vs 18): This MUST emit E INVALID SESSION DECL. A command line carrying a fractional ] is also an invalid session declaration: A.4.2 Nonexistent session (fractional reference to an inactive session) Session 17 is started and then ended: A later unsolicited line still labeled with .17 refers to an inactive session: This MUST emit E NON EXISTENT SESSION(17) and (by default) the unit MUST be dropped (not delivered). An unsolicited line referencing a session that never started is also nonexistent: This MUST emit E NON EXISTENT SESSION(99) and (by default) the unit MUST be dropped (not delivered). A.4.3 Invalid session termination (! on integer-only ]) Stale-marked integer-only sequence counters are not valid session terminations: This MUST emit E INVALID SESSION TERMINATION. --- End of document."}, {"slug": "meta-library-semantics", "display_title": "Meta Library Semantics", "preview_title": "BCODe_meta_Library_Semantics.v9aligned 窶・Preview", "description": "BCODe meta Library Semantics Specification (BCODe.meta Convention v9) Document date: 2026-02-23 Status: Library semantics (normative) Normative convention baseline: BCODe.meta 窶・Convention v9 (2026-02-22) Scop?", "corpus_text": "BCODe meta Library Semantics Specification (BCODe.meta Convention v9) Document date: 2026-02-23 Status: Library semantics (normative) Normative convention baseline: BCODe.meta 窶・Convention v9 (2026-02-22) Scope This document specifies the observable behavior of the bcode meta library: How it consumes a stream of bytes via the underlying SAB streaming parser and delivers atomic units to the application. How it buffers and assembles multiline packets ([ batching, including open-ended packets) and header-prefix runs (-N[). How it captures and exposes per-line payload bytes ($ string payload and binary payload forms). How it performs BCODe.meta sequence and session analysis and emits diagnostics. How it stages and serializes outgoing transmissions (TX) when TX support is enabled. This document does not redefine BCODe syntax. It also does not redefine BCODe.meta on窶層ire meaning ; where possible it imports those rules from the BCODe.meta Convention v9 document and focuses on how this library exposes them. Normative keywords (MUST, MUST NOT, SHOULD, SHOULD NOT, MAY) are to be interpreted as in RFC 2119. Normative references BCODe syntax / SAB parser : defines byte-to-line parsing, payload tokenization, and the parser-level reset event. BCODe.meta Convention v9 (2026-02-22) : defines on窶層ire meaning for ^, \\, ^\\, [, ], header-prefix -N[, sessions via fractional ], rollover marker < on ], ephemeral qualifier ? on ], and required reaction to parser reset events. Where this spec says 窶・per v9 窶・ it refers to those imported rules. Where this spec says 窶・library-specific 窶・ it defines behavior not standardized by v9. Terminology Line A parsed BCODe line produced by the SAB parser (bcode line t). Header-prefix line A line that carries a negative [ value: -N[ for integer N 竕･ 1 (per v9 header-prefix convention). Header-prefix lines are buffered and later attached to a unit; they are never delivered standalone . Multiline packet / batch A group of one or more content lines framed by the v9 [ batching convention and delivered atomically. Deliverable unit (unit) The atomic item delivered to the application callbacks: Content : either 1 content line, or N content lines from a completed multiline packet. Optional headers : 0..K header-prefix lines attached to that unit. Unit kind (per v9) Command : no ^ and no \\. Direct response : ^ or \\ (but not ^\\). Unsolicited : tagged with both ^ and \\ (written ^\\). Primary sequence number The integer part of ] (per v9). This library tracks peer primary sequences and can emit mismatch diagnostics. Session discriminator The fractional component .ﾎ・in a pair-shaped ] value (ﾎ.ﾎ拆) used by v9 to label asynchronous followup sessions. Ephemeral qualifier The ? qualifier on ] (per v9 ﾂｧ4.3). Ephemeral units are excluded from default-writer peer sequence tracking. Reserved busy-refusal form The v9 reserved negative direct response used for ephemeral contention: !0.T] \\ ... ﾎｺ (excluded from default sequence tracking). Public API contracts 4.1 Configuration (bcode meta config t) The configuration struct defines fixed capacities and a small number of behavior knobs: RX buffering capacity rx max header lines Maximum number of buffered header-prefix lines waiting to attach to the next deliverable unit. If rx max header lines == 0, all header-prefix lines are dropped (with BC META ERR HEADER LIMIT). rx max multiline lines Maximum number of content lines buffered for one multiline packet. If exceeded: BC META ERR PACKET LIMIT and the packet is dropped. rx payload bytes (overloaded; library-specific) RX payload capture pool capacity in bytes. Also the per-packet payload-byte budget enforced while buffering a packet (only when nonzero). Special case: rx payload bytes == 0 disables payload capture and disables the per-packet payload budget check. RX session behavior rx enable session timeout, rx session timeout ms Enables receiver-side idle session timeout behavior (v9 session idle timeout). The application MUST provide monotonic time via bcode meta tick(now ms) for timeouts to take effect. TX staging capacity tx max header lines, tx max multiline lines Maximum number of staged TX header lines and content lines for a single in-flight TX unit. tx payload bytes Budget for serialized outbound bytes for the staged TX unit (0 = unbounded). Optional bookkeeping table limits (used by both RX and TX) tx max active requests Size of the pending-request table used to validate v9 session-start discriminators and to match outbound requests with inbound direct responses. If 0: request tracking is disabled and some validations become best-effort. tx max active sessions Size of the active-session table used for RX in-session followup classification and TX in-session validation. If 0: session tracking is disabled; all in-session followups will be treated as referencing a nonexistent session and will be dropped. Behavior knobs strict open contiguous If true: RX open-ended packets ( i[) MUST increase contiguously by 1 ( 1[, 2[, 窶ｦ). Otherwise the library permits non-contiguous monotonic increases. tx manage primary seq If true: the library stamps/advances integer ] primary sequence on outbound units where required and resets the managed primary sequence to 0 on parser reset. Serialization use crlf selects line termination (\\r\\n vs \\n) for TX serialization. 4.2 Callbacks (bcode meta callbacks t) Delivery callbacks For each delivered unit, exactly one of the following may be called (depending on unit kind): on command(user, unit) on direct response(user, unit) Special case: if TX failure is signaled for an outbound request that expected a direct response, the library calls on direct response(user, NULL) (see ﾂｧ8.5). on unsolicited sessionless(user, unit) on unsolicited in session(user, unit) Session lifecycle callbacks on session start(user, session n) 窶・v9 session start observation. on session end(user, session n, by timeout) 窶・v9 end marker observation or local idle timeout. Diagnostics on meta error(user, ctx) is called for meta-layer errors and policy/validation events (batching violations, limit overflows, session violations, etc.). ctx- code identifies the event; ctx- line index, ctx- session n, and ctx- a/ctx- b provide context. Reset on reset(user, is ack) is called when the SAB parser reports a reset event. No deliverable unit is produced for a reset. 4.3 Pointer lifetime (hard rule) All pointers reachable from a delivered bcode meta unit t (including header and content bcode line t pointers and any payload pointer) are valid only during the callback invocation . The application MUST copy data it needs to retain beyond the callback. BCODe.meta Convention v9 semantics as implemented 5.1 Unit classification and delivery (per v9) The library classifies completed deliverable units using v9窶冱 tagging rules: Command : no ^ and no \\ 竍・delivered via on command. Direct response : has exactly one of ^ or \\ 竍・delivered via on direct response. Unsolicited : has both ^ and \\ 竍・delivered via one of: on unsolicited sessionless if not an in-session followup, or on unsolicited in session if it is an in-session followup for an active session discriminator .ﾎ・ A deliverable unit is: a single content line, or a completed multiline packet (N content lines), plus any attached header-prefix run. Header-prefix lines are never delivered standalone. 5.2 Header-prefix runs (per v9 ﾂｧ3.0 + ﾂｧ3.4, plus library details) 5.2.1 Buffering and attachment A header-prefix run is a contiguous run of one or more -N[ lines immediately preceding a deliverable content unit. The library buffers such lines and attempts to attach them to the next delivered unit. Header-prefix lines MUST NOT be delivered as independent units. 5.2.2 Ordering rule Per v9 窶徭tack form窶・ the buffered header run MUST be a contiguous decreasing sequence: -K[, -(K-1)[, 窶ｦ, -2[, -1[ Ordering violations can be detected in two places: While collecting headers: if a newly received header-prefix line does not match the expected next -N[ value, the library emits BC META ERR HEADER ORDER and clears the buffered header run immediately. At unit delivery time: if a content unit becomes deliverable while a header run is pending but incomplete (i.e., the library is still expecting additional headers down to -1[), the library emits BC META ERR HEADER ORDER, delivers the content unit without headers, and sets BC META UNIT F DROPPED on that delivered unit. 5.2.3 Capacity limit If buffering a header line would exceed rx max header lines (or if rx max header lines == 0), the library emits BC META ERR HEADER LIMIT and discards the entire buffered header run. Header-prefix lines are not delivered. 5.2.4 Header/sequence coupling Per v9 ﾂｧ3.4, header-prefix lines MUST copy the ] field of the immediately following line (or omit ] if the following line omits it). The library enforces this by requiring each buffered header line窶冱 ] field to exactly match the first content line窶冱 ] field (including qualifiers/modifiers). If coupling fails, the library emits BC META ERR HEADER DISALLOWED, discards the header run, and delivers the content unit with BC META UNIT F DROPPED and without headers. 5.3 Multiline batching with [ (per v9 ﾂｧ3, plus library details) 5.3.1 Fixed-bound packets The library supports fixed-bound batching where each content line carries an [ value of the form i.t with: i = 1-based line index t = total line count Packet closes when the line with i == t is received. Violations of shape, index/total mismatch, unexpected close, or interleaving emit the corresponding BC META ERR BATCH error and the packet is dropped. 5.3.2 Open-ended packets The library supports open-ended batching per v9: Non-final lines carry i[ ( qualifier on [) with monotonically increasing i. The final line closes the packet with a fixed-bound i.t[ terminator. If strict open contiguous is true, then the open-ended index MUST increment contiguously by 1. Open-ended units are delivered with unit flag BC META UNIT F OPEN ENDED in addition to BC META UNIT F PACKET. 5.3.3 Packet buffering limits If buffering would exceed rx max multiline lines, the library emits BC META ERR PACKET LIMIT and drops the packet. If rx payload bytes != 0 and the cumulative payload bytes across buffered packet lines would exceed rx payload bytes, the library emits BC META ERR PAYLOAD OVERFLOW and drops the packet. 5.3.4 Multiline consistency (v9 ﾂｧ3.1.1) When a packet completes, the library enforces v9 multiline consistency: All content lines in the unit MUST have the same meta kind (command, direct response, unsolicited). Violation 竍・BC META ERR BATCH MIXED KIND and drop. If the kind is direct response, all lines MUST have the same polarity (^ vs \\). Violation 竍・BC META ERR BATCH MIXED POLARITY and drop. If the kind is unsolicited and any line is labeled as in-session (fractional ] discriminator .ﾎ・, then all lines MUST be labeled with the same .ﾎ・ Violation 竍・BC META ERR BATCH MIXED SESSION and drop. 5.4 Sequence counters ] and mismatch diagnostics (v9 ﾂｧ4 + ﾂｧ6.1) 5.4.1 What is tracked The library performs peer sequence tracking on the first content line of each completed deliverable unit. The following units are excluded from default peer sequence tracking: Units whose first content line has ? qualified ] (ephemeral stream). The reserved busy-refusal form !0.T] \\ 窶ｦ ﾎｺ. 5.4.2 Expected-next rule Let the last tracked primary be N. For the next tracked unit, expected primary is: 0 if the previously tracked unit carried the rollover marker < on its ], otherwise N + 1. 5.4.3 Mismatch behavior If the observed primary differs from expected: Emit BC META ERR SEQ MISMATCH with ctx- a = expected and ctx- b = observed. Still update the recorded last primary to the observed value. Library policy: mismatch is log-only (the unit is still delivered). 5.5 Sessions encoded in ] (v9 ﾂｧ2.4 + ﾂｧ6.2窶督ｧ6.8) This library implements v9 session semantics using an active-session table sized by tx max active sessions. 5.5.1 Session start (v9 ﾂｧ2.4.2) A session discriminator ﾎ・MAY start only from a positive direct response (^) that carries a pair-shaped ] value ﾎ.ﾎ拆 whose fractional component matches the request窶冱 integer ] value. If request tracking is enabled (tx max active requests 0), the library validates that ﾎ・corresponds to a pending request and that the request窶冱 ephemeral-ness matches the ? qualifier (per v9). If request tracking is disabled, the library cannot validate and treats a positive direct response with a valid discriminator as a session start best-effort. On session start, the library: records session ﾎ・as active (subject to table capacity), and calls on session start(user, ﾎ・ once when the session transitions from inactive to active. 5.5.2 In-session followups (v9 ﾂｧ2.4.3) While session ﾎ・is active, any unsolicited unit (^\\) whose ] is pair-shaped and has fractional discriminator .ﾎ・is delivered as in-session via on unsolicited in session, with unit.session n = ﾎ・ 5.5.3 End of session (v9 ﾂｧ2.4.4) If an in-session unsolicited unit窶冱 final content line carries the stale marker on its ] (i.e., !ﾎ.ﾎ拆), the library ends the session after delivering the unit: calls on session end(user, ﾎ・ by timeout=false), marks the session inactive. 5.5.4 Nonexistent session (v9 ﾂｧ2.4.4 + ﾂｧ6.7) If an unsolicited unit is labeled with .ﾎ・but session ﾎ・is not active, the library: emits BC META ERR NON EXISTENT SESSION with ctx- session n = ﾎ・ and drops the unit (it is not delivered to application callbacks). Library policy note: v9 defines a nonexistent session policy knob; this library currently behaves as if it is fixed to DROP (no pass-through mode). 5.5.5 Invalid session declaration / termination (v9 ﾂｧ6.6, ﾂｧ6.8) The library emits non-fatal diagnostics for per-line protocol violations: BC META ERR INVALID SESSION DECL when a fractional discriminator appears in a context disallowed by v9 (e.g., command carries ﾎ.ﾎ拆, negative response carries ﾎ.ﾎ拆 not in reserved busy-refusal form, etc.). BC META ERR INVALID SESSION TERMINATION when ! is applied to an integer-only ] (!ﾎ]). These diagnostics do not automatically reset parser/meta state and do not necessarily prevent unit delivery (unless another rule causes the unit to be dropped). 5.6 Parser reset event handling (v9 ﾂｧ5.1) When the SAB parser reports a reset event, the library MUST: discard any partially buffered packet state, discard any buffered header-prefix run not yet attached to a delivered unit, clear direct-response bookkeeping, clear request and session tracking state, reset the managed outbound primary sequence to 0 if tx manage primary seq is enabled, and then call on reset(user, is ack). No deliverable unit is produced for a reset. Payload capture semantics (library-specific) 6.1 Line payload fields Each delivered bcode line t exposes: payload tag (BC PAYLOAD NONE, BC PAYLOAD STRING, BC PAYLOAD BINARY) payload len = number of payload bytes observed on-wire for that line (sum over payload bodies) payload = pointer to captured bytes, or NULL. Important: payload len 0 does not imply payload != NULL. payload may be NULL if capture is disabled (rx payload bytes == 0) or if capture overflow caused the line/unit to be dropped. 6.2 Capture pool The library maintains a single RX payload capture pool of capacity rx payload bytes bytes. The pool is used to store payload bytes for buffered headers and buffered packet lines, and for the currently building line. The pool is reset when a unit is delivered and after aborting a packet/unit. 6.3 Payload overflow handling If the library cannot capture a line窶冱 full payload body into the RX pool (pool capacity exceeded while building that line): Emit BC META ERR PAYLOAD OVERFLOW. Drop the affected line/unit. If a multiline packet was in progress, abort and drop the entire packet. Clear any buffered header-prefix run. Continue parsing subsequent lines (resynchronization is at the SAB line boundary). Separately, while buffering a multiline packet, if rx payload bytes != 0 and the cumulative payload bytes across buffered packet lines would exceed rx payload bytes, the library emits BC META ERR PAYLOAD OVERFLOW and drops the packet. Resynchronization and 窶彭ropped窶・signaling (library-specific) For hard drops (packet malformed, packet limit, payload overflow, nonexistent session, etc.), the unit is not delivered; meta clears its buffered state and continues processing subsequent lines. For soft drops where only header-prefix metadata is discarded at the moment of unit delivery (e.g., an incomplete header run or a coupling failure), the content unit is delivered without headers and with BC META UNIT F DROPPED set. Header-prefix runs that are discarded earlier (for example due to rx max header lines overflow while collecting headers) are not necessarily reflected via BC META UNIT F DROPPED. The library does not currently implement a v9 drop sink diagnostic tap; dropped units are observable only via on meta error and, when applicable, BC META UNIT F DROPPED. TX semantics (library-specific, v9-compatible) 8.1 TX lifecycle TX is single-flight: 1) bcode meta tx begin(kind, request line, session n) 2) bcode meta tx push header line() / bcode meta tx push line() to stage lines 3) bcode meta tx size() finalizes decoration and returns required serialized bytes 4) bcode meta tx write(buf) serializes 5) bcode meta tx complete(success) commits or discards bookkeeping and releases staged state 8.2 TX limits If staging exceeds TX capacities (tx max header lines, tx max multiline lines, tx payload bytes), TX APIs return BC META ERR TX LIMIT or report BC META ERR TX LIMIT via on meta error as appropriate. 8.3 Managed primary sequence (tx manage primary seq) If enabled, the library stamps/advances integer primary ] for what it transmits and commits that advancement only on tx complete(success=true). On parser reset, it resets this managed primary sequence to 0. 8.4 TX in-session validation If TX kind is IN SESSION, the provided session n MUST correspond to an active session. Otherwise bcode meta tx begin() returns BC META ERR NON EXISTENT SESSION. 8.5 Direct-response expectation on TX failure If an outbound command 窶彳xpects a direct response窶・and the application calls tx complete(success=false), the library MUST call: on direct response(user, NULL) exactly once for that failed request. A command is considered 窶彳xpects direct response窶・only if every staged content line carried the same explicit nonnegative integer ] prior to tx size(). Mapping: v9 events/policies 竊・bcode meta surface 9.1 v9 events v9 event name Library exposure --- --- E SEQ MISMATCH on meta error(BC META ERR SEQ MISMATCH); unit still delivered E SESSION START(ﾎ・ on session start(ﾎ・ (best-effort if request tracking disabled) E SESSION END(ﾎ・ on session end(ﾎ・ by timeout=false) E SESSION END(ﾎ・ timeout) on session end(ﾎ・ by timeout=true) (requires bcode meta tick) E NON EXISTENT SESSION(ﾎ・ on meta error(BC META ERR NON EXISTENT SESSION); unit dropped E INVALID SESSION DECL on meta error(BC META ERR INVALID SESSION DECL) (non-fatal) E INVALID SESSION TERMINATION on meta error(BC META ERR INVALID SESSION TERMINATION) (non-fatal) E HEADER START / E HEADER TO CONTENT Not exposed as dedicated callbacks; headers only appear attached on delivered units Parser reset event on reset(is ack) 9.2 v9 policy knobs v9 defines standardized knob names; this library窶冱 current support is: session idle timeout (ﾎ煩・ 竊・supported via rx enable session timeout, rx session timeout ms, and bcode meta tick(). seq mismatch policy 竊・fixed behavior equivalent to LOG ONLY. nonexistent session policy 竊・fixed behavior equivalent to DROP. drop sink 竊・not implemented. allow ephemeral interjection 竊・not configurable (library parses ? and supports reserved busy refusal handling; higher layers must enforce any disable policy). ephemeral sessionless policy 竊・not applicable (since allow/deny is not implemented here). Conformance and deviations An implementation MAY claim conformance to BCODe.meta Convention v9 only if it implements all v9-required on-wire behaviors it claims to support. Known deliberate library-level constraints: No configurable pass-through for nonexistent sessions (always drop). No drop sink export path. rx payload bytes is overloaded as both capture-pool capacity and, when nonzero, per-packet payload budget."}, {"slug": "rest", "display_title": "BCODe.rest (v6.1.3)", "preview_title": "BCODe_rest_Convention.updated.v6.1.3 窶・Local Preview", "description": "BCODe.rest 窶・Process Control Convention over BCODe Streams (Draft) Document date: 2026-02-10 Status: Draft convention (built on BCODe syntax + interpretation + BCODe.meta) Revision: v6.1.3 (v6.1.2 + align <c u?", "corpus_text": "BCODe.rest 窶・Process Control Convention over BCODe Streams (Draft) Document date: 2026-02-10 Status: Draft convention (built on BCODe syntax + interpretation + BCODe.meta) Revision: v6.1.3 (v6.1.2 + align <c unsolicited follow-ons with updated BCODe.meta session semantics) BCODe.rest (formerly PCOB) is a convention for forming simple telemetry statements and control operations. It is REST-inspired in the Representation State Transfer sense, but is designed for streams (serial ports, TCP, WebSockets), not intermittent HTTP packets. BCODe.rest composes: BCODe syntax (line/field grammar) BCODe interpretation (qualifiers, quality-first accessors) BCODe.meta (responses, unsolicited updates, batching, sequencing, reset) --- Resources are the semantic anchor BCODe.rest is resource-oriented. The resource ID is fundamental to decoding the meaning of BCODe.rest lines. 1.1 Resource ID format (64-bit) The resource ID is the integer part of the command field: upper 32 bits: IANA PEN (namespacing by entity) lower 32 bits: resource identifier within that namespace 1.2 Publishing rule (industrial-grade interoperability) Any party that publishes a BCODe.rest specification intended for third-party use MUST: obtain an IANA PEN, and place it in the upper 32 bits of all published resource IDs. 1.3 PEN=0 means 窶彗d-hoc窶・A PEN value of 0 designates a resource ID as ad-hoc : the meaning is not discoverable via registry lookup, and requires full contextual information (local docs, source, out-of-band agreement). This is intentional to streamline tinkering, prototypes, and early development. 1.4 Appropriated defunct PENs (TBD standard resources) IANA PEN numbers 5, 6, 7, 8 are assigned to defunct entities and are appropriated by convention for future standard resource definitions (TBD) . --- Resource lookup (discovery) When a user encounters an unknown resource ID, the upper 32-bit PEN can be used as a discovery hook: 1) Extract upper 32-bit PEN 2) Look up the PEN in the IANA PEN registry 3) Extract a domain name from the registry contact email (substring after @) 4) Fetch a discovery endpoint: Format is TBD, but the goal is that an AI (or a tool) can fetch a structured map that describes: resource IDs and their record layouts, parameter meanings (A..Z) for those resources, command meanings and examples, and units/ranges if applicable. Recommendation: cache lookup results and pin by version/hash for reproducibility. --- Indexing (@) The @ parameter identifies a particular instance of a resource within a system. integer part: instance index (0,1,2,窶ｦ) fractional part (optional): additional hierarchy level (application-defined) Example: --- Command letters (operation categories) BCODe.rest uses the lowercase command letter to identify an operation category. Current reserved set (summary): 4.1 Reads a 窶・read dynamic dataset (idempotent; may be stale) e 窶・read static dataset (idempotent; cacheable during resource lifetime; never stale) 4.2 Data mutation b 窶・stored data update/readback (idempotent; PUT-ish) <b = update stored/initialized values using supplied parameters (atomic) b = return previously written or initialized values d 窶・delta change to stored data (non-idempotent; atomic; quantized to closest realizable; rejects out-of-range) 4.3 Actions c 窶・control action with side effects (non-idempotent) <c = execute action c = admission-check only (NOP; same response as <c) 4.4 Other reserved categories f 窶・data feeds and logged events (streaming + buffered playback + release) i 窶・allocate/deallocate (may be multi-response) Other command letters are reserved. --- Field model, lookup.json, and quality/diagnostics 5.1 lookup.json is authoritative for field layout For a given (RID, N) and operation category (a, e, b, d, c, f, i), lookup.json defines: which parameters may appear in requests and responses, the meaning and type of each field, and any enumerations (including per-field diagnostic codes, if used). 5.2 Field presence rule (unsupported vs supported-but-unavailable) For response datasets that return fields (a, e, b, and any response datasets defined for c/d): 1) Unsupported field If the device does not support a field at all, the field MUST NOT appear in the response. 2) Supported field If the device supports the field, then the field MUST appear in the response as either: a normal value , or a nonstandard (diagnostic) value-kind , optionally with a diagnostic code. This makes 窶徙mitted窶・unambiguous: omitted == unsupported. 5.3 Diagnostic value-kinds and optional diagnostic codes If a supported field cannot be returned as a normal value (unknown, pending, invalid, not yet initialized, etc.), the responder MUST return a diagnostic value-kind for that parameter (as defined by BCODe interpretation). If the implementation can provide a specific reason, it MAY attach a nonnegative integer diagnostic code (meaning defined in lookup.json for that (RID,N,field)). Receivers MUST treat unknown diagnostic codes as opaque integers. 5.4 Stale modifier ! The stale modifier ! is an orthogonal qualifier defined by BCODe interpretation. BCODe.rest constrains when stale is allowed: Allowed on parameter fields: a (dynamic read) Forbidden on parameter fields: e (static read) Recommended forbidden on parameter fields: b and d (stored-state operations), unless lookup.json explicitly states otherwise. Allowed on the command field (statement-level) for feeds only: unsolicited f and unsolicited f MAY use ! on the command field to signal global buffer pressure, and MUST use it under the global-saturation condition defined in ﾂｧ8.6.6.1 (see ﾂｧ8.6.6). Unless explicitly defined by this specification, ! on a command field is undefined and SHOULD be ignored by receivers. 5.5 Feed-status command qualifiers ! and ? For unsolicited feed statements (f and f), BCODe.rest defines two statement-level qualifiers that MUST be attached to the command field , not to any parameter field: ! on the command field 窶・the device is in a global buffer-saturated state (see ﾂｧ8.6.6.1). ? on the command field 窶・the specific resource has experienced buffer overflow data loss (see ﾂｧ8.6.6.2). These qualifiers MAY appear together on the same command field. When both are present, the recommended order is !? (e.g., !?#...f), but receivers SHOULD accept either order. These meanings apply only to the command field of unsolicited feed statements. On parameter fields, ? retains its normal BCODe interpretation meaning (unknown/diagnostic value-kind). --- Sequences and ordinals (N, /R, R) 6.1 Command sequence N The fractional portion of the command field is the command sequence number N. N selects the dataset/stage the command refers to. BCODe.rest deliberately uses N as a stable selector so the meaning of A..Z does not need to change when the protocol evolves. 6.2 Request ordinal R via /R (requests only) BCODe syntax supports an exponent suffix ( or /) on a number field. In BCODe.rest, the divisor suffix /R on the command field is reserved for request-line ordinals within a [-batched multiline request packet. R is a nonnegative integer identifier; treat its digits as an identifier (not float math). Implementations MUST NOT use R on request lines. Rules: For single-line requests, /0 is implied and MAY be omitted. For multiline request packets, every line MUST include /R, and all /R values within the packet MUST be distinct. /R values SHOULD be contiguous starting at 0 (/0, /1, ...). Devices MAY reject non-contiguous ordinals as malformed. Parameter meaning MUST NOT depend on the [ framing line index; it depends on (RID,@,N,command letter, verb qualifier, /R). 6.3 Response ordinal R via R (responses only) The exponent suffix R on the command field is reserved for responses (direct responses ^ or \\, and unsolicited follow-ons ^\\): R is a response ordinal identifier associated with request sequence N. Implementations MUST NOT use /R on response lines. This is intentionally designed so that: you can add additional response datasets later without shifting N, and response meaning does not depend on whether [ batching is used. 6.4 Response ordinal rules The direct response to a request MUST use 0. If the direct response is multiline, it MUST be batched with [ and MUST use distinct ordinals 0, 1, 2, 窶ｦ across its lines. Later updates are unsolicited (see ﾂｧ7) and may use any ordinal value. 6.5 Ordinal repetition (progress / updates) R MAY repeat to represent incremental updates for the same stage. Example: progress updates at ordinal 2: Receivers MAY treat repeated (N,R) updates as 窶徑atest wins窶・ using timestamps and/or ] sequencing to order. --- Response vs unsolicited (BCODe.meta composition) BCODe.rest relies on BCODe.meta to distinguish: direct responses (^ or \\), versus unsolicited follow-ons (^\\). 7.1 Direct response MUST be immediate and tagged The immediate response to a command MUST be a response line (BCODe.meta): ^ for affirmative acknowledgement (accepted), or \\ for negative acknowledgement (rejected; may include an error/reason code). The response MAY carry data if the result is immediately available. If multiple lines are needed immediately, the response MUST be batched using [. 7.2 Delayed results are unsolicited and MUST include \\ If the 窶徨eal result窶・arrives later (async completion), it is not a direct response; it is an unsolicited statement and MUST include both ^ and \\ (i.e., ^\\). Delayed results MAY be batched with [. 7.3 Multiline requests (atomic delivery) Any BCODe.rest request MAY be delivered as a [-batched multiline packet per BCODe.meta. The [ line numbering (e.g., 1.3[ / 2.3[) is framing only and MUST NOT change parameter interpretation. For a multiline request packet: All lines MUST have the same base command identity (same RID, command sequence N, command letter, and </ qualifier, if any). Each line MUST include a request ordinal /R on the command field (ﾂｧ6.2). All /R values within the packet MUST be distinct . /R values SHOULD be contiguous starting at 0 (/0, /1, 窶ｦ). Devices MAY reject non-contiguous ordinals as malformed. Selector parameters such as @ and (for controls) ] MUST be present and identical across all lines. Any non-selector (payload) parameter letter MUST NOT appear more than once across the packet; duplicates make the request malformed. Selector parameters such as @ and (for controls) ] MAY repeat across lines, but their value-kind and digits MUST be identical across the packet. For <b and d, a multiline request packet represents a single atomic update transaction: the device MUST either commit all supplied updates as one unit or reject the request (no changes applied). 7.3.1 Illustrative examples The following examples show request packets that are split across multiple lines but evaluated as a single logical request. Example A 窶・fixed-bound two-line <b UPDATE (one atomic commit) Controller updates four stored fields (A, B, C, D) in one transaction: Notes: The device MUST NOT apply A/B after receiving line 1. It applies everything after validating the whole packet. Any failure (e.g., C invalid) rejects the entire <b update. Example B 窶・open-ended <b UPDATE (length not known until the end) Open-ended batching lets a controller stream a packet without knowing the total line count up front. The packet is closed by a final fixed-bound line i.t[: Notes: The device MUST buffer (or otherwise defer execution) until the closing i.t[ line arrives. If any line is missing or the counters are inconsistent, the request is malformed and MUST be rejected (no changes applied). Example C 窶・fixed-bound three-line d delta update (one atomic commit) Controller requests incremental changes to three stored values: Notes: The device applies closest realizable deltas where needed, but if the resulting value would violate bounds, it MUST reject the entire packet. The response shape is lookup-defined; this example shows absolute results but it may also include applied deltas. Example D 窶・multiline <c control with required ] (selectors must match) A control has many parameters, so the controller splits them across lines. The ] control sequence identifier MUST appear on every line and MUST match: Example E 窶・malformed multiline <b due to duplicate payload parameter Here the payload parameter A appears twice across the packet, which is ambiguous. The device MUST reject and apply nothing: Example F 窶・malformed multiline request due to selector mismatch Selector parameters must be identical across all lines. If they differ, the packet is malformed: Example G 窶・malformed multiline <c due to ] mismatch Example H 窶・malformed multiline request due to missing /R If any line in a multiline request omits /R, the packet is malformed (because parameter interpretation would depend on framing order): --- Operation semantics 8.1 Dynamic read (a) Dynamic reads are idempotent reads of the dynamic dataset for (RID,@,N). 8.1.1 Staleness is allowed Dynamic read responses MAY include stale values for supported fields. Stale is indicated using the stale modifier !. Dynamic read responses MAY mix: fresh values, stale values, diagnostic value-kinds, and omitted fields (unsupported only). 8.1.2 Failure model A dynamic read request SHOULD be accepted (^) if the request is valid, even if some or many fields are returned diagnostically. Request-level failures MUST be rejected (\\) with an a-group error code (see ﾂｧ11). --- 8.2 Static read (e) Static reads are idempotent reads of the static dataset for (RID,@,N) and are cacheable during the resource lifetime. 8.2.1 Staleness is forbidden Static read responses MUST NOT mark any returned field as stale (MUST NOT use !). If a supported static field cannot be returned as a normal value, the responder MUST return a diagnostic value-kind (optionally with a diagnostic code), not a stale value. --- 8.3 Stored data update/readback (b) 窶・idempotent b represents idempotent operations over stored or initialized values associated with (RID,@,N). 8.3.1 b READBACK b returns previously written or initialized values for supported fields defined by lookup.json. Unsupported fields MUST be omitted. Supported fields MUST be returned as a value or a diagnostic value-kind (e.g., 窶從ot yet initialized窶・, optionally with a diagnostic code. b SHOULD NOT use the stale modifier !. 8.3.2 <b UPDATE (PUT-ish) <b updates stored/initialized values using the supplied parameters. Omitted fields are not updated: If a parameter field is absent from the <b request, it MUST NOT be modified. Atomicity (never partial): <b updates are atomic. The device MUST commit all supplied parameter updates or none . Required parameters: lookup.json MAY require that a specific parameter be present for a particular (RID,N) update variant. If a required parameter is missing, the device MUST reject the update. Discouraged coupled presence: A device MAY require parameters to appear in combination (e.g., A only valid with B), though this is discouraged. If such a rule exists, it MUST be declared in lookup.json, and violations MUST reject the update. Lockout: A device MAY lock out <b updates (temporary or permanent). When locked out, the device MUST reject the update. Response payload (recommended): On acceptance, the direct response SHOULD include the resulting stored value(s) for the supplied parameters. If the resulting values are not immediately available, the direct response MAY be a bare ACK, followed later by unsolicited completion reporting using ^\\ as required by ﾂｧ7.2. --- 8.4 Delta change to stored data (d) 窶・non-idempotent d applies incremental changes to stored values without specifying exact absolute values. d is not idempotent . d updates are atomic (never partial), like <b. 8.4.1 Relationship to <b All <b update variants are conceptually expressible as d variants, but d support MAY be excluded: globally for a device, per (RID,N) variant, and/or per parameter, as declared by lookup.json and device behavior. A device that does not support d for a requested target MUST reject the command with a d-group error. 8.4.2 Delta meaning and forms For parameters that support d, the supplied numeric value represents a requested change , not an absolute target. Delta forms include: signed numeric deltas (e.g., +5, -0.25), epsilon changes (smallest realizable increment/decrement), suggested deltas (device may quantize to realizable steps). Exact encoding rules are defined by BCODe numeric interpretation and constrained by lookup.json. 8.4.3 Closest realizable change If the device cannot apply the exact requested delta, it MUST apply the closest realizable change . The applied delta becomes the effective change. Quantization vs saturation: The device determines the closest realizable change by quantizing the requested delta to a realizable increment for that parameter. The device MUST NOT 窶徭aturate窶・or clamp a request that would exceed bounds by silently reducing the delta to fit within min/max. After selecting the closest realizable change, if applying it would exceed a maximum or minimum or produce an invalid value, the request MUST be rejected and no values may change. 8.4.4 Rejection rules (no changes applied) A d request MUST be rejected (and MUST NOT change any values) if: the applied change would exceed a maximum or minimum, the resulting value would be invalid, the parameter does not support delta updates, or the update violates a declared constraint. 8.4.5 Response payload (recommended) On acceptance, the direct response SHOULD report the resulting absolute values of the modified fields and/or the applied deltas, as defined by lookup.json. If completion is delayed, use ^\\ follow-ons per ﾂｧ7.2. --- 8.5 Controls and actions (c) 窶・non-idempotent c initiates, schedules, modifies, or terminates actions with side effects . 8.5.1 Control action classes A c control MAY represent one or more of the following action classes (as defined by lookup.json for (RID,N)): Instigation 窶・cause something to happen (e.g., breaker trip) Latched action 窶・latch output/state to a target state Timed latch 窶・latch to a target state, then revert after a duration Mode change 窶・start/stop a process; transition operational modes Termination 窶・stop an action in process; cancel a scheduled action Controls MAY be immediate or time-delayed, depending on parameters and lookup.json. 8.5.2 Synchronous direct response is mandatory Every c request MUST receive an immediate direct response indicating acceptance (^) or rejection (\\). This direct response indicates acceptance/rejection of the control request , not necessarily completion. 8.5.3 Unsolicited progress/completion updates (BCODe.meta sessions) After accepting a <c request, the device MAY emit unsolicited ^\\ messages reporting: progress, state transitions, completion, cancellation, or failure. Unsolicited updates MUST be correlatable to the control instance (see ﾂｧ8.5.6). BCODe.meta session binding (normative): BCODe.rest control follow-ons are in-session unsolicited statements as defined by BCODe.meta. A control follow-on session is keyed by the requester-provided control identifier S (the integer value in the request窶冱 ] field). A device MUST NOT emit any control follow-ons for S unless it has first started session S by accepting the control request and returning an affirmative direct response whose ] field carries the fractional discriminator .S (i.e., ﾎ.S]). While session S is active, any control follow-on: MUST be tagged as unsolicited (^\\), MUST carry a ] field whose fractional component equals S (i.e., ﾎ.S]), and SHOULD use a primary sequence number ﾎ that increases monotonically. When the control reaches a terminal outcome (completed / cancelled / failed, lookup-defined), the device SHOULD end the session explicitly. The final follow-on for session S MUST mark the ] field stale to indicate end-of-session: !ﾎ.S]. Batching note (normative): Control follow-ons MAY be delivered as [-batched multiline packets. If batched, every line in the packet MUST be tagged ^\\ and MUST carry a ] field whose fractional component equals S (i.e., ﾎ.S]). If the final follow-on that ends session S is batched, the stale ! MUST be applied to the ] field of the final line of the packet (so the session terminates after the entire atomic unit is received). After a stale-terminated final follow-on (!ﾎ.S] ^\\ ... c), the device MUST NOT emit additional ^\\ lines labeled with .S. Receivers will treat later .S lines as references to a non-existent session and (by default) drop them under the BCODe.meta rules. 8.5.4 <c vs c intent qualifiers The command-field qualifier selects execution vs admission-check: <c 窶・execute the action (side effects permitted; unsolicited follow-ons permitted) c 窶・admission-check only (guaranteed NOP; no side effects; unsolicited follow-ons forbidden) 8.5.5 <c and c equivalence constraints <c and c are equivalent in parameters and validation: Parameter-equivalent: The same parameters are sent and interpreted the same way. Direct responses identical: The direct response to <c and the direct response to the corresponding c MUST be identical (same ACK/NAK and same payload fields, if any). The only difference is that c is guaranteed NOP and MUST NOT generate any unsolicited follow-on messages. Race note: A c acceptance means 窶忤ould accept now窶・ later <c execution may be rejected if device state changed. 8.5.6 Required control sequence counter ] and BCODe.meta session labeling A control request (<c or c) MUST include a sequence counter field ] (request control identifier). The request ] value MUST be a nonnegative integer identifier (no sign and no fractional digits). The intent is that its decimal digits can be echoed verbatim as the BCODe.meta session discriminator in accepted responses and follow-ons. Let the requester-provided control identifier be S (the request ] integer). Lexical rules: S is an identifier. The requester SHOULD generate S as a monotonically increasing integer (wrap-around permitted). Requesters SHOULD avoid leading zeros. Responders echo the canonical decimal digits of S when forming .S in their ] field. If a responder cannot echo all digits of S in the fractional portion of its ] field, it MUST reject the control request as malformed. Uniqueness (single controller): BCODe.rest assumes a single controller per device. The controller MUST NOT reuse an S value while the corresponding BCODe.meta session S may still be active (i.e., while follow-ons could still be emitted for that control). If the device ends the session explicitly using a stale-marked ] follow-on (!ﾎ.S]), the controller MAY reuse S only after observing that termination. If the device does not end sessions explicitly, controllers MUST apply a conservative local policy (e.g., timeouts) before reusing S to avoid ambiguity. Direct response rules (normative): Accepted control: The direct response MUST be affirmative (^) and MUST start BCODe.meta session S by including a ] field whose fractional component equals S (i.e., ﾎ.S]). If the direct response is multiline (batched with [), every line in the response packet MUST carry a ] field whose fractional component equals S (i.e., ﾎ.S]). Rejected control: The direct response MUST be negative (\\) and MUST NOT carry a fractional ] component (i.e., it MUST NOT use ﾎ.S]). Follow-on rules (normative): For an accepted control whose direct response started session S: Any later unsolicited progress/completion/cancellation/failure message for that control MUST be sent as an in-session unsolicited statement (^\\) carrying ] = ﾎ.S] (fractional discriminator equals S). If a follow-on is multiline (batched with [), every line in the follow-on packet MUST carry a ] field whose fractional component equals S. The final unsolicited statement for that control MUST mark the ] field stale to indicate end-of-session: !ﾎ.S]. If the final follow-on is multiline, the stale ! MUST appear on the ] field of the final line of that final packet. Note on !: The ! used here is a stale qualifier on the meta ] field (session termination). It is distinct from the BCODe.rest command-field stale ! used only for unsolicited feed buffer-saturation signaling (ﾂｧ8.6.6). --- 8.6 Data feeds and logged events (f) The f category provides a unified model for: live streaming feed data (unsolicited push), and buffered/logged event playback (unsolicited push of historical records), with an explicit release mechanism so devices with finite buffers can discard delivered records safely. There are three on-wire forms: f, f, and <f. 8.6.1 Forms and roles f (unqualified) f is used in two roles: 1) Requester-to-device command requests that manage feeds and request playback. 2) Device-to-requester unsolicited live feed updates (streaming data). f (buffered playback) f is emitted by the device as unsolicited buffered/logged records (historical playback). It is not used for requester-issued commands. <f (release) <f is a requester-issued command that releases buffered/logged records from device storage. Release is referenced by the record identifier carried on the corresponding f / f unsolicited records in the BCODe.meta ^ field (ﾂｧ8.6.3). 8.6.2 Unsolicited feed statements are correlated to a (dynamic read) All unsolicited feed statements (f live updates and f buffered playback) MUST correlate with the dynamic dataset accessible by the a command: The (RID,@,N) tuple on an unsolicited feed statement identifies the same dataset addressed by an a read. Any parameter fields present in the feed statement MUST have the same meaning as the corresponding fields in the a dataset for that (RID,@,N). Feed statements MAY contain a subset of fields (e.g., only changed values). Receivers MAY issue a reads to obtain a full snapshot. In other words, unsolicited f/ f statements are a push representation of dynamic read data, not a separate schema. 8.6.3 Required record identifier in the ^ field All unsolicited feed statements (both f and f) MUST include a BCODe.meta ^ field. If the device supports a per-record identifier, it MUST encode that identifier as the numeric value immediately preceding ^ (or ^\\). This numeric value is the record identifier K. When present, K is the reference used by <f release commands. For a given feed stream identified by (RID,@,N), the device MUST emit unsolicited feed records in a well-defined order for that stream. In timestamp mode (ﾂｧ8.6.3.1), K MUST be strictly increasing in that transmission order. In event-identifier mode (ﾂｧ8.6.3.2), K MUST uniquely identify retained records and continuity MUST be representable using the (E,P) rule. A device MAY choose to make K monotonic across all feed streams as well, but this is not required. lookup.json MUST document the meaning of K for each (RID,@,N) feed stream, including: timebase/units/epoch (if time-based), wrap/reset behavior, and whether event identifiers are stream-scoped or globally allocated. 8.6.3.1 Timestamp mode (recommended: Unix Epoch) In timestamp mode, K represents a time value (wall-clock, monotonic uptime, or boot-count+uptime) as documented in lookup.json. Devices SHOULD synchronize to Unix Epoch time (e.g., seconds or milliseconds since 1970-01-01T00:00:00Z). Most devices will not have an atomic clock; receivers SHOULD assume that timestamp accuracy depends on periodic external synchronization (e.g., NTP, GPS) and/or an onboard RTC. Timestamp-quality qualifiers on the ^ field: ? 窶・time convergence pending (e.g., NTP convergence, GPS acquiring fix). K is monotonic, but wall-clock accuracy is not yet guaranteed. -? 窶・time synchronization failed (e.g., RTC lost time, time source unreachable). K is present, but accuracy may be poor or drifting. ?< 窶・no time synchronization configured . K is present but SHOULD be treated as a local monotonic timebase, not authoritative wall-clock. ! 窶・time possibly stale (the synchronization interval has been exceeded; drift is possible). Rules: A device in timestamp mode MUST ensure that K does not decrease for a given (RID,@,N) stream in the order records are transmitted. If wall-clock time would step backward, the device MUST either delay emission, slew using a monotonic timebase, or switch to event-identifier mode (ﾂｧ8.6.3.2). ! MUST NOT be combined with ? or ?< on the same ^ field. A device MAY default its startup clock to Epoch 0 (common in embedded Linux). If doing so, it SHOULD tag ^ with ? until synchronization is achieved. 8.6.3.1.1 Boot-count + uptime model (limited devices) Some devices cannot maintain wall-clock time across power loss, but can: count startups/resets using a persistent counter (e.g., stored in nonvolatile memory), and measure runtime while powered (uptime). In this model, the ^ record identifier K is encoded as a number pair : Where: B is a boot sequence identifier (a monotonically increasing counter across device startups; wrap-around permitted). U is the uptime since that boot in units documented in lookup.json (e.g., milliseconds). Rules: For a given (RID,@,N) stream, successive (B,U) pairs in the order transmitted MUST be strictly increasing under lexicographic ordering: B2 B1, or B2 == B1 and U2 U1. B MUST change when the device restarts (a new boot), and U MUST restart near 0 for that boot. Within a boot, U MUST be monotonic for the stream in transmission order. If the counter used for U may wrap during continuous operation, the device MUST prevent K from decreasing by either: using a sufficiently wide uptime counter for the intended operational window, or incrementing B when U wraps (treating wrap as a new boot epoch). Recommendation: Devices using this model SHOULD tag the ^ field with ?< to indicate that no authoritative wall-clock synchronization is configured. Receiver guidance (non-normative): Receivers MAY correlate (B,U) to local time by recording the receiver's local time when a new B value is first observed and then treating subsequent records for that same B as offset by U. Time while the device is powered off is not represented by this model. 8.6.3.2 Event-identifier mode for timestamp-less buffered logs (^!) A device that supports buffered/logged playback but cannot produce a usable timestamp MAY operate in event-identifier mode . In this mode, the ^ field MUST be tagged with ! and the numeric preceding ^ MUST be a number pair : Where: E is the identifier of the current event record. P is the identifier of the previous event record for the same (RID,@,N) stream at the time the record was created. Rules: E and P are identifiers. Receivers MUST treat their digits as identifiers (not float math; not wall-clock time). E values SHOULD be unique among all currently retained records for that stream (and MAY be globally unique across streams). For a healthy continuous stream, each successive record SHOULD satisfy P == E prev. If the device knows records were discarded due to overflow, it MUST signal loss using the command-field loss qualifier ? (ﾂｧ8.6.6.2). On the first record after a stream reset or at a buffer boundary where no previous record is available, the device MUST set P == E (self-reference). Restrictions: ?, -?, and ?< MUST NOT be used on the ^ field in this mode. 8.6.3.3 Bare-^ mode (no per-record identifier) Devices that do not support any per-record identifier MAY emit the ^ field with no numeric value. Such statements are orderable only by transport sequence. Devices operating in this mode MUST NOT emit buffered playback statements ( f) and MUST reject <f release requests with -102.4 (feed/log operation not supported for this (RID,@,N); no releasable buffer exists). 8.6.4 Enabling and disabling streaming (requests using f) Requester-issued f commands enable or disable streaming of unsolicited live feed data for a resource. The exact parameter set for enabling/disabling (and any rate, filter, or mode selection) is defined by lookup.json. Devices SHOULD support disabling a feed to reduce bandwidth and buffer pressure. A successful enable does not imply that the device has buffered historical data; it only controls future live streaming. 8.6.5 Buffered playback and release 8.6.5.1 Requesting playback of unreleased buffered data (requests using f) A requester-issued f command MAY request the device to transmit any unreleased buffered/logged records for that resource. Transmission of buffered data is performed by emitting unsolicited f statements. Transmission does NOT imply release. Buffered records remain stored until explicitly released by <f. lookup.json MAY define parameters for requesting playback within a window, selecting a replay mode, or otherwise controlling replay. The log stream itself is identified by the standard selectors (RID,@,N). 8.6.5.2 Buffered records ( f) are unsolicited and identified All f buffered records: MUST be sent as unsolicited statements (^\\), MUST carry the required ^ record identifier (ﾂｧ8.6.3), and MUST use the same data field meanings as a (ﾂｧ8.6.2). 8.6.5.3 Releasing buffered records (<f) Release is the only mechanism by which the requester authorizes the device to discard buffered/logged records. Devices MUST NOT treat 窶徭uccessfully transmitted窶・as 窶徨eleased窶・implicitly. A requester releases buffered records by issuing a <f command that includes one or more release selector fields. BCODe.rest reserves parameter letters for <f release: A 窶・the primary release selector (required for all <f release requests) B 窶・optional secondary selector (used only for range release; see ﾂｧ8.6.5.3.2) lookup.json MUST NOT redefine A or B for <f release semantics. Additional parameters MAY be defined by lookup.json for device-specific release modes, provided they do not change the interpretation of A and B. The numeric value(s) carried on release selectors refer to record identifiers previously observed in the ^ field of unsolicited feed records for the targeted (RID,@,N) stream (ﾂｧ8.6.3). 8.6.5.3.1 Single-event release (happy path; required for ^! timestamp-less logs) In event-identifier mode (^!, ﾂｧ8.6.3.2), a requester releases a specific buffered record by including a selector in parameter A of the form: On-wire this is written as a single field whose label is A, e.g. !1234,1233A. Rules: 1) If event E is retained for the targeted (RID,@,N) stream and any supplied preconditions are satisfied, the device MUST release that record and MUST respond with acceptance (^). 2) If event E is not retained because it was already released , the device MAY: respond with acceptance (^) to preserve idempotent 窶彗lready done窶・semantics, or reject with -102.13 (Event not found / already released). If a device chooses one behavior, it MUST apply it consistently for that (RID,@,N) and document the behavior in lookup.json. 3) If the request supplies (E,P) and the supplied P does not match the retained metadata for event E, the device MUST reject with -102.14 (Release precondition failed) and MUST NOT release any records. 4) If the request does not uniquely identify a single release target (malformed selector token, missing required ! in event-identifier mode, or conflicting selectors), the device MUST reject with -102.17. 8.6.5.3.2 Range release (optional optimization) As an optimization, devices MAY support bulk release by identifier range. If supported, the requester specifies an upper bound using A and MAY specify a lower bound using B. The exact range model (inclusive/exclusive endpoints, allowed forms, and wrap behavior) MUST be documented in lookup.json. If range release is not supported, the device MUST reject range-release requests with -102.16 (Range release not supported). 8.6.5.3.3 Retention-model safety If the requested release would discard records outside the device窶冱 supported retention model, the device MUST reject the command (no changes applied) using -102.11 (Release rejected). 8.6.6 Buffer pressure and data loss signaling on feed commands To support robust loss detection with finite buffers, unsolicited feed statements MUST carry command-field qualifiers under the conditions below. Important: These qualifiers MUST be attached to the command field , not to any parameter field (ﾂｧ5.5). 8.6.6.1 Global buffer saturation 竍・command-level stale ! If buffered data on any resource in the device has reached its maximum buffer limit (i.e., at least one buffer cannot accept more data), then all unsolicited f and all unsolicited f statements emitted by the device MUST bear the stale qualifier ! on the command field. This ! indicates the device is globally buffer-saturated and unsolicited feeds should be treated as potentially stale/at-risk. The ! qualifier MUST NOT be cleared until all buffers for all resources have available capacity to buffer more data. 8.6.6.2 Per-resource overflow discard 竍・command-level loss ? If buffered data for a particular resource was discarded due to overflow, then unsolicited feed statements for that resource MUST bear the loss qualifier ? on the command field: Applies to both unsolicited live feed statements (f) and unsolicited buffered playback statements ( f) for that resource. The ? overflow/loss condition is latched and can only be cleared by a requester-issued f command that targets that resource (i.e., an explicit feed management request). 8.6.6.3 Combined qualifiers If both global saturation and per-resource loss apply, both qualifiers MUST be attached to the command field (e.g., !?...f). 8.6.7 Direct responses to feed commands Direct responses to requester-issued f and <f commands follow normal BCODe.meta rules: accepted: ^ rejected: \\ with an error code Unsolicited feed statements are not direct responses and MUST be emitted as ^\\ statements (consistent with ﾂｧ7.2). --- Worked examples 9.1 Immediate single-line ACK with data (read) 9.2 Immediate multiline ACK (atomic batch) 9.3 Direct ACK now, unsolicited completion later 9.4 <b atomic update (idempotent PUT-ish) 9.5 d delta update (non-idempotent) 9.6 c admission check then <c execute, correlated by ] 9.7 Live feeds, buffered playback, and release (f, f, <f) --- Instantiation and instance lifetime (i) BCODe.rest uses the @ parameter to select a specific instance of a resource. For instantiable resource types, instances are created and destroyed via the reserved command letter i. This section defines the on-wire semantics for i so that @ addressing is implementable and grep-friendly. 10.1 Terminology RID : the 64-bit resource ID in the integer part of the command field (PEN<<32 id32). Instance selector : the @ parameter value (index 0 in the parameter array). Instance key : (RID, @). 10.2 i verb selection via command-field qualifier For the i operation category, the command-field qualifier selects the verb: ... i 竍・ALLOCATE (instantiate / create) < ... i 竍・DEALLOCATE (destroy) no < or qualifier 竍・MANAGEMENT (idempotent control-plane for allocation policy) This is intentionally designed so that allocation and deallocation are easily discoverable by text search. 10.3 Allocation/deallocation variants via command sequence N The command sequence selector N (fractional digits of the command field) is reserved for variant selection within the allocate/deallocate category. For i and <i, N MAY be used to select different argument sets or behaviors (constructor/destructor variants). Receivers MUST treat the fractional digits as an identifier, not float math. Reserved: N=0 is reserved for allocation policy gating (see ﾂｧ10.5). It MUST use unqualified i (MANAGEMENT). 10.4 @ rules for instantiation 10.4.1 Allocate ( i) If @ is present with a numeric value: it is a requested instance selector. If @ is absent: it is a request for a responder-assigned instance selector. The responder MAY reject if responder-assigned instance IDs are not supported for that RID. 10.4.2 Deallocate (<i) @ MUST be present with a numeric value selecting the instance to destroy. 10.4.3 Type-scope selector (@ = NULL) Some i MANAGEMENT operations and e listings address the resource type , not a particular instance. This is expressed by providing @ with a NULL value-kind (as defined by BCODe interpretation; commonly written < ?@). 10.5 Allocation policy gating (MANAGEMENT, unqualified i, N=0) Because allocation/deallocation have side-effects, implementations SHOULD support an explicit enable/disable gate. A gate-control request is: command letter: i (unqualified; MANAGEMENT) command sequence: N=0 @: SHOULD be NULL (type-scope) to avoid ambiguity Parameters: A (boolean): enable allocation ( i) B (boolean): enable deallocation (<i) C (boolean): permanence/lock flag If C=1, subsequent wire attempts to change gates MUST be rejected. Implementations MAY allow an application-local mechanism to unlock gates. Example: enable allocation, disable deallocation, lock policy: 10.6 Allocation timestamp tracking Implementations SHOULD record an allocation timestamp for each successfully created instance key (RID,@). The representation is implementation-defined (wall-clock or monotonic), but MUST be stable for ordering. This timestamp is used for: diagnostic listing (see ﾂｧ10.7), and global deallocation ordering (see ﾂｧ10.8). 10.7 Instance listing (idempotent) via e at type-scope Instance enumeration is idempotent , so it is expressed as an e read, not as an i verb. Request: command letter: e RID: the resource type @: NULL (type-scope) Response: SHOULD be batched with [ if multiple instances are returned. Each line SHOULD include: the instance selector @ (numeric), and T parameter: allocation timestamp (see ﾂｧ10.6). Example: 10.8 Global deallocate-all (optional) Some systems require a 窶徼ear down all instances窶・mechanism. A global deallocate-all request is: command letter: i verb: DEALLOCATE (< qualifier) @: NULL (type-scope) command field numeric: MAY be empty (no RID specified) to mean 窶彗ll RIDs窶・Example: Ordering rule: Instances MUST be deallocated in reverse allocation timestamp order (most recent first), across all RIDs. If timestamps are equal, implementations MAY break ties by (RID,@) ordering. --- Error reporting (wire: value on \\) BCODe.rest defines a provisional error registry for the numeric value carried on the \\ response line. To keep the main spec readable: human-friendly: keep full error tables in an appendix machine-friendly: publish a JSON and/or a C header (e.g., bcode rest errors.h) 11.0 Grouping rules Subcode digits are identifiers. Treat the fractional digits as an identifier (subcode), not float math. 11.0.1 Reserved groups -1 is reserved for BCODe.meta errors (framing/meta commands). -95 is reserved for BCODe.rest generic errors that are not scoped to a specific command letter. Devices MUST NOT use -1 or -95 for command-scoped errors. 11.0.2 Standard command-scoped groups For errors scoped to a specific command letter, the group SHOULD be the negative decimal value of the command letter (ASCII): a 竍・-97 b 竍・-98 c 竍・-99 d 竍・-100 e 竍・-101 f 竍・-102 i 竍・-105 11.0.3 Device-specific command-scoped groups (optional) A device MAY publish device-specific command-scoped groups by subtracting 1000 from the standard command-scoped group. Example: Standard d group is -100 Device-specific d group is -1100 So a device-specific d subcode .10 would be reported as -1100.10\\ instead of -100.10\\ . If device-specific groups are used, they MUST be documented in the device窶冱 lookup.json (including subcode meanings). --- 11.1 Baseline request-level subcodes (recommended minimum) The following subcodes are recommended minimums for all operation categories (both standard command-scoped groups and their optional device-specific -1000 offsets). Where applicable, the same subcodes MAY also be used under the generic -95 group: .1 Malformed request (syntax/shape invalid for this (RID,N)). .2 Invalid/unknown (RID,@). .3 Access denied. .4 Operation not supported for this target. .5 Temporarily unavailable / busy (retry may succeed). --- 11.2 <b UPDATE error subcodes (required minimum) Because <b updates are atomic, failures MUST reject the request (no changes applied). Group: standard -98 ; device-specific -1098 (if declared in lookup.json). If using the device-specific group, substitute -1098 for -98 in the codes below. -98.1 Malformed update / illegal parameter set. -98.10 Missing required parameter. -98.11 Invalid required combination (discouraged coupled presence). -98.12 Value rejected (invalid / out-of-range / unparseable). -98.20 Update locked out (policy / interlock / safety gate). -98.22 Conflict / resource busy (atomic commit not possible now). -98.23 Commit failed (internal error; no changes applied). --- 11.3 d delta update error subcodes (required minimum) Because d updates are atomic, failures MUST reject the request (no changes applied). Group: standard -100 ; device-specific -1100 (if declared in lookup.json). If using the device-specific group, substitute -1100 for -100 in the codes below. -100.1 Malformed delta request / illegal parameter set. -100.10 Parameter or variant does not support delta updates. -100.11 Change would exceed max/min. -100.12 Change would produce invalid value. -100.20 Delta updates locked out. -100.22 Conflict / resource busy. -100.23 Commit failed (internal; no changes applied). --- 11.4 c control error subcodes (required minimum) Group: standard -99 ; device-specific -1099 (if declared in lookup.json). If using the device-specific group, substitute -1099 for -99 in the codes below. -99.1 Malformed control request / illegal parameter set. -99.20 Control locked out (policy / interlock / safety state). -99.21 Illegal state transition / action not valid in current mode. -99.22 Conflict / action already in progress / resource busy. -99.30 Missing required control sequence counter ]. --- 11.5 f feed/log error subcodes (recommended minimum) f-group errors cover requester-issued f and <f requests. Group: standard -102 ; device-specific -1102 (if declared in lookup.json). If using the device-specific group, substitute -1102 for -102 in the codes below. -102.1 Malformed feed/log request / illegal parameter set. -102.4 Feed/log operation not supported for this (RID,@,N) (including 窶從o buffer exists窶・where required). -102.5 Temporarily unavailable / busy. -102.10 Invalid identifier range (min/max invalid or unsupported for the stream窶冱 ^ mode). -102.11 Release rejected (requested release would violate retention model or is otherwise invalid). -102.12 Playback request rejected (cannot transmit buffered data now). -102.13 Event not found / already released. A single-event <f release referenced an event ID that is not present in the retained buffer for the targeted (RID,@,N) stream. -102.14 Release precondition failed (previous-ID mismatch). The <f request provided an event identifier pair (E,P) (event-identifier mode), but the retained metadata for event E does not match the supplied P. No records were released. -102.15 Single-event release not supported. Device supports buffered playback for this (RID,@,N) but does not support per-event release; only range release (or other lookup-defined release semantics) is supported. -102.16 Range release not supported. Device supports single-event release for this (RID,@,N) but does not support bulk min/max release semantics. -102.17 Release target ambiguous / invalid selector. The <f request does not uniquely identify a release target under the rules for this (RID,@,N) (e.g., missing required A selector, missing required ! tag in event-identifier mode, malformed selector token, or conflicting selectors). --- 11.6 Errors for i i-category errors MUST use error group -105 (standard) or -1105 (device-specific, if declared in lookup.json). Subcodes are defined in bcode rest errors.h and are carried as fractional identifier digits on the numeric value of \\. --- End of document."}, {"slug": "best-practices", "display_title": "Best Practices", "preview_title": "BCODe_Best_Practices_and_Conventions_Draft_v13 窶・Preview", "description": "BCODe Best Practices & Conventions (Draft) Document date: 2026-02-02 Audience: protocol designers, firmware implementers, host/tool implementers Applies to: BCODe (lowercase e ) streams over serial ports, TCP,?", "corpus_text": "BCODe Best Practices & Conventions (Draft) Document date: 2026-02-02 Audience: protocol designers, firmware implementers, host/tool implementers Applies to: BCODe (lowercase e ) streams over serial ports, TCP, WebSockets, pipes, and similar byte streams. Companion specs (syntax + standard interpretations): BCODe Syntax Specification (Draft, 2026-01-30) 訷filecite訷Ｕurn3file0訷・BCODe Value Interpretation (Draft, 2026-01-30) 訷filecite訷Ｕurn3file1訷・--- Purpose BCODe is a small, streaming, ASCII protocol designed to make simple telemetry and control : easy to generate (even with plain printf-style output), easy to transport over streams, easy to inspect, filter, and debug with commodity tooling (logs, grep, etc.), and easy to parse deterministically in constrained environments. The tradeoff is intentional: BCODe is not a general-purpose document format. It is optimized for flat, line-oriented statements with a strict upper bound of 32 parameter identities . If you need nested objects, arbitrary key naming, schema evolution within the payload, or tree-shaped data models, BCODe expects you to justify that complexity and then choose a different representation. --- The BCODe layering model One of the most important design tenets is a clean separation: 1) Syntax 窶・what bytes mean structurally 2) Interpretation 窶・how a parsed field becomes a numeric representation (integer, fixed-point pair, exponent) and how qualifiers map to value-classes 3) Semantics 窶・what the numbers mean for a specific application or device domain 4) Conventions 窶・standardized semantic profiles that encourage interoperability (e.g., BCODe.meta, BCODe.rest) BCODe works best when you do not skip layers. 2.1 Syntax: a streaming, latch-on-command model BCODe is parsed from an unbounded byte stream ; there is no EOF concept. A 窶徑ine窶・is a logical unit that ends when a command character is read, at which point the entire line is latched atomically . 訷filecite訷Ｕurn3file8訷・Fields are terminated by: PARAM terminators (ASCII 0x40窶・x5F) for intermediate fields CMD terminators (ASCII 0x60窶・x7F) for the final field, which also latches the line 訷filecite訷Ｕurn2file17訷・2.2 Interpretation: quality-first telemetry and typed accessors A parsed field has (at least) these properties: a base qualifier mask (- < ?), an orthogonal stale flag (!), a numeric 窶徭hape窶・(empty/single/pair), and optional exponent metadata. 訷filecite訷Ｕurn2file2訷・BCODe interpretation is explicitly quality-first : callers should be able to refuse a 窶徂ard numeric窶・result when the field is unknown, null, NaN, infinity, epsilon-only, etc. 訷filecite訷Ｕurn2file2訷・2.3 Semantics: application-owned meaning BCODe syntax and interpretation do not assign meaning to particular parameter letters or command letters. That mapping is owned by your application or by shared conventions. 訷filecite訷Ｕurn3file4訷・2.4 Conventions: standard semantic profiles In this document we treat 窶徭tandard semantics窶・as conventions : BCODe.meta 窶・command/response, unsolicited frames, multiline grouping, sequence counters BCODe.rest 窶・resource-oriented process-control semantics built on BCODe streams (inspired by Representation State Transfer, not HTTP packets) --- The 32-parameter reality (and why it窶冱 a feature) BCODe has exactly 32 parameter identities because parameter identity is defined by the low 5 bits of the terminator byte (term & 0x1F), producing indices 0..31. 訷filecite訷Ｕurn2file15訷・This constraint is a design choice: It bounds parser state. It forces semantic discipline. It encourages stable, conventional mappings. It makes bitmask operations natural and fast (selection, reduction, filtering). 訷filecite訷Ｕurn2file10訷・3.1 Best practices under the 32-parameter limit Do: Reserve a small set of parameters for cross-cutting conventions (e.g., meta, sequencing, routing). Treat A窶纏 as your 窶彭omain payload窶・bucket unless a convention says otherwise. Create (and publish) a parameter map table : what each letter means in each command context. Keep each parameter self-contained (see 窶彿nterparameter dependency窶・below). Don窶冲: Create a new parameter just to represent 窶忻alidity窶・ 窶徨eason窶・ 窶徇ode窶・ or 窶徭tatus窶・if it can be expressed by qualifiers or diagnostics. Create brittle schemas where field A is only valid if fields B and C are present. Attempt to encode nested structures by inventing ad-hoc 窶彙egin/end窶・markers inside parameters. --- Make simple tasks simple (and keep them that way) BCODe窶冱 窶徭uperpower窶・is that a BCODe line is: short, stable, grep-able, and can be generated with almost no tooling. 4.1 Generation should remain trivial BCODe should be easy enough that a developer can emit valid output with: a few print statements, and a small amount of local formatting discipline. If your application layer requires: multi-pass serialization, schema registries, complicated escaping rules, or mandatory binary-to-text encodings 窶ｦyou are eroding the core advantage of BCODe. 4.2 窶廨repability窶・as a design constraint Prefer designs where: you can locate occurrences of a parameter with grep 'A', you can locate a command class with grep 'a$' (or similar), you can eyeball bounds (< / ) and state (?, !) without decoding. This pushes you toward: flat lines, minimal implicit coupling, and stable letter assignments. --- Qualifiers: encode quality and intent in the field itself BCODe provides a compact set of field qualifiers: The syntax spec defines their syntactic role, and the companion interpretation spec defines standard meanings. 訷filecite訷Ｕurn2file14訷・5.1 Staleness is ! (orthogonal) The ! qualifier is an orthogonal freshness modifier that may be combined with any base value class, including infinity and NaN. It does not change the base class. 訷filecite訷Ｕurn2file3訷・Examples: !12.3A 窶・stale but still a hard numeric value ! ?A 窶・stale positive infinity !-< ?A 窶・stale NaN 5.2 Base value-class truth table (- < ?) The four base qualifiers define the base value class , independent of staleness. The interpretation spec reserves and standardizes combinations including epsilon, infinity, null, NaN, and signaling NaN. 訷filecite訷Ｕurn2file4訷・Key combinations (summary): Exact (hard numeric): no < or or ? (optionally - for sign) Bounds: < means 窶忻alue is less than stated窶・(upper bound) means 窶忻alue is greater than stated窶・(lower bound) 訷filecite訷Ｕurn2file4訷・Unknown/pending: ? Noise/unstable: -? Epsilon (smallest device step): <? (positive) and -<? (negative) 訷filecite訷Ｕurn2file0訷・Infinity: ? (positive) and - ? (negative) 訷filecite訷Ｕurn2file0訷・sNaN (signaling NaN): < and -< (reserved; C1 only; value1 carries a payload/code) 訷filecite訷Ｕurn2file3訷・Null (no data): < ? NaN (invalid computational result): -< ? (quiet/invalid; not a hard value) 訷filecite訷Ｕurn2file0訷・Important: 窶廝ounds窶・are not hard values. Accessors that return hard numerics should reject </ unless an explicit bound/interval type is requested. 訷filecite訷Ｕurn2file6訷・5.3 Diagnostics without extra parameters Qualifiers let a single parameter express 窶徼his isn窶冲 a usable measurement,窶・while still carrying a numeric code that describes why . This is a core design strategy: avoid adding a separate X status parameter, avoid inventing a 窶徨eason窶・parameter, and avoid interparameter dependency. Two common patterns: 1) Signaling NaN with a diagnostic code (reserved by the interpretation spec): (Use single-number shape C1 for sNaN.) 訷filecite訷Ｕurn2file3訷・2) Unknown/Noise with a diagnostic code (application-defined): (Interpretation policy: numeric digits 窶徇ay be present but should not be treated as hard窶・for certain value classes.) 訷filecite訷Ｕurn2file4訷・--- Use qualifiers for control intent (not just telemetry) Qualifiers are also useful when sending commands . Instead of forcing the host to compute an exact target that the device may not be able to hit cleanly, the host can send intent: 6.1 Bounds delegate resolution to the device Example: 窶彜et temperature to at least 100ﾂｰC窶・ The device is responsible for: choosing the nearest representable setpoint 竕･ 100, handling overshoot policy, and acknowledging what it actually applied (if desired). 6.2 Epsilon steps avoid 窶徂ost knows device resolution窶・For 窶彿ncrease by the smallest representable increment窶・ This delegates the increment size to the device, avoiding a host-side dependency on device quantization. --- Avoid interparameter dependency One of the strongest BCODe line-design principles is: A parameter should 窶徭tand alone窶・as much as possible. Interparameter dependency is where protocols go to die: it creates hidden rules, brittle parsing, and complicated failure modes. 7.1 Practical rules If a value can be 窶彿nvalid窶・ encode invalidity in the field itself (qualifiers), not in a separate field. If a value needs a reason code, encode it in the same field as a diagnostic number. If a value is stale, mark it stale with !, rather than introducing A age ms. If a value is bounded, encode bounds with </ , rather than A low / A high pairs unless you truly need intervals. 7.2 Use reducers and masks for policy, not schema coupling The interpretation spec describes a 窶徨educer窶・that summarizes per-field status into bitmasks (missing/empty/stale/exact/bound/diagnostic) so software layers can apply policy without baking in semantics. 訷filecite訷Ｕurn2file11訷・Transforms and reducers naturally use 32-bit masks keyed by the 32 parameter identities. 訷filecite訷Ｕurn2file10訷・Recommended pipeline: --- Convention: BCODe.meta (Command窶迭esponse) BCODe.meta is a convention for request/response framing, unsolicited statements, multiline grouping, and sequence counters. It reserves a small set of parameters for 窶徘rotocol plumbing窶・rather than application data. 8.1 Response tagging ^ 窶・affirmative response (optional integer value may be a timestamp) \\ 窶・negative response (optional numeric may be a reason code; may be negative) ^\\ 窶・unsolicited statement (sent without a request; ^ may carry a timestamp) Commands themselves do not carry ^ or \\. Affirmative response, no timestamp Affirmative response with timestamp Negative response, no reason Negative response with reason Unsolicited statement 8.1.1 Error reporting in the \\ field (provisional) The \\ parameter MAY carry a numeric value to explain why a request was denied, rejected, or could not be processed. This section defines a provisional BCODe.rest error-code registry for that numeric value. This convention applies to: Negative responses (lines tagged with \\) Unsolicited follow-ons (lines tagged with ^\\) where the \\ field carries a failure/status code If the \\ field is empty, the error/status is unspecified. 8.1.1.1 On-the-wire encoding BCODe.rest encodes an error as a (group, subcode) pair inside the \\ field. The group is a negative integer (e.g., -1, -2, -97). The subcode is a nonnegative integer written after the decimal point (e.g., .0, .1, .12). Decoder requirement (normative): Decoders MUST NOT treat the error value as a floating-point quantity. They MUST decode it using the raw parsed integer pair: group = signed integer from the integer part subcode = base-10 integer from the fractional digits (value2, using frac width) This preserves the distinction between -1.1 (subcode 1) and -1.10 (subcode 10). Encoding guidance (recommended): Always include a decimal point and at least one digit (i.e., prefer -1.0\\ over -1\\). For subcodes 竕･ 10, include all digits (e.g., -1.10\\). Avoid leading zeros in the subcode (e.g., prefer -1.2\\ over -1.02\\) unless you intentionally use fixed-width formatting. 8.1.1.2 Provisional registry constants (C header reference) The following reference definitions are taken from the existing PCOB implementation and translated to BCODe.rest naming. 8.1.1.3 General errors (group -1) For general errors, use: -(1).<subcode \\ (i.e., -1.<subcode \\) Subcode Symbol Code Meaning -------: -------- ------ --------- 0 BCODEREST ERRGEN CMD UNKNOWN -1.0\\ The command is unknown 1 BCODEREST ERRGEN RES UNKNOWN -1.1\\ The resource id is unknown 2 BCODEREST ERRGEN SEQ MISSING -1.2\\ The command sequence is missing 3 BCODEREST ERRGEN SEQ UNKNOWN -1.3\\ The command sequence is unknown 4 BCODEREST ERRGEN PAYLOAD MISSING -1.4\\ Expected payload but was missing 5 BCODEREST ERRGEN PAYLOAD OVERFLOW -1.5\\ Buffer reserved for payload overflowed 6 BCODEREST ERRGEN PAYLOAD INVALID -1.6\\ Error in the payload data 7 BCODEREST ERRGEN INDEX MISSING -1.7\\ Resource index (@) missing from command 8 BCODEREST ERRGEN INDEX UNKNOWN -1.8\\ Resource index does not exist 9 BCODEREST ERRGEN PARAM MISSING -1.9\\ Required parameter missing from command 10 BCODEREST ERRGEN PARAM OVERRANGE -1.10\\ Parameter exceeds acceptable range 11 BCODEREST ERRGEN PARAM UNDERRANGE -1.11\\ Parameter is less than acceptable 12 BCODEREST ERRGEN PARAM BADQUAL -1.12\\ Parameter has bad qualifier 13 BCODEREST ERRGEN PARAM INVALID -1.13\\ Parameter value was invalid 14 BCODEREST ERRGEN RESP OVERFLOW -1.14\\ Multiline response messages exceed buffer 15 BCODEREST ERRGEN RANGE MISSING -1.15\\ Expected a range specification 16 BCODEREST ERRGEN RANGE OVERFLOW -1.16\\ Expected range extent is too high 17 BCODEREST ERRGEN LINE MISSING -1.17\\ Expected more BCODe lines in input 8.1.1.4 Multiline errors (group -2) For multiline errors, use: -(2).<subcode \\ (i.e., -2.<subcode \\) Subcode Symbol Code Meaning -------: -------- ------ --------- 0 BCODEREST ERRML EXPECTED -2.0\\ Missing multiline parameter [ in a sequence 1 BCODEREST ERRML LAST MISSING -2.1\\ Multiline command missing last value 2 BCODEREST ERRML LAST OVERFLOW -2.2\\ Multiline command exceeds parser buffer 3 BCODEREST ERRML LAST ALTERED -2.3\\ 窶廰ast element窶・did not remain constant in sequence 4 BCODEREST ERRML CNTR START -2.4\\ Counter did not start at 1 5 BCODEREST ERRML CNTR OVERRANGE -2.5\\ Counter is greater than last 6 BCODEREST ERRML CNTR SEQUENCE -2.6\\ Counter did not match expected sequence 8.1.1.5 Command-specific error groups (group = -ASCII(command)) BCODe.rest reserves command-specific error groups using the negative ASCII value of the command letter. Group Command Notes ------: :------: ------ -97 a Read dynamic -98 b Write configuration (provisional) -99 c Control operation -100 d (reserved / TBD) -101 e Read static -102 f Manage feeds -105 i Allocate / deallocate Command-specific subcodes are command-defined. This document currently defines subcodes for b, c, and i (below). b write configuration errors (group -98) Subcode Symbol Code Meaning -------: -------- ------ --------- 0 BCODEREST ERR b EXPECTATION -98.0\\ State incompatible with parameter values 1 BCODEREST ERR b DENIED -98.1\\ Write denied 2 BCODEREST ERR b INTERNAL -98.2\\ Internal error c control operation errors (group -99) Subcode Symbol Code Meaning -------: -------- ------ --------- 0 BCODEREST ERR c DISABLED -99.0\\ Control is disabled 1 BCODEREST ERR c NOT APPLICABLE -99.1\\ Resource not in applicable state 2 BCODEREST ERR c COMMENCEMENT -99.2\\ Error starting the control i allocate/deallocate errors (group -105) Subcode Symbol Code Meaning -------: -------- ------ --------- 0 BCODEREST ERR i PREV -105.0\\ Resource already allocated 1 BCODEREST ERR i DEPENDENCY -105.1\\ Required dependency not allocated 2 BCODEREST ERR i INVALID -105.2\\ Initialization error due to supplied parameters 8.1.1.6 Device-specific errors (group = -1000 - ASCII(command)) BCODe.rest reserves a device-specific error space per command: Device-specific group = BCODEREST ERRDEV + (-(ASCII(command))) Equivalently: Device-specific group = -(1000 + ASCII(command)) Examples: Group Command Meaning -------: :------: --------- -1097 a Device errors -1098 b Device errors -1099 c Device errors -1100 d Device errors -1101 e Device errors -1102 f Device errors -1105 i Device errors Device-specific subcodes (fractional digits) are vendor-defined. Vendors SHOULD document these codes in their BCODe.rest lookup mechanism (see ﾂｧ9.2.1) so third parties can decode failures without out-of-band knowledge. 8.2 Multiline grouping: [ (packet) and ] (sequence) [ 窶・multiline packet tag The [ parameter marks a set of lines as a packet that must be evaluated as a group. The purpose of [ is atomic batching : receivers SHOULD buffer packet lines and deliver them to the application as a single grouped statement , rather than exposing each line as an independent statement. The [ field on each line uses the form i.t[: integer part i identifies the 1-based line index within the packet fractional part t identifies the total number of lines in the packet Packet lines SHOULD be contiguous and in order (1..t). Interleaving lines from different packets is discouraged and may be treated as an error. If a packet is incomplete or inconsistent (missing indices, mismatched totals, etc.), receivers SHOULD discard the packet (or surface an explicit packet error), rather than delivering partial application data. Open-ended packets (unknown length) Some multiline responses (direct responses or unsolicited follow-ons) cannot know their final line count when the first line is transmitted. In this case, a packet MAY be sent without an upfront end bound by qualifying the [ parameter with the qualifier. Each non-final line MUST include a [ field of the form n[ (single-integer), where n is the 1-based line index within the packet. The numeric n value MUST monotonically increase for each subsequent line (canonical form increments by +1). The packet MUST be terminated by a final line whose [ field is encoded in the fixed-bound form n.t[ without the qualifier, where t is the final total number of lines in the packet and n == t. This closing line MUST be syntactically indistinguishable from the last line of a packet that had fixed bounds from the start. Receivers MUST NOT deliver any packet lines to the application until the terminating fixed-bound line is received (atomic batching). Example: open-ended packet closed at 3 lines Example: three-line packet Example: two-line unsolicited packet A response to a multiline command does not need to match the number of lines in the initial command. ] 窶・sequence number Use ] as a sequence counter to help: debug ordering, detect missing statements, detect remote resets (sequence discontinuity), correlate multi-line packets. Example: three-line sequence Example: discontinuity (detect reset) Design note: choose a rollover strategy that makes rollover either known or extremely improbable (e.g., 64-bit). 8.3 RESET command ( ) The backtick command ( ) is reserved as a RESET command. Semantics (normative): Upon receiving the RESET command, a device MUST silently discard any currently parsed parameters and any in-progress payload reception. The device MUST NOT send any response (no ^ / \\ / ^\\ tagging). RESET is intentionally silent. After RESET, all ] sequence counters transmitted from the device MUST restart from 0. Usage (informative): RESET is intended for session start or resynchronization on stream transports (serial consoles, terminal sessions, etc.) to ensure no lingering partial commands are in effect. Because $ string payloads terminate on a newline, RESET SHOULD be sent after one or more \\n bytes to terminate any partially received string payload. For extra insurance when attaching mid-stream, multiple \\n bytes MAY be sent first to 窶徘ad窶・through any short binary payload reception on the receiver before issuing RESET. Example session-start resync sequence (bytes sent by host): --- Convention: BCODe.rest (Process control over BCODe streams) BCODe.rest (renamed from 窶弃COB窶・ is a convention for simple control and telemetry over BCODe. It encodes the idea of resources , indexes , commands , and command sequences . This convention is 窶彝EST-inspired窶・in the Representation State Transfer sense, not 窶廩TTP REST窶・ 9.1 窶彝EST窶・here is not HTTP HTTP REST is optimized for discrete, intermittent packet exchange. BCODe.rest is optimized for continuous streams (serial ports, TCP streams, WebSockets) where ordering and incremental delivery are first-class. Not everything in BCODe.rest will map cleanly to HTTP verbs, and that is expected. 9.2 Resource identifier (64-bit) A resource is identified by a unique 64-bit number, carried as the integer part of the BCODe command. Split: Upper 32 bits: IANA PEN (namespacing by organization) Lower 32 bits: resource identifier within that PEN窶冱 namespace Resources typically model a record with multiple fields (e.g., thermostat: temperature, thresholds, state bits). 9.2.1 Resource ID ownership and PEN-based lookup BCODe.rest treats the 64-bit resource ID as the primary key for decoding the meaning of a statement. If you do not know what a resource ID means, you cannot reliably interpret the line窶冱 parameters. Publishing rule (normative): Any party that publishes a BCODe.rest specification intended for interoperable third-party decoding MUST obtain an IANA Private Enterprise Number (PEN) and place it in the upper 32 bits of every resource ID it defines. The PEN acts as a global namespace boundary. The lower 32 bits are then free for that PEN-holder to partition as needed. Ad-hoc namespace (PEN = 0) (convention): A PEN value of 0 in the upper 32 bits designates a resource ID as ad-hoc : its meaning is not discoverable via the PEN lookup mechanism and requires full contextual information (out-of-band documentation, local agreements, or direct source access). This is intended to streamline tinkering, prototypes, and initial development. Any party publishing a specification intended for third-party decoding MUST NOT use PEN 0; obtain an IANA PEN and use it instead. Standard-definition namespace (PENs 5窶・) (convention, TBD): IANA PEN values 5, 6, 7, and 8 are early registry assignments (currently listed as ACC, TWG, CAYMAN, and PSI) and are treated by BCODe.rest as defunct/appropriable for standard resource definitions. BCODe.rest reserves these PEN values for future standard resource definitions (governance and format TBD). Until those standard definitions are published, implementations SHOULD treat these PENs as reserved and SHOULD NOT use them for vendor-specific namespaces. Discovery rule (normative, convention): When a decoder encounters an unknown resource ID, it SHOULD: 1) Extract the upper 32-bit PEN. 2) If the PEN is 0, treat the line as ad-hoc (no lookup is possible) and rely on full contextual information. 3) Otherwise, look up that PEN in the IANA PEN registry. 4) Extract a domain name from the registry窶冱 contact email (typically the substring after @). 5) Retrieve the vendor窶冱 BCODe.rest lookup document via HTTP at: https://<domain /BCODe.rest/lookup.json (recommended) http://<domain /BCODe.rest/lookup.json (optional fallback) The lookup document provides the mappings needed to interpret the resource and its parameter semantics (format TBD). Implementation notes (informative): PEN holders SHOULD ensure their PEN registry contact email uses a stable organizational domain suitable for discovery (avoid throwaway email domains). Consumers SHOULD cache lookup results (including negative results) and treat the lookup as advisory: lack of a lookup document must not break parsing of the underlying BCODe stream. 9.3 Index (@) The parameter @ identifies an instance of the resource (e.g., thermostat 0, 1, 2). The index may include a fractional value to add another hierarchy layer. 9.4 Command, command sequence, and response ordinal The command is the lowercase letter at the end of the line. The command sequence is the fractional portion of the command窶冱 resource number (the .N part). Statements associated with that request are numbered with a response ordinal encoded as a R suffix on the command number. Syntactically, this reuses BCODe窶冱 scientific exponent suffix ( ), which is already parsed into (exp present, exp10). In BCODe.rest , interpret exp10 as a response ordinal , not as numeric scaling (for the command field only). Rules: A request command sequence N MUST be a nonnegative integer (application-defined). Any statement that refers to that request MUST reuse the exact same sequence N. Any such statement MUST include an explicit ordinal R where R is a nonnegative integer (digits required; do not rely on the implicit default exponent). For a given request, response ordinals SHOULD be allocated monotonically starting at R = 0 and increasing when a new kind of statement is introduced. A given ordinal R MAY be repeated to publish incremental updates for the same statement kind (for example, progress reporting). In that case, multiple lines with the same R are an update stream ; ordering should be determined by timestamps (on ^) and/or a ] sequence counter if present. This scheme allows a command that originally had a single response to evolve into 窶徇ultiple responses窶・without renumbering the command sequence N (so you don窶冲 shift dataset IDs embedded in that fractional portion). 9.4.1 Direct response vs delayed results (BCODe.meta interaction) BCODe.rest relies on BCODe.meta for command/response framing: Direct response (immediate acknowledgement) The direct response to a command MUST be an affirmative acknowledgement tagged with ^. The direct response MUST begin with ordinal 0. If the direct response requires more than one line, those lines MUST be grouped as a multiline packet using the [ parameter (each line contains [). Packet enumeration MAY be fixed-bound (i.t[) or open-ended ( n[ ... terminating with n.t[), as defined in ﾂｧ8.2. In a multiline direct response packet, ordinals MUST start at 0 but MAY use 1, 2, 窶ｦ on subsequent lines. This ensures the interpretation of each line does not depend on the presence of [; [ only controls atomic batching . Delayed results (follow-on statements) Delayed results are considered unsolicited statements and therefore: MUST include both ^ and \\ tags (i.e. ^\\ is present on each line). MUST use ordinals that are either: new ordinals that continue after the direct response (e.g., if the direct response used 0 only, the first new delayed statement uses 1; if the direct response used 0.. 2, the first new delayed statement uses 3), or repeats of an existing ordinal R 0 to publish incremental updates (progress/status) for that stage. 0 is reserved for the direct acknowledgement packet and MUST NOT be used for delayed follow-ons. If a delayed result spans multiple lines, it MUST be grouped as a packet using [ and SHOULD use consecutive ordinals within that packet. Open-ended packet enumeration (using on [) is permitted when the final line count is not known up front; see ﾂｧ8.2. In unsolicited follow-ons, the \\ field MAY carry a numeric failure/status code (including negatives). If no failure/status code is needed, it may be empty; the presence of \\ still serves as part of the unsolicited marker in ^\\. 9.4.2 Ordinal reuse for progress / intermediate updates Sometimes a device needs to publish incremental updates for the same stage (for example, percent completion while an operation is running) without allocating a brand-new ordinal for every update. In that case, the device MAY repeat the same R on multiple statements for the same command sequence N. Receivers should treat multiple statements with the same (N, R) as an update stream (for many applications, 窶徑atest wins窶・ for logs, keep all). Example (percent completion updates using repeated 2): Example (direct acknowledgement only; delayed single-line result later): Example (multiline direct response: must use [; ordinals begin at 0 and continue): Example (direct acknowledgement only; delayed multi-line result later): Example (direct acknowledgement; later unsolicited failure code on \\): 9.5 Read commands Two read classes: a 窶・read dynamic dataset (timestamp recommended) Synchronous data (returned in the direct response): Synchronous data across multiple lines (must be grouped with [): Delayed data (direct response is ack; data arrives later as unsolicited ^\\): Delayed data across multiple lines (unsolicited result must still be grouped with [): Delayed failure (direct ack; later unsolicited completion carries a failure code on \\): e 窶・read static dataset (timestamp optional) Synchronous data (returned in the direct response): Delayed data (direct ack; data arrives later as unsolicited ^\\): Other command letters (brief): c 窶・initiate resource control (req/resp) f 窶・data feed (unsolicited) i 窶・(de)allocate (req/multi-resp) --- Streaming-first transport design BCODe assumes a stream: no EOF requirement, robust resynchronization after errors, and deterministic parsing even with interleaving comments/payloads between tokens. 訷filecite訷Ｕurn3file11訷・This makes BCODe a natural fit for: serial ports WebSockets TCP streams embedded debugging consoles 10.1 Payloads: carry strings and binary without 窶廱SON gymnastics窶・BCODe supports payloads as first-class syntax: $... string payload (ends at LF or NUL; body is opaque) %...% hex-byte payload (whitespace allowed; comments allowed inside) & raw-binary payload (length derived from the numeric accumulator/value1; body is opaque) 訷filecite訷Ｕurn3file12訷・Qualifiers apply only to fields , not to payloads. 訷filecite訷Ｕurn2file13訷・--- JSON vs BCODe (comparison boxes) 11.1 Names, translation, and arbitration Topic JSON BCODe --- --- --- Field identification String keys (names) Letter parameters (codes) Cross-language friction Keys often reflect one language窶冱 vocabulary and abbreviations Language-neutral wire identifiers Arbitration Naming debates are common (窶徼empC窶・vs 窶徼emperature celsius窶・ No naming arbitration on the wire Schema churn Renames and aliases become long-term baggage Semantics evolve in docs/profiles while letters remain stable Tooling Requires JSON tooling; grep is noisier Grep-friendly by design Principle: human language belongs in documentation and UI, not in the wire format. 11.2 Strings, binary, and payload realism Topic JSON BCODe --- --- --- Strings Native Native (payloads) Binary Not native; must be encoded (e.g., Base64) Native (& raw-binary) Streaming fit Encoded blobs and framing complicate streams Payload bodies are designed for streams 訷filecite訷Ｕurn3file12訷・11.3 IEEE-754 telemetry fidelity BCODe窶冱 qualifier classes explicitly represent exceptional numeric states such as infinity, NaN, null/no-data, epsilon, and signaling NaN. 訷filecite訷Ｕurn2file0訷・A particularly important capability is signaling NaN: < and -< are reserved for sNaN and carry a payload/code in value1 (C1 only). 訷filecite訷Ｕurn2file3訷・--- When to choose something else Choose a different representation when you truly need: nested trees / arbitrary depth objects, large evolving schemas with self-describing names, ad-hoc arrays of heterogeneous objects, or interoperability primarily driven by 窶忤eb document窶・tooling. BCODe is intentionally not trying to be everything. --- Appendix A. Quick reference: corrected 窶徭pecial value窶・spellings This appendix corrects and summarizes the standardized qualifier combinations (base - < ? plus orthogonal !). 訷filecite訷Ｕurn2file4訷・Examples shown with parameter A. A.1 Unknown / pending A.2 Noise / unstable signal A.3 Epsilon (device窶冱 smallest step) A.4 Infinity (beyond measurable range) A.5 Null (explicit no-data) A.6 NaN (invalid computational result) A.7 Signaling NaN (sNaN) with payload/code (C1 only) A.8 Stale modifier (orthogonal) --- Appendix B. Minimal 窶彡onvention stack窶・recommendation If you want a pragmatic default for most device+host ecosystems: 1) BCODe syntax (mandatory) 訷filecite訷Ｕurn3file0訷・2) BCODe interpretation (strongly recommended) 訷filecite訷Ｕurn3file1訷・3) BCODe.meta for request/response + sequencing 4) BCODe.rest for resource-oriented telemetry and control over streams This gives you: stable parsing and typed accessors, a robust command/response story, and a scalable resource model窶背ithout abandoning BCODe窶冱 simplicity. --- End of document."}, {"slug": "telemetry-guide", "display_title": "Telemetry Guide", "preview_title": "BCODe_telemetry_scalable_complexity_guide_plus 窶・Local Preview", "description": "BCODe for Telemetry: Design Rationale, Exceptions, and Scalable Complexity Status: Informative guide (not normative) Audience: firmware/device implementers, telemetry pipeline/tool authors, protocol designers ?", "corpus_text": "BCODe for Telemetry: Design Rationale, Exceptions, and Scalable Complexity Status: Informative guide (not normative) Audience: firmware/device implementers, telemetry pipeline/tool authors, protocol designers Applies to: BCODe syntax v10 + interpretation v10, and the conventions BCODe.meta (2026窶・2窶・2) and BCODe.rest v6.1.1 (2026窶・2窶・4) --- What this document is This guide explains why BCODe looks the way it does in the context of telemetric data transmission and reception , and how its ecosystem is intentionally designed for scalable complexity : start with a tiny ad窶蘇oc BCODe syntax protocol to bring up hardware quickly then 窶忖pgrade in place窶・by adopting: BCODe interpretation for quality/exception semantics BCODe.meta for command/response + batching + sequencing + reset BCODe.rest for resource-oriented semantics, discovery hooks, and deployment-grade interoperability The important theme is: you do not throw away your parser as you scale. You add conventions. --- Telemetry is not 窶徊ust numbers窶・Real telemetry systems must communicate: measurements (scalars, counters, rates) bounds (窶彗t least this窶・ 窶從o more than that窶・ unknown / pending / not initialized invalid computational results (NaN / signaling NaN) freshness (窶徼his value exists but is stale窶・ exceptions and diagnostics (why something is missing/unusable) attached context (notes, binary frames, checksums, event records) BCODe窶冱 split between syntax and interpretation is aimed at making these realities explicit without turning a stream protocol into a heavyweight schema language. --- Why the core syntax is telemetry-friendly 2.1 Streaming parsing and atomic latching BCODe is parsed from an unbounded byte stream (serial, pipes, TCP, logs). A logical 窶徑ine窶・ends when a command terminator (ASCII 0x60窶・x7F) is seen in normal mode . Rationale: in noisy or chunked transports, receivers must avoid applying partial updates. BCODe latches all parsed state (fields + payloads) atomically only when a command character arrives. This is a natural resynchronization boundary and a safe 窶彡ommit point窶・ 2.2 ASCII-column partitioning BCODe assigns meaning by ASCII 窶彡olumn窶・(upper 3 bits): Column 2 (0x20窶・x3F) : digits, punctuation, qualifiers, payload/comment markers Column 3 (0x40窶・x5F) : parameter terminators (end a field, continue the line) Column 4 (0x60窶・x7F) : command terminators (end the final field and latch) Rationale: receivers can classify bytes with cheap range checks / bitmasks, and terminators are structurally distinct from data. This improves parser simplicity and robustness in embedded contexts. 2.3 Single-letter parameters and 窶從o bikeshedding窶・Premise: single-letter parameter names avoid bikeshedding. BCODe provides exactly 32 parameter identities (low 5 bits of a terminator). This is deliberate: the mapping from 窶徘arameter index窶・to 窶徇eaning窶・is documented once (per resource/protocol) the wire format stays stable and compact software can naturally summarize presence/quality via uint32 t bitmasks This is a pragmatic trade: you sacrifice self-describing verbosity on the wire to gain stability, bandwidth efficiency, and fewer naming debates. --- Numbers: locale tolerance, scientific notation, and safety constraints 3.1 Fixed-point pairs preserve intent A numeric field can be: empty (no numeric content) single integer (value1) a two-integer pair (value1 and value2 with a recorded fractional width) This supports deterministic parsing and preserves how many digits were spelled (leading zeros in the fractional part are meaningful). 3.2 Premise: 窶・窶・and 窶・窶・are used as decimal separators in the world BCODe accepts both . and , as the pair separator . Many systems and humans use . as a decimal separator. Many locales use , as a decimal separator. BCODe窶冱 syntax accepts both to reduce friction. Important detail: in syntax v10, . and , are pair separators , not locale-dependent decimal points, and the parser records the sign of the second component based on the separator (, 竍・negative value2). The interpretation layer decides what that means for a given accessor/application. Practical recommendation for interoperability: standardize on . for ordinary fractional values unless you have a strong compatibility reason not to if you accept ,-emitters, treat that as a compatibility transform in your receiver pipeline rather than assuming all senders intend the same semantics 3.3 Premise: scientific notation is needed Telemetry often spans orders of magnitude. BCODe supports a compact exponent suffix: k 竍・multiply mantissa by 10^k /k 竍・multiply mantissa by 10^-k Rationale: this allows scientific-scale representation without colliding with command/parameter terminators (letters are reserved for framing in BCODe). 3.4 Uppercase-only hex is a safety choice Hex literals use #...# and hex payloads use %...%. Hex digits are uppercase only . Rationale: lowercase a窶吐 live in the command terminator column; forbidding lowercase reduces accidental collisions and helps robust resync behavior. --- Qualifiers: communicating exceptions and data quality on the wire 4.1 Premise: the need to communicate more than just the data BCODe fields support qualifier characters: base qualifiers: -, <, , ? freshness modifier: ! (stale) 4.2 Quality-first model (why this matters) In telemetry, the first question is often: 窶彿s the value usable?窶・窶彿f not, why not?窶・窶徙nly then, what is the number?窶・BCODe窶冱 interpretation model makes this first-class. Instead of sentinel numbers, you can express: bounds (< / ) unknown/pending (?) noise/unstable (-?) epsilon / infinity (combinations with ?) null/no-data (distinct from 窶彗bsent field窶・ NaN / signaling NaN (reserved qualifier combinations) 4.3 Staleness as an orthogonal modifier Premise: the role of qualifiers in communicating telemetric data exceptions. ! is orthogonal: a value can be 窶徭tale but finite窶・ 窶徭tale infinity窶・ 窶徭tale NaN窶・ etc. This prevents 窶彷reshness窶・from being conflated with 窶忻alidity窶・ --- Multiple interpretations of the same field: a feature for telemetry pipelines Premise: develop context and justification for the multiple interpretations of the same field. Telemetry systems have multiple consumers: control loops want strict hard numbers UIs want best-effort display (including bounds, null, stale) logging wants preservation (raw + parsed + diagnostics) health monitoring wants fast triage (窶彗ny NaN/null/noise?窶・ BCODe supports this by separating: raw parsed truth (qualifiers, numeric shape, exponent metadata) typed accessors that apply local policy (strict vs permissive) optional transforms (normalization / compatibility) reducers that summarize per-field status into bitmasks (missing, empty, stale, diagnostic, hard-ok, etc.) This is scalable: you keep one parser and add policy layers per consumer. --- Payloads and comments: attaching context in telemetry streams Telemetry sometimes needs to attach more than numeric fields: $... string payloads (opaque until LF/NUL) %...% hex-byte payloads (comment-friendly; whitespace and comments removed before decode) & raw binary payloads (length derived from value1 only) Rationale: you can attach: human-readable notes (firmware version, assertions) checksums compact binary frames without changing the core field grammar. Comments (;...LF and ( ... )) are treated as whitespace: helpful for debugging and logs, but not semantic. --- Scalable complexity: from bench hacks to deployment conventions BCODe is intentionally layered. Complexity is optional and additive: BCODe syntax 窶・a compact, streaming-safe grammar for fields/payloads. BCODe interpretation 窶・standard meaning for qualifiers, quality-first accessors, reducers/transforms. BCODe.meta 窶・a control-plane convention over streams (ACK/NAK, unsolicited, batching, sequencing, reset). BCODe.rest 窶・an application-plane convention: resource IDs, operation categories, discovery hooks, diagnostics, feeds, etc. The key property: each layer composes over the same syntax . --- 7.1 Stage 0: Ad-hoc syntax protocols (device bring-up) For bench testing, you can define your own meaning for parameters and command letters: choose parameters: A temperature, B humidity choose command: m measurement snapshot Example: Benefits for bring-up: extremely low overhead to implement atomic latch on command terminator prevents partial updates log-friendly and grep-friendly At this stage, you can ignore request/response, discovery, strict semantics, etc. --- 7.2 Stage 1: Add standard exception semantics (interpretation) As soon as a system needs to communicate 窶從ot ready / invalid / bounded / stale窶・ ad-hoc sentinel values become a liability. The interpretation layer gives standardized qualifier meanings and recommended accessor behavior. Examples: This stage is still lightweight: it mostly affects how receivers interpret fields, not the on-wire grammar. --- 7.3 Stage 2: Upgrade to BCODe.meta (deployment-grade reliability without redesign) When you need real command/response behavior and robustness, adopt BCODe.meta . BCODe.meta reserves: ^ affirmative response tag \\ negative response tag ^\\ unsolicited statement tag [ multiline packet/batch tag (atomic delivery) ] sequence counter reset command 7.3.1 Command/response vs unsolicited Requests (窶彡ommands窶・ do not contain ^ or \\. Direct responses are tagged: ^ (accept) or \\ (reject). Unsolicited statements must contain both: ^\\. This cleanly separates: 窶廬 am replying to something窶・from 窶廬 am spontaneously reporting an event窶・ 7.3.2 Multiline batching is for delivery, not semantics [ enables an atomic multi-line packet: receiver should buffer until packet completes then deliver the group as one unit This is crucial for telemetry and control when you need multi-field updates without partial application. 7.3.3 Sequencing and reset for resynchronization ] gives sequence counters so you can detect loss or resets provides a defined reset behavior: discard pending parse state, send no response, reset device-transmitted counters --- 7.4 Stage 3: Upgrade to BCODe.rest (resource semantics and interoperability) BCODe.rest is a convention for forming telemetry statements and control operations over streams. It composes: syntax + interpretation + meta. BCODe.rest provides the missing 窶彭eployment plane窶・ resource-oriented semantics and stable IDs standardized operation categories discovery hooks (lookup.json) unambiguous field presence rules (unsupported vs diagnostic) systematic diagnostics and error groups feed streaming and buffered log playback with explicit release 7.4.1 The ad-hoc-to-deployment bridge: PEN=0 BCODe.rest resource IDs are 64-bit; upper 32 bits are an IANA PEN namespace. PEN=0 is explicitly reserved for ad-hoc resource IDs. Later, you can obtain a PEN and migrate to globally namespaced IDs. This is the scalable complexity story in one feature: prototypes don窶冲 need a registry step, but deployed systems can. 7.4.2 Resources, indexing, and datasets Key selectors: RID : the resource ID in the command field @: selects an instance of a resource (indexing) N: command sequence selector (fractional part of the command field); used as a stable dataset/variant selector This makes it possible to evolve datasets without reassigning parameter meanings. 7.4.3 Standard operation categories (verbs) BCODe.rest reserves command letters as operation categories, including: a dynamic read (idempotent; may be stale) e static read (idempotent; never stale) b stored update/readback (idempotent; PUT-ish) d delta update (non-idempotent; atomic; quantized; rejects out-of-range) c control actions (side effects) f feeds/logs (streaming + buffered playback + release) i allocate/deallocate (instantiation lifecycle) You can implement only a subset at first and expand later. 7.4.4 Field presence rule: 窶徙mitted == unsupported窶・For response datasets (reads and defined response payloads): Unsupported field: MUST NOT appear. Supported field: MUST appear either as a normal value or as a diagnostic value-kind (optionally with a diagnostic code). This removes a major ambiguity from ad-hoc protocols. 7.4.5 Stale rules are tightened in rest BCODe.rest constrains staleness: allowed on parameter fields for a (dynamic reads) forbidden for e (static reads) discouraged for stored-state operations unless explicitly defined It also defines command-field qualifiers for feeds (f / f) under buffer pressure and loss conditions. 7.4.6 Requests, responses, ordinals, and batching BCODe.rest uses: /R on the command field for request ordinals within a [ batched request packet R on the command field for response ordinals 0 is the required ordinal for the direct response This provides a stable mechanism for multi-line requests/responses and later expansion of response datasets. 7.4.7 Controls are correlatable For c operations: <c executes, c is admission-check only (NOP) controls require a ] request sequence identifier responses and unsolicited progress/completion updates must echo an identifier derived from the request This makes async actions traceable. 7.4.8 Feeds and buffered logs (f, f, <f) BCODe.rest defines a unified model for: live feed updates (f, unsolicited) buffered playback ( f, unsolicited) explicit release (<f) so devices can safely discard delivered records It also standardizes: required ^ field presence on unsolicited feed statements record identifiers (timestamp mode recommended; event-identifier mode with ^! when no timestamps exist) command-field qualifiers: ! on unsolicited feed command field for global buffer saturation ? on unsolicited feed command field for per-resource overflow data loss 7.4.9 Instantiation (i) For instantiable resources, i provides allocate/deallocate semantics (with @ selecting instances) and supports allocation policy gating. This is optional, but it enables large systems to manage dynamic resources in a uniform way. --- Putting it together: recommended 窶徃rowth path窶・8.1 A realistic evolution timeline Bench bring-up: ad-hoc parameter mapping over syntax First integration: adopt qualifier semantics (interpretation) to stop using sentinel numbers System hardening: adopt meta (ACK/NAK, reset, sequencing, batching) Deployment interoperability: adopt rest (resource IDs, discovery hooks, standard operations, diagnostic rules, feeds) 8.2 Two common adoption strategies Strategy A 窶・窶徭tart ad-hoc, then adopt conventions窶・Fastest to type and debug; migration later. Strategy B 窶・窶忖se rest semantics early with PEN=0窶・Often smoother long-term: start with rest operation categories + resource model, but use PEN=0 later move to a real PEN and publish lookup.json --- Design 窶徃otchas窶・and best practices Avoid using meta-reserved tokens (^, \\, [, ], ) as application-defined parameters/commands if you plan to adopt meta/rest later. Prefer standardized qualifier semantics early; it keeps your data model stable. Treat receiver-side normalization (e.g., comma separator compatibility) as a transform step; don窶冲 bake assumptions into the base parser. For binary payloads: %...% is great when you want comments and readability & is great for throughput, but implement strict length caps and resync behavior Decide per consumer whether bounds are acceptable; don窶冲 silently coerce bounds into exact numbers in control loops. --- Glossary PARAM terminator: ASCII 0x40窶・x5F, ends a field and labels it. CMD terminator: ASCII 0x60窶・x7F, ends the final field and latches the line. Latch: the moment a line becomes visible to the application (atomic commit point). RID: resource ID (BCODe.rest) in the integer portion of the command field. PEN: IANA Private Enterprise Number (namespace for RIDs). Dataset selector N: command sequence selector (fractional digits on command field) used as a stable dataset/variant selector. Request ordinal /R: ordinal used inside a batched request packet. Response ordinal R: ordinal used for response datasets and follow-ons. --- Appendix A 窶・Where the authoritative rules live This guide is informative. The normative rules are defined in the underlying documents: BCODe Syntax Specification (Draft v10) BCODe Value Interpretation (Draft v10) BCODe.meta 窶・Convention for Command/Response, Batching, Sequencing, Reset (Draft) BCODe.rest 窶・Process Control Convention over BCODe Streams (Draft v6.1.1) --- Additional items worth adding for an even more 窶彭eployment-ready窶・guide This section is informative and focuses on practical gaps that usually show up when BCODe moves from a lab bench to a production telemetry pipeline. 11.1 Define interoperability 窶徘rofiles窶・(capability levels) BCODe scales because you can implement subsets. It helps readers if the guide defines a few common profiles that tooling can advertise (or that you can put in device documentation): Profile S (Syntax-only bring-up): parse fields, latch on CMD; ad-hoc parameter mapping. Profile I (Interpretation-aware telemetry): implement qualifier classification + typed accessors; reject non-hard values where needed. Profile M (Meta control-plane): implement ^, \\, ^\\, [, ], and reset . Profile R (REST application-plane): implement BCODe.rest resource ID parsing, operation categories, and the field presence rule. Profile F (Feeds/logs): implement f, f, <f with record identifiers and release semantics. Profile X (Instantiation): implement i allocation/deallocation and @ type-scope listing rules. Even if you don窶冲 formalize this as a standard, listing profiles clarifies what 窶徭upport窶・means and prevents tooling from guessing. 11.2 Add a 窶徨eceiver hardening窶・checklist (limits, resync, and DoS resistance) BCODe is stream-friendly, which also means it can be abused if you parse untrusted input. A short checklist helps implementers: Impose bounds on: maximum digits in value1 / value2 maximum frac width maximum exponent magnitude maximum payload length hints maximum raw payload length for & Treat overflow / excessive lengths as malformed and resynchronize. Budget memory : for $ and %...%, decide whether you buffer payloads, stream them, or hash/CRC them incrementally. Validate length hints (when present) and treat mismatches as parse errors. Prefer 窶彭rop line + resync窶・as your uniform recovery strategy for malformed constructs. This turns 窶彿t works on clean data窶・into 窶彿t is robust on real links.窶・11.3 Spell out a duplicate-parameter policy BCODe syntax does not inherently forbid repeating a parameter within one line. The interpretation layer窶冱 typical adapter pattern implicitly picks a policy (often 窶徑ast wins窶・. In real deployments, you should document one of: Last-wins (common; simple; matches many streaming adapters) First-wins (more conservative for 窶忤rite once窶・semantics) Reject duplicates (strict; best when you want to detect malformed senders) BCODe.rest has additional strictness for multiline packets (e.g., duplicates across a batched request packet can be malformed), so the guide should recommend rejecting duplicates in BCODe.rest requests unless a selector is explicitly allowed to repeat. 11.4 Add a 窶徭ession hygiene窶・snippet for serial/terminal workflows If your transport is a UART or a terminal session, add a small operational note: Send a few newlines to terminate any unterminated $... string payload. Then send meta RESET ( ) to discard partial parse state and reset device sequence counters. Only then begin issuing commands or enabling feeds. This is the kind of tip that drastically reduces 窶彿t gets confused sometimes窶・reports in the field. 11.5 Expand the BCODe.rest discovery story (lookup.json workflow) The current guide mentions discovery hooks; adding a short, explicit description helps users see the 窶忖pgrade path窶・ Resource IDs encode an IANA PEN in their upper 32 bits. A tool can look up that PEN in the IANA registry, derive a domain from the registry contact, and then fetch a conventional endpoint like: https://<domain /BCODe.rest/lookup.json Cache and pin lookup results by version/hash for reproducible decoding. This makes the 窶徘rototype (PEN=0) 竊・deployment (real PEN + published schema)窶・path concrete. 11.6 Add an error model cheat sheet BCODe.meta and BCODe.rest make negative acknowledgements (\\) carry a numeric error/reason code. For real deployments, readers benefit from a tiny summary: meta-level errors (reserved group) rest generic errors (reserved group) command-scoped rest errors by operation category (a, b, c, d, e, f, i), with subcodes in the fractional digits The big win is that tooling can classify failures without per-device bespoke rules. 11.7 Include a small 窶徙peration semantics窶・table (idempotence, atomicity, stale allowance) A compact table makes BCODe.rest easier to implement correctly: Category Typical meaning Idempotent? Atomic update? Stale allowed? --- --- ---: ---: ---: a dynamic read yes n/a yes (parameter fields) e static read yes n/a no b stored update/readback yes yes (updates) generally no d delta update no yes generally no c control action no request validation is atomic n/a f feeds/logs mixed release is atomic special command-field rules i allocate/deallocate mixed yes n/a Readers can then jump to the detailed sections when needed. 11.8 Add a 窶徼ime and ordering窶・note (feeds vs sequencing) BCODe provides multiple ordering mechanisms: BCODe.meta ] sequence counters : detect missing statements/resets on the transport. BCODe.rest feed record identifiers in ^` : order within a feed stream (timestamp mode recommended; event-identifier mode when no timestamps exist). A short section explaining how these complement (not replace) each other makes it easier to build correct log replay and monitoring tools. 11.9 Suggest a conformance/testing strategy Because BCODe is streaming, the most common bug class is chunking dependence (窶忤orks if read() returns whole lines窶・. It窶冱 worth adding a paragraph encouraging implementers to: run the provided syntax conformance vectors test random chunk boundaries and random byte corruption assert that line latching and resync behavior is stable --- Appendix B 窶・Quick-reference 窶忤ire contract窶・for telemetry deployments (optional) If you want the guide to be especially usable, consider adding a 1窶・ page appendix that states, in plain language: 窶弩hat is a line and when is it committed?窶・窶弩hat does it mean when a field is missing vs empty vs null?窶・窶弩hich qualifiers mean 窶賄o not use this number窶・窶・窶廩ow do I know a message is unsolicited vs a response?窶・窶廩ow do I safely enable feeds and detect data loss?窶・窶弩here do I look up resource/field meanings?窶・This appendix tends to become the most copied page in internal wikis."}, {"slug": "chat-summary", "display_title": "Chat Summary", "preview_title": "chat-summary-json-cbor-msgpack-bcode 窶・Preview", "description": "Chat Summary: JSON Origins, Special Numeric Values, and Interpretation Across JSON/CBOR/MessagePack/BCODe Date: 2026-02-14 Topic: Douglas Crockford and JSON; why JSON excludes NaN/Infinity; how CBOR and Messag?", "corpus_text": "Chat Summary: JSON Origins, Special Numeric Values, and Interpretation Across JSON/CBOR/MessagePack/BCODe Date: 2026-02-14 Topic: Douglas Crockford and JSON; why JSON excludes NaN/Infinity; how CBOR and MessagePack handle 窶彳xceptional窶・values; and how all of that compares to BCODe窶冱 interpretation layer (quality-first telemetry). --- 1) Did Douglas Crockford 窶彿nvent窶・JSON? The discussion started with a common question: did Douglas Crockford really invent JSON? Key distinction that emerged: The syntax that looks like JSON (objects {}, arrays [], strings, numbers, booleans) already existed as part of JavaScript literal notation . Crockford窶冱 central contribution was to package a strict, minimal subset of that notation as a language-neutral data interchange format , publish it, and push it into the broader web ecosystem. This is consistent with the later standards posture: JSON is defined as a grammar/data-interchange format, not as a programming language feature. See the JSON grammar and value definition in RFC 8259. Sources: RFC 8259 (JSON grammar / values) 窶・https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc8259 --- 2) What 窶彷ormalizing JSON窶・meant in practice The conversation unpacked 窶彷ormalizing窶・into a handful of concrete actions: Choosing and freezing a subset of JavaScript literal syntax as 窶彭ata only窶・ Publishing a public definition (grammar + examples) and advocating the format as an alternative to XML. Pushing JSON toward standardization and broad adoption. Two primary sources frame this: Crockford窶冱 窶彷at-free窶・writeup explicitly states JSON窶冱 minimalist posture and explains why it omits NaN and Infinity. Source: https://www.json.org/fatfree.html ECMA-404 explicitly states its scope is syntax only , and that it 窶彿ntentionally does not define 窶ｦ semantics or interpretation窶・ Source: https://ecma-international.org/publications-and-standards/standards/ecma-404/ --- 3) The JSON 窶徭emantic value set窶・A major part of the conversation was clarifying what JSON can mean at the lowest level. RFC 8259 defines a JSON value as one of: object array number string true false null (And it explicitly disallows any other literal names.) Source: RFC 8259 窶・https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc8259 This is a very small universe by design. --- 4) The debate: JSON窶冱 minimalism vs telemetry needs (NaN/Infinity) 4.1 JSON窶冱 stated rationale for excluding NaN / Infinity Crockford窶冱 窶彷at-free窶・text says JSON omits those values because it 窶彭oes not want to be tied to any particular internal representation.窶・Source: https://www.json.org/fatfree.html The standards also define JSON numbers lexically (digits, optional fraction/exponent), so tokens like NaN/Infinity are not valid JSON numbers. Source: RFC 8259 窶・https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc8259 4.2 The user窶冱 critique (and what real systems show) The user argued (coherently) that: Many systems do use IEEE-754 in practice. Infinity/NaN are useful (especially in telemetry) because they allow exceptional computation results to propagate. When JSON forbids them, people invent ad hoc encodings, which fragments semantics anyway . Real-world evidence that this happens: JavaScript窶冱 JSON.stringify maps NaN and ﾂｱInfinity to null (lossy). Source (ECMA-262 5.1): https://262.ecma-international.org/5.1/ See JSON.stringify NOTE 4. Fluent Bit encountered invalid JSON when converting MessagePack containing NaN into JSON, prompting an option to convert NaN 竊・null during msgpack竊男son conversion. Sources: Fluent Bit config option: https://docs.fluentbit.io/manual/administration/configuring-fluent-bit/classic-mode/configuration-file Fluent Bit issue #1588: https://github.com/fluent/fluent-bit/issues/1588 4.3 I-JSON as an 窶彿nterop profile窶・response The conversation also referenced that the IETF published a restricted JSON profile (I-JSON) to reduce surprises and maximize interoperability. Source: RFC 7493 窶・https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc7493 This is an example of a broader pattern: JSON the grammar is minimal, ecosystem 窶徘rofiles窶・or 窶徭chemas窶・attempt to fill in missing interoperability constraints. --- 5) Interpretation-level comparison: CBOR vs MessagePack vs BCODe This part of the conversation shifted from 窶徭yntax窶・to interpretation : what meaning a receiver can derive after parsing . 5.1 BCODe: quality-first interpretation model (v10) BCODe窶冱 interpretation document (draft v10) defines a parser output record with: qualifier mask (from - < ?) stale flag (!) numeric shape (empty / single / pair) mantissas and exponent metadata And it defines a truth table where qualifier combinations map to value/quality classes (hard finite, bounds, unknown, noise, epsilon, infinity, null, NaN, signaling-NaN payload codes, etc.), with ! as an orthogonal 窶徭tale窶・modifier. This is explicitly 窶徠uality-first telemetry窶・ an API must be able to refuse to produce a hard numeric when the field indicates unknown/null/NaN/inf/bounds/etc. (Reference: 窶廝CODe Value Interpretation (Draft v10)窶・窶・provided in-chat as an uploaded file.) 5.2 CBOR: rich typed values + semantic tags CBOR defines a richer core type system via 窶徇ajor types窶・(ints, byte/text strings, arrays, maps, tags, and simple/float values). Source: RFC 8949 窶・https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc8949.html Interpretation-relevant highlights: CBOR supports IEEE-754 floats (so NaN/Infinity are representable in float encodings). CBOR has simple values including null and undefined. CBOR has tags (major type 6) to add standardized semantic overlays (date/time, bignums, decimals, etc.). 5.3 MessagePack: compact typed values + 窶彳xt窶・semantic escape hatch MessagePack defines a smaller type system (int, float, nil, bool, str/bin, array/map, ext). The spec explicitly says Float represents IEEE-754 double precision, including NaN and Infinity. Source: MessagePack spec 窶・https://github.com/msgpack/msgpack/blob/master/spec.md MessagePack窶冱 semantic extensibility relies on 窶彳xt types窶・(type code + bytes), which are application-defined (except a few conventions like timestamp). 5.4 Key contrast that emerged CBOR / MessagePack: decode bytes into typed values; any 窶徠uality窶・concept (bounds, stale, unknown, noise) is usually schema-level or application convention. BCODe: standardizes a quality algebra at the field level (qualifiers + stale), so consumers can gate numeric accessors consistently. --- 6) Real systems using MessagePack or CBOR (and how they approximate BCODe concepts) This section captures the concrete examples we enumerated. 6.1 Fluentd forward input (MessagePack/JSON) Fluentd窶冱 forward input accepts JSON or MessagePack and internally uses MessagePack. Source: https://docs.fluentd.org/input/forward Equivalent-to-BCODe behaviors: Stale/fresh: inferred from timestamps (EventTime), not a stale qualifier. Quality/bounds/unknown: represented only via application fields or omitted keys. 6.2 Fluent Bit (MessagePack internally; JSON outputs) Fluent Bit documents json.convert nan to null, converting NaN 竊・null during msgpack竊男son conversion. Source: https://docs.fluentbit.io/manual/administration/configuring-fluent-bit/classic-mode/configuration-file The motivating bug report shows NaN leading to invalid JSON output ({\"foo\":nan}) before such handling. Source: https://github.com/fluent/fluent-bit/issues/1588 Equivalent-to-BCODe behaviors: Non-finite values survive inside MessagePack, but are often collapsed or mapped away when bridging to JSON. 6.3 Telegraf MessagePack serializer (InfluxData) Telegraf documents a MessagePack output data format. Source: https://docs.influxdata.com/telegraf/v1/data formats/output/msgpack/ A concrete issue shows that Telegraf drops NaN/Inf in at least one pipeline (Graphite 竊・InfluxDB) because the backend doesn窶冲 support them. Source: https://github.com/influxdata/telegraf/issues/6415 Equivalent-to-BCODe behaviors: NaN/Inf: treated as invalid/unacceptable for downstream rather than represented as a first-class 窶彭iagnostic窶・value class. Stale: inferred from timestamps. 6.4 Neovim API (MessagePack-RPC) Neovim窶冱 API documentation notes msgpack-rpc client libraries for connecting. Source: https://neovim.io/doc/user/api.html Equivalent-to-BCODe behaviors: Error/invalid cases are typically expressed as RPC errors or omitted fields, not a standardized 窶徠uality class窶・ Float semantics depend on client libraries; MessagePack supports NaN/Inf, but application-level meaning is not standardized. 6.5 SenML over CBOR (IoT telemetry) and LwM2M 1.1 SenML defines 窶弑pdate Time窶・(ut) as the maximum time before a sensor will provide an updated reading, usable to detect sensor/comms failures. Source: RFC 8428 窶・https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc8428.html IANA窶冱 SenML registry maps labels and includes the CBOR label for ut. Source: https://www.iana.org/assignments/senml/senml.xhtml Zephyr窶冱 LwM2M docs note that LwM2M 1.1 adds support for SenML CBOR/JSON and time series data. Source: https://docs.zephyrproject.org/latest/connectivity/networking/api/lwm2m.html Equivalent-to-BCODe behaviors: 窶彜tale窶・is modeled via timestamps + update-time semantics, not a stale bit. 窶弉uality窶・is typically schema/application-specific. 6.6 DAG-CBOR (IPLD): a CBOR profile that forbids NaN/Inf DAG-CBOR explicitly states that IEEE 754 special values NaN/Infinity/-Infinity must not be accepted. Source: https://ipld.io/specs/codecs/dag-cbor/spec/ Equivalent-to-BCODe behaviors: Exceptional numeric states must be represented by other schema conventions (e.g., tagged union objects), because the codec/profile forbids encoding them at all. 6.7 fxamacker/cbor (Go) policy example fxamacker/cbor documents: 窶廝y default, decoder treats time values of floating-point NaN and Infinity as if they are CBOR Null or CBOR Undefined.窶・Source: https://github.com/fxamacker/cbor Equivalent-to-BCODe behaviors: This is a library policy (domain-specific: time decoding), not a universally standardized CBOR semantic rule. 6.8 MessagePack library divergence on special floats (NaN/Inf/sNaN) msgpack-erlang historically failed to unpack NaN/Inf (returning {error, incomplete}), showing real-world implementation divergence. Source: https://github.com/msgpack/msgpack-erlang/issues/72 msgpack-c reports inconsistent preservation of signaling-NaN between float32 and float64 on unpack (sNaN may become qNaN). Source: https://github.com/msgpack/msgpack-c/issues/1087 These examples matter for BCODe because BCODe窶冱 sNaN class is semantic by design (with explicit payload codes), whereas 窶忖se raw IEEE NaN payloads on the wire窶・can be undermined by decoder normalization. --- 7) Practical takeaways that emerged JSON窶冱 minimal grammar makes it ubiquitous , but it pushes semantics (quality, NaN/Inf handling, versioning, schema, canonicalization) into higher layers. CBOR and MessagePack both can carry NaN/Inf , but real systems often: convert them to null when bridging to JSON, reject or drop them due to downstream constraints, or apply domain-specific rules (time decoding, canonical forms, etc.). BCODe窶冱 differentiator is interpretation standardization : every field can carry an explicit quality class, 窶徭tale窶・is orthogonal, accessors can be specified to refuse hard-numeric conversion unless the value is truly 窶徂ard/finite窶・ --- 8) Appendix: a schema-level 窶廝CODe-like窶・pattern for CBOR/MessagePack (if needed) If you want BCODe-style semantics but must use CBOR/MessagePack, the stable pattern is a tagged union / wrapper: BCODe窶冱 approach is essentially to make a compact, standardized equivalent of this wrapper implicit in the field syntax/qualifiers, instead of requiring a wrapper object for every scalar value. --- 9) Source index (URLs) RFC 8259 窶・JSON grammar and value set: https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc8259 ECMA-404 窶・JSON syntax-only scope: https://ecma-international.org/publications-and-standards/standards/ecma-404/ Crockford 窶彷at-free窶・rationale (NaN/Inf): https://www.json.org/fatfree.html ECMA-262 5.1 JSON.stringify behavior (NaN/Inf 竊・null): https://262.ecma-international.org/5.1/ MDN JSON.stringify notes: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global Objects/JSON/stringify RFC 7493 窶・I-JSON profile: https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc7493 RFC 8949 窶・CBOR: https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc8949.html MessagePack spec: https://github.com/msgpack/msgpack/blob/master/spec.md Fluentd forward input: https://docs.fluentd.org/input/forward Fluent Bit config option: https://docs.fluentbit.io/manual/administration/configuring-fluent-bit/classic-mode/configuration-file Fluent Bit issue #1588: https://github.com/fluent/fluent-bit/issues/1588 Telegraf MessagePack output: https://docs.influxdata.com/telegraf/v1/data formats/output/msgpack/ Telegraf issue #6415: https://github.com/influxdata/telegraf/issues/6415 Neovim API docs: https://neovim.io/doc/user/api.html RFC 8428 窶・SenML: https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc8428.html IANA SenML registry: https://www.iana.org/assignments/senml/senml.xhtml Zephyr LwM2M SenML CBOR note: https://docs.zephyrproject.org/latest/connectivity/networking/api/lwm2m.html DAG-CBOR forbids NaN/Inf: https://ipld.io/specs/codecs/dag-cbor/spec/ fxamacker/cbor NaN/Inf time decode policy: https://github.com/fxamacker/cbor msgpack-erlang NaN/Inf issue: https://github.com/msgpack/msgpack-erlang/issues/72 msgpack-c signaling NaN issue: https://github.com/msgpack/msgpack-c/issues/1087"}, {"slug": "syntax-v12", "display_title": "Syntax (v12)", "preview_title": "bcode-syntax-with-tests-v13 窶・Preview", "description": "BCODe Syntax Specification (Draft v13) BCODe (lowercase e ) is a streaming ASCII protocol for numeric data with payloads and comments. This document defines syntax and streaming parsing rules only . Companion ?", "corpus_text": "BCODe Syntax Specification (Draft v13) BCODe (lowercase e ) is a streaming ASCII protocol for numeric data with payloads and comments. This document defines syntax and streaming parsing rules only . Companion document: BCODe Value Interpretation (Draft) Status: Draft Document date: 2026-02-22 Syntax version: v13 Audience: implementers Companion document: bcode-interpretation-v13.html defines standard interpretations, transforms, reducers, and reference accessors. This document (syntax) does not assign meaning to commands or parameters. Normative keywords 窶廴UST窶・ 窶廴UST NOT窶・ 窶彜HOULD窶・ 窶彜HOULD NOT窶・ and 窶廴AY窶・are to be interpreted as in RFC 2119. Contents Scope Metanotation and Abstract Symbols Streaming model ASCII column grammar Line structure & latching Whitespace Comments Payloads Fields Numbers & fractional width Scientific exponent suffix Implementation limits Interleaving Opaque regions & precedence Conformance Error handling & resynchronization Appendix A 窶・ABNF Appendix B 窶・Streaming state machine Appendix C 窶・State machine diagram Appendix D 窶・Canonical C parser Appendix E 窶・Design notes Appendix F 窶・Conformance tests Appendix G 窶・Streaming conformance Appendix H 窶・Code generation reference Scope This document defines the core syntax and streaming parsing model of BCODe: ASCII-column token classes, lines and latching, fields (qualifiers + numbers), payloads, comments, whitespace, interleaving rules, deterministic recognition precedence, and a canonical streaming parser reference. This document does not assign semantic meaning to any particular parameter character or command character, except where a character is reserved for parser-level resynchronization. The command byte DEL (0x7F) is reserved for parser reset/resynchronization and MUST NOT be assigned higher-layer meaning (see Section 16.1). Interpretation of qualifier combinations and numeric types is defined separately. Metanotation and Abstract Symbols (Informative) This section defines the metanotation used in this document when describing BCODe syntax abstractly. These symbols are used only in specification prose and formal derivations. They do not appear on the wire and do not alter the grammar defined elsewhere in this document. Greek letters represent abstract roles within a BCODe line. Literal ASCII punctuation (such as ., ,, , /) is shown explicitly and always represents actual on-wire characters. 2.1 Terminators Command Terminator ﾎｺ竄・Represents a command terminator character (ASCII 0x60窶・x7F). The subscript n provides local numbering within a given derivation or example. It has no semantic meaning beyond distinguishing occurrences in the text. If identity is relevant, the actual ASCII character is stated explicitly, for example: ﾎｺ竄・= 'b' --- Parameter Terminator ﾎ竄・Represents a parameter terminator character (ASCII 0x40窶・x5F). The subscript n provides local numbering within a given derivation or example. It does not imply any absolute indexing or bit position. If identity matters, the specific ASCII character is given explicitly, for example: ﾎ竄・= 'A' --- 2.2 Field Values Abstract Field Value ﾎｦ Represents a complete numeric field value, independent of its internal structure. This abstraction is used when the internal decomposition of the field value is not relevant to the discussion. --- Numeric Decomposition When the internal structure of a field value matters, it is decomposed as: ﾎｦ ::= ﾎ・[ . , ﾎ・] [ ( /) ﾎ・] Where: ﾎ・represents the first numeric value (value1). ﾎ・represents the second numeric value (value2), if present. ﾎ・represents the exponent magnitude, if present. . or , are literal on-wire pair separators. or / are literal on-wire exponent operators. The comma separator indicates a negative ﾎ・ as defined in the syntax rules. The exponent magnitude ﾎ・corresponds to the integer value following or /. Subscripts MAY be used when multiple values appear in the same derivation: ﾎ凪ａ, ﾎ披ａ, ﾎ樞ａ --- 2.3 Payload Structure Abstract Payload ﾎｩ Represents an abstract payload body (string, hex-byte, or raw binary payload). When a payload is preceded by a numeric length hint, the abstract form is written: ﾎ・ﾎｩ where ﾎ・represents the length hint value and ﾎｩ represents the payload body. --- 2.4 Abstract Line Structure A BCODe line is abstractly represented as: ( ﾎｦ ﾎ竄・) ﾎｦ ﾎｺ竄・Meaning: Zero or more parameter-terminated fields Followed by one command-terminated field The line is latched upon reading ﾎｺ竄・ as defined by the command termination rules elsewhere in this document. --- 2.5 Notes Greek symbols are used only for specification clarity and never appear in the transmitted byte stream. ASCII punctuation shown in this section (., ,, , /) always represents literal on-wire characters. Subscripts provide local disambiguation within a derivation and have no independent protocol meaning. This metanotation is layered: discussions may operate at the ﾎｦ level (entire field value) or at the ﾎ・ﾎ・ﾎ・level (numeric decomposition) as appropriate. Streaming model BCODe is parsed from a potentially unbounded byte stream. There is no concept of end-of-file . The consumer decides where the stream starts and ends. A BCODe 窶徑ine窶・is a logical unit that ends when a command character is read in normal mode. All parsed state (fields, payloads) is latched atomically at that moment. 3.1 Stream start, session boundaries, and transport open events (Normative) Because BCODe has no end-of-file and command bytes are only recognized in normal mode (see Section 14 and Appendix B), a receiver cannot assume it is synchronized unless the transport or a higher-layer convention provides an explicit stream start. An implementation MUST reset its parser to the baseline state ( S\\ NORMAL with an empty pending line) whenever it begins consuming a new logical stream. Transports with a distinct open event. On session-oriented transports with a reliable 窶徙pen窶・event (for example: TCP connection establishment and WebSocket open), a receiver MUST reset its parser at the open event, and MUST NOT carry parser state across sessions. Transports without a distinct open event. On channels where a receiver may begin observing bytes at an arbitrary time, or where peers may reset independently while the channel remains 窶忖p窶・(for example: UART links, named FIFOs, and UDP), higher layers MUST provide an explicit resynchronization mechanism. This specification reserves the command byte DEL (0x7F) as an in-band parser reset/resynchronization command (Section 16.1). ASCII column grammar (Normative) Metanotation reference. In abstract descriptions, a parameter terminator is denoted ﾎ竄・and a command terminator is denoted ﾎｺ竄・ Thus a field is terminated by either ﾎ竄・(PARAM) or ﾎｺ竄・(CMD). These symbols are descriptive only; on-wire classification remains defined by ASCII range (Section 4). BCODe assigns grammatical meaning by ASCII 窶彡olumn窶・ i.e., by the upper three bits of the byte (c & 0xE0). Token identity within a class can be derived from the lower five bits (c & 0x1F). 4.1 ASCII columns used ASCII range Column Typical chars BCODe role --- --- --- --- 0x20窶・x3F 2 <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" SP ! \" ## %% && ' (;) + / 0窶・ : < = ? , - . $$</code </pre Field content, qualifiers, numeric punctuation, payload/comment markers, exponent markers 0x40窶・x5F 3 <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" @ A窶纏 [ \\ ] ^ </code </pre Parameter characters (terminate intermediate fields) 0x60窶・x7F 4 <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" a窶奴 DEL {} </code </pre Command characters (terminate line and latch). The byte DEL (0x7F) is reserved for parser reset/resynchronization (Section 15.1). Line structure & latching (Normative) Abstract line form. Using the metanotation defined in Section 2, a BCODe line has the abstract structure: ( ﾎｦ ﾎ竄・) ﾎｦ ﾎｺ竄・This expression captures the structural rule that zero or more parameter-terminated fields precede exactly one command-terminated field, and that latching occurs upon reading ﾎｺ竄・ A BCODe line is any sequence of fields, payloads, and whitespace/comments that ends with a command character. Newlines are not line terminators in BCODe. All fields and payloads parsed since the previous command character are latched when the next command character is read. No semantic action is taken prior to latching. Payloads SHOULD precede fields for readability, but this is not required. Whitespace (Normative) Outside opaque regions, the following are treated identically as ignorable whitespace: SP (0x20), HTAB (0x09), CR (0x0D), LF (0x0A) Outside opaque regions and comments, whitespace MAY appear anywhere (including inside numbers, exponents, and between qualifiers) and MUST NOT affect syntax-level values. Comments (Normative) Comments are treated as ignorable whitespace with opaque content: the parser MUST NOT interpret comment contents as syntax, and comment contents are not part of the latched semantic record. 7.1 Semicolon comment A semicolon comment begins with ; and ends at the next LF (0x0A). 7.2 Parenthesized comment A parenthesized comment begins with ( and ends at the next ). Comments are not nestable. 7.3 Where comments are recognized Comments are recognized in normal mode. Comments are not recognized inside opaque regions (string payload bodies and raw binary bodies). Comments are recognized inside %...% hex payload bodies and removed before decoding. Payloads (Normative) A line may include zero or more payloads, appearing anywhere before the command character. Payloads are latched along with fields when the command character is read. 8.1 String payload (opaque) A string payload begins with $ and ends at LF (0x0A) or NUL (0x00). The body is opaque: no comments or other syntax are recognized inside. Optional length hint An optional unsigned integer length hint MAY precede the $. It provides a receiver a head窶爽p for buffer sizing and an extra end窶奏o窶粗nd verification signal. The hint indicates the number of payload bytes excluding the terminating LF/NUL. The length hint uses the normal integer literal syntax: decimal digits or uppercase hex #...#. Whitespace (SP/HTAB/CR/LF) is ignored, and comments MAY appear between digits and before $. Qualifiers have no meaning for payload length and SHOULD NOT be used on a length hint. If a length hint is present, the string payload length (bytes before LF/NUL) MUST match it exactly. If the terminator occurs early, or if more bytes arrive than hinted, this is a parse error. 8.2 Hex-byte binary payload (comment-friendly) A hex-byte payload is bounded by % characters and encodes bytes as pairs of uppercase hex digits. Whitespace is allowed and ignored. Comments are allowed inside and removed prior to decoding. Optional decoded-length hint An optional unsigned integer length hint MAY precede the opening %. The hint indicates the number of decoded bytes carried inside %...% (i.e., after removing whitespace/comments and converting hex digit pairs to bytes). After removing whitespace and comments from %...%, the remaining hex digit count MUST be even (two digits per byte), and digits MUST be uppercase 0窶・ or A窶擢. If a decoded-length hint is present, the decoded byte count MUST match it exactly; otherwise this is a parse error. 8.3 Length-prefixed raw binary payload (opaque body) A length-prefixed raw binary payload begins with an & delimiter and consumes exactly payload\\ length raw bytes. A numeric length MAY appear immediately before & (allowing intervening whitespace), otherwise length defaults to 0. Raw payload length derivation (updated) The payload length MUST be derived from the field窶冱 first numeric value (value1) only. If value1 has already been committed, payload length = value1. Otherwise, if a first-number accumulator exists, payload length is the current accumulator value. Otherwise, payload length = 0. Decimal fractions and exponent suffixes MUST NOT affect payload length. Including them is safe but discouraged. After determining payload length, the parser MUST consume/reset the numeric accumulator and then consume exactly payload length raw bytes. If & appears while a hex number is open (i.e., between the opening and closing #), parsing resumes in that same 窶徂ex-open窶・mode after the raw payload is consumed. This is permitted but strongly discouraged. 8.4 Qualifiers do not apply to payloads Qualifier characters (-, <, , ?, !) apply only to fields. If qualifiers appear adjacent to payloads, they MUST NOT be interpreted as modifying that payload. Fields (Normative) Fields carry numeric data and are terminated by either a parameter character (intermediate fields) or a command character (final field). 9.1 Field termination A parameter character (ASCII 0x40窶・x5F) terminates a field and identifies a parameter. A command character (ASCII 0x60窶・x7F) terminates the final field and latches the entire line. Terminators are not part of the field value. 9.2 Qualifiers (syntax only) Each field may contain any combination of the following qualifier characters: This document defines only the syntax of qualifier presence. The standard interpretation of qualifier combinations and the meaning of ! (freshness modifier) are defined separately. 9.3 Empty fields (Normative) Empty fields are permitted. An empty field is a field terminator (parameter or command character) that occurs when no numeric value has been provided for the current field. A parser MUST treat an empty field as having: value1 = 0, value2 = 0, frac width = 0, and qualifier flags as accumulated (if any qualifiers appeared). 9.4 Enumeration of field forms (Normative) Decimal vs hex encoding, pair separator choice (. for positive value2, , for negative value2), and optional exponent suffix do not create distinct field forms. The terminator class (PARAM vs CMD) does create distinct field forms. 8.4.1 Content shapes Shape ID Canonical spelling Description --- --- --- C0 <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" Q T</code </pre Empty field (no numeric content) C1 <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" Q N [EXP] T</code </pre Single-number field with optional exponent suffix C2 <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" Q N S M [EXP] T</code </pre Two-number field (fixed-point pair) with optional exponent suffix 8.4.2 Distinct field forms by terminator class Each content shape has two terminator-class variants: 窶ｦP for parameter terminators (0x40窶・x5F) and 窶ｦC for command terminators (0x60窶・x7F). Form ID Shape Terminator Canonical spelling --- --- --- --- F0P C0 PARAM <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" Q PARAM</code </pre F1P C1 PARAM <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" Q N [EXP] PARAM</code </pre F2P C2 PARAM <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" Q N S M [EXP] PARAM</code </pre F0C C0 CMD <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" Q CMD</code </pre F1C C1 CMD <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" Q N [EXP] CMD</code </pre F2C C2 CMD <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" Q N S M [EXP] CMD</code </pre Whitespace/comments and interleaved payloads (outside opaque regions) do not change the field form classification (C0/C1/C2, PARAM/CMD). Numbers & fractional width (Normative) 10.1 One or two numeric values A field contains one or two numeric values. If two values are present, they are separated by either . or ,. The separator indicates the sign of the second value: . indicates a non-negative value2, and , indicates a negative value2. The digits of value2 encode the magnitude; the sign MUST be derived solely from the separator and MUST be recorded by the parser. Note: In BCODe syntax, . and , are pair separators, not locale-dependent decimal separators. This specification records the sign and digits; numeric interpretation is defined separately. 10.2 Decimal vs hex Each numeric value is either decimal digits (0窶・) or hex digits bounded by #: 10.3 Uppercase-only hex digits (safety constraint) Hex digits MUST be uppercase only: 0窶・ and A窶擢. Lowercase a窶吐 are forbidden. A hex value MUST be terminated by a closing #, and MUST contain at least one hex digit. Hex literals are opaque to field terminators: while inside an open #...# sequence, PARAM and CMD characters MUST NOT terminate the field. Only the closing # ends the hex literal. If a terminator is encountered before the closing #, the construct is malformed and a parser SHOULD resynchronize. 10.4 Leading zeros Leading zeros in value1 are permitted and MUST NOT affect syntax-level numeric parsing. Leading zeros in value2 are permitted; the digit count in value2 is recorded as frac width. 10.5 Fractional width recording For every field, the parser MUST record frac width as follows: if a second numeric value is absent, frac width = 0; otherwise, frac width is the number of digits in value2 as encoded (whitespace/comments ignored; # delimiters excluded). Scientific exponent suffix (Normative) BCODe supports a compact scientific notation suffix on the mantissa. The exponent is an integer and is encoded using a column-2 marker character to avoid reusing the - qualifier. 11.1 Syntax Marker Meaning Exponent value if digits omitted --- --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" </code </pre Positive exponent +1 (discouraged) <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" /</code </pre Negative exponent -1 (discouraged) The exponent marker MUST occur after the mantissa (value1 or value1.value2) and before the field terminator. The pair separator (. or ,) MUST NOT occur after an exponent marker. The exponent digits (if present) MUST be decimal digits 0窶・ (whitespace/comments may appear between digits). If an exponent marker is present with no digits, the exponent magnitude defaults to 1 (safe but discouraged). Only one exponent marker is allowed per field. 11.2 Parser output A conforming parser MUST record the exponent suffix as: exp present (boolean) and exp10 (signed integer base-10 exponent; 0 if absent). This document defines how the exponent is parsed and recorded. How typed accessors apply the exponent is defined in the interpretation document. 11.3 Examples Implementation limits (Normative) The BCODe language does not impose fixed numeric size limits. Implementations MAY impose bounds on numeric magnitude, digit count, fractional width, exponent magnitude, and payload lengths for practical reasons. If an implementation cannot represent a value (overflow, excessive length, etc.), it MUST treat the construct as malformed and apply its resynchronization strategy. Interleaving (Normative) BCODe permits comments and payloads to appear between tokens, including within fields and within numeric spellings, subject to opaque-region rules. Interleaving of payloads and comments is permitted in normal mode, including between digits of a numeric spelling or exponent. Comments and payload markers are not recognized inside opaque regions (string payload bodies and raw-binary bodies). Comments are recognized inside %...% and removed prior to hex decoding. Opaque regions & recognition precedence (Normative) 14.1 Opaque regions String payload body: after $ until LF or NUL terminator (terminator consumed) Raw binary payload body: after & until exactly payload\\ length bytes are consumed 14.2 Recognition precedence outside opaque regions ; begins a semicolon comment (ends at LF) ( begins a parenthesized comment (ends at )) $ begins a string payload (opaque) % begins a hex-byte payload (comments allowed inside) & begins a raw binary payload (length derived from value1 as in Section 8.3) Parameter character (0x40窶・x5F) terminates a field Command character (0x60窶・x7F) terminates the final field and latches the line Otherwise, bytes contribute to the current field (qualifiers/numbers/exponent), ignoring whitespace This precedence yields a single deterministic parse of the stream. Conformance (Normative) MUST classify PARAM as 0x40窶・x5F and CMD as 0x60窶・x7F. MUST latch line state only on CMD encountered outside opaque regions and comments. MUST treat the command byte DEL (0x7F) as a reserved parser reset/resynchronization token in normal mode (Section 16.1), and MUST NOT deliver it as an application-visible command. MUST treat SP/HTAB/CR/LF as ignorable whitespace outside opaque regions/comments. MUST accept both pair separators . and ,; . indicates a non-negative value2, and , indicates a negative value2 (digits encode magnitude). MUST enforce uppercase-only hex digits (0窶・A窶擢) in #...# and in %...%. MUST require at least one hex digit inside #...# (no empty hex values). MUST record frac width per Section 10.5. MUST record exponent suffix as exp present and exp10 per Section 11. MUST treat string payload body and raw binary body as opaque; no comments/syntax recognized inside. MUST allow comments inside %...% and remove them before hex decoding. MUST start a raw binary payload on & with length defaulting to 0 when absent. MUST derive raw payload length from value1 only; fraction/exponent MUST NOT affect length. MUST permit empty fields and treat them as zeros per Section 9.3. MUST accept the qualifier character set - < ? ! syntactically. Error handling & resynchronization Recommended strategy: on detecting a malformed construct in normal mode (invalid hex digit, malformed #...#, odd digit count in %...%, malformed exponent, etc.), an implementation SHOULD discard the pending line state and resynchronize by scanning until the next command character encountered in normal mode. 16.1 Reserved parser reset / resynchronization command (DEL) The command byte DEL (ASCII 0x7F) is reserved for parser reset / resynchronization and MUST NOT be assigned meaning by higher-layer schemas, conventions, or applications. The reset byte is recognized only when encountered as a command terminator in S\\ NORMAL (see Appendix B.2). It is not recognized inside comment bodies, or inside opaque regions such as $...LF/NUL string bodies or &...raw bytes... bodies. When DEL is read in S\\ NORMAL , a conforming parser MUST discard any pending (not-yet-latched) line state and MUST report a parser reset event to the host (implementation-defined API; see Appendix D for one reference). The parser MUST NOT report any normal 窶徑ine latched窶・event for DEL, and MUST NOT deliver the reset byte upward as an application-visible command. 15.1.1 Reset acknowledgement token A reset acknowledgement is encoded as the two-byte sequence 0x3E 0x7F (ASCII followed by DEL). In this document we write this token as <DEL , where <DEL denotes the single byte 0x7F. It consists of a line containing only the qualifier (no numeric content) terminated by the reserved reset command byte. Parsers MAY classify reset events as either 窶徨eset request窶・or 窶徨eset acknowledgement窶・based on whether the pending line state matches this acknowledgement shape. A receiver that implements the reset mechanism MUST transmit the reset acknowledgement token (0x3E 0x7F) after receiving a reset request. A receiver MUST NOT transmit a reset acknowledgement in response to a reset acknowledgement. Diagnostics: Implementations MAY render the 0x7F byte as 窶廛EL窶・ 窶弯?窶・ or 窶・DEL 窶・in logs and UIs. The on-wire acknowledgement is always exactly two bytes. 16.2 Recommended serial resynchronization procedure (Informative) Because command bytes are not recognized inside opaque regions and comments, a peer may be 窶徭tuck窶・consuming an unknown number of bytes in a parenthesized comment body (until )), a semicolon comment (until LF), a $ string payload body (until LF/NUL), or a raw & payload body (until N bytes are consumed). The following byte sequence is commonly used on serial/terminal links to regain synchronization. After each step, the sender MUST check RX for the reset acknowledgement token (0x3E 0x7F, written <DEL ; Section 16.1.1). If the acknowledgement is observed, the sender MUST stop transmitting further resynchronization bytes. Send a single ) byte (0x29) to terminate any parenthesized comment. Send a single DEL byte (0x7F) as a reset request. Send a single LF byte (0x0A, \\n) to terminate any semicolon comment and to terminate any $...LF string payload body. Send DEL (0x7F) repeatedly (checking RX for <DEL after each transmitted byte) until the peer responds with the reset acknowledgement token <DEL . If a bare DEL (0x7F) is observed on RX before any byte is observed, abort and fail (probable serial loopback/echo). Because DEL (0x7F) is non-printing and may be intercepted by TTY line editing, 窶徇anual reset窶・typically requires a tool, macro, or device-specific UI that can emit the byte explicitly on the wire (raw/binary mode). When raw binary payloads are used, such tooling may also need to transmit enough bytes to exhaust a known maximum raw payload length before a reset can be recognized. Appendix A 窶・ABNF (RFC 5234 style) ABNF cannot fully express streaming state (opaque regions and byte-counted raw binary). The ABNF below describes token shapes; normative state behavior is defined in Appendix B. Appendix B 窶・Streaming parser state machine (Normative) B.1 States S\\ NORMAL : normal recognition mode S\\ SEMI\\ COMMENT : inside ;...LF S\\ PAREN\\ COMMENT : inside (...) S\\ STRING\\ PAYLOAD : inside $...LF/NUL (opaque) S\\ HEX\\ PAYLOAD : inside %...% (comments allowed) S\\ RAWBIN\\ PAYLOAD : consuming payload\\ length raw bytes after & (opaque) B.2 Latching rule A command character (ASCII 0x60窶・x7F) latches the pending line state only when encountered in S\\ NORMAL . Command characters in any other state are treated as literal data and MUST NOT latch. The reserved command byte DEL (0x7F) is handled specially in S\\ NORMAL : it triggers a parser reset/resynchronization event and discards pending line state rather than producing a normal line latch (Section 16.1). B.3 Key transitions Length hint recognition: For $ and opening %, a length hint is recognized only when the parser has accumulated a standalone, unqualified integer immediately before the payload start. If recognized, that integer is consumed as the payload窶冱 length hint and is not part of any field. Appendix C 窶・State machine diagram (Informative) Copy into any Mermaid renderer (this HTML does not load external scripts). Appendix D 窶・Canonical C parser (Reference) This is a canonical streaming parser for the syntax rules in this document. It reports fields/payloads as they are parsed; an application that wants a 窶忤hole latched line窶・can buffer events until on line latched. Show canonical C parser (single-file reference) Appendix E 窶・Design notes (Informative) E.1 ASCII-column partitioning Using ASCII range classes (column 3 for parameters and column 4 for commands) creates a hard boundary between 窶彭ata characters窶・and 窶徭tructural terminators窶・ Parsers can classify bytes via range checks or bit masks. E.2 Latching on command The 窶彡ommit on command character窶・model provides atomic updates and avoids partial application of streamed data. It also provides a natural resynchronization boundary in noisy links. E.3 Uppercase-only hex is a safety feature Lowercase a窶吐 live in the command-column ASCII range. Forbidding them reduces the chance that malformed or truncated hex sequences could accidentally resemble command characters or otherwise destabilize parsing. E.4 Scientific exponent suffix The exponent suffix ( and /) adds scale expressiveness while keeping the base qualifier set unchanged. The suffix is intentionally constrained (integer decimal exponent, default magnitude 1 if digits omitted) to preserve streaming determinism. E.5 Reserved reset byte choice (DEL) BCODe reserves exactly one command byte for parser-level resynchronization. Earlier drafts reserved the printable backtick character ( , 0x60); this draft instead reserves DEL (0x7F). Opportunity cost. Many applications want to use human-readable command characters in the CMD range. Reserving a commonly typed printable character has a higher long-term cost than reserving a non-printing control code. Reserving DEL preserves the rest of the command set (including backtick) for higher-layer meaning. Reset is a special case. Parser reset is primarily required to establish synchronization on communication channels without a distinct 窶徙pen窶・event (see Section 3.1) and as a programmatic recovery mechanism after corruption. It is not a common 窶彙usiness-level窶・command. Human/manual operation is environment-specific. Some terminal and TTY stacks treat 0x7F as an erase/backspace key and may intercept it unless the link is in raw/binary mode. Implementations that expose a 窶徇anual reset窶・workflow should provide a tool, macro, or UI affordance to emit 0x7F explicitly. E.6 Reset cannot preempt opaque payloads The reset command is recognized only in S\\ NORMAL . Inside opaque payload bodies ($...LF/NUL and raw &...bytes...), all bytes窶琶ncluding CMD bytes窶蚤re treated as literal payload data. As a result, resynchronization may require draining or terminating the current opaque region (for example by sending LF to end a string payload), or by sending enough bytes to exhaust a known maximum raw payload length before the reset byte can be recognized. Appendix F 窶・Conformance tests (Recommended) This appendix provides reference test vectors for BCODe syntax parsers. A conforming implementation SHOULD parse these inputs into the same sequence of events (fields, payload bytes, and line latches). The event log format used below matches the reference implementation in bcode parser with lenprefix v7.c. Implementations may buffer differently internally, but the observable results at field termination and payload decoding SHOULD match. F.1 Canonical event log format Note: In this log format, v2 is rendered as a signed integer: it is negative iff the pair separator was , (see Section 10.1). F.2 Test vectors T01 窶・basic two fields Two numeric fields: one PARAM, one CMD. Input Expected events T02 窶・empty fields Empty fields allowed for both PARAM and CMD. Input Expected events T03 窶・pair frac\\ width Dot separator; leading zeros in fractional contribute to frac\\ width. Input Expected events T04 窶・pair comma (negative value2) Comma separator indicates negative value2; digit spelling encodes magnitude. Input Expected events T05 窶・hex single Uppercase hex literal in #...#. Input Expected events T06 窶・hex with whitespace Whitespace inside hex digits is ignored. Input Expected events T07 窶・comments inside numbers Paren comment inside number; semicolon comment ends at LF. Input Expected events T08 窶・string payload semicolon not comment Semicolon is literal inside $...LF string payload. Input Expected events T09 窶・string payload null $ followed immediately by NUL encodes a NULL string payload. Input Expected events T10 窶・hex payload basic %...% hex bytes decode (whitespace ignored). Input Expected events T11 窶・hex payload with comments Comments allowed inside %...% and removed prior to decoding. Input Expected events T12 窶・hex payload interleaved in number A payload may appear between digits; digits concatenate around it. Input Expected events T13 窶・raw payload length from accumulator Length-prefixed raw payload uses digits before & (when value1 not committed). Input Expected events T14 窶・raw payload default length 0 & with no preceding number has length 0 (NULL binary payload). Input Expected events T15 窶・raw length ignores fraction and exponent Length derives from value1 only; fraction/exponent do not affect length. Input Expected events T16 窶・exponent after value1 Scientific suffix on single-number field. Input Expected events T17 窶・exponent negative default '/' with no digits defaults magnitude to 1, i.e., exp10=-1. Input Expected events T18 窶・exponent after value2 Exponent may follow the second number in a pair. Input Expected events T19 窶・illegal separator after exponent triggers resync A separator after exponent is malformed; parser resyncs to next CMD. Input Expected events T20 窶・hex-open raw payload restore If & occurs in open hex (#... not closed), parser restores hex-open mode after payload. Input Expected events T21 窶・whitespace in exponent digits Whitespace between exponent marker and digits is ignored. Input Expected events T22 窶・default exponent magnitude +1 ' ' with no digits defaults to exp10=+1. Input Expected events T23 窶・negative pair frac\\ width Comma separator indicates negative value2; leading zeros contribute to frac width. Input Expected events T24 窶・negative pair hex value2 Hex spelling for value2 with a comma separator produces a negative second value; frac width is the hex digit count (excluding #). Input Expected events T25 窶・negative pair with exponent after value2 Exponent may follow the second number in a pair; comma separator still indicates negative value2. Input Expected events T26 窶・reserved reset command (request) The single byte 0x7F (DEL) is reserved as a parser reset/resynchronization token. It does not produce a normal latch. Input Expected events T27 窶・reset acknowledgement token The reset acknowledgement token is encoded as bytes 0x3E 0x7F (ASCII followed by DEL). Input Expected events Appendix H 窶・Code generation reference This appendix is informative . It is a compact, implementation-oriented summary intended to help generate correct parser and consumer code from the specification. H.1 Reference files produced alongside this spec bcode parser with lenprefix v7.c 窶・canonical streaming syntax parser (reference implementation). bcode streaming conformance tests v7.c 窶・chunking/stress tests for streaming invariance. bcode interp v3.h / bcode interp v3.c 窶・reference interpretation API (transforms, reducer, accessors). bcode-interpretation-v13.html 窶・companion specification for interpretations and API behavior. See also: Section 12.6 of bcode-interpretation-v13.html for canonical field normalization pseudocode (parser adapters). H.2 Token class quick table Token Meaning Parsed where? Notes --- --- --- --- <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" 0x20, TAB, CR, LF</code </pre Whitespace Everywhere except 窶徙paque regions窶・TAB/LF/CR are treated the same as spaces. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" ;</code </pre Line comment Normal mode Runs until LF. If LF never occurs, the comment continues indefinitely (streaming model). <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" (...)</code </pre Parentheses comment Normal mode Runs until the next ). Unterminated comment continues indefinitely. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" $</code </pre String payload Normal mode Ends only at LF or NUL. Within a string payload, comment and terminator tokens are not recognized. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" %</code </pre Hex-byte payload Normal mode Payload content is 2-digit hex bytes; whitespace is allowed; comments are allowed inside. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" &amp;</code </pre Raw-binary payload Normal mode Consumes an integer length (defaults to 0) then reads that many raw bytes (opaque region). <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" #...#</code </pre Hex number literal Inside number spelling Hex digits MUST be uppercase. While # is open, PARAM/CMD bytes are not terminators; only closing # ends the literal. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" . or ,</code </pre Pair separator Normal mode (number spelling) Separates value1 and value2. . indicates non-negative value2; , indicates negative value2 (digits encode magnitude). The width of value2 is preserved. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" / /</code </pre Exponent suffix marker Normal mode (after mantissa) is positive exponent, / is negative exponent. If no digits follow, exponent magnitude defaults to 1. <pre <code class=\"language-bcode\" - &lt; &gt; ? !</code </pre Qualifiers / modifiers Normal mode (field prefix) Any combination of - < ? may appear; ! is orthogonal staleness. H.3 Parameter & command terminators Terminators are organized by ASCII column (low 5 bits). Column 3 is the parameter terminator range and column 4 is the command terminator range: PARAM : 0x40..0x5F 窶・ends a field, continues the line. CMD : 0x60..0x7F 窶・ends the final field and latches the entire line. Parameter identity is defined by the low 5 bits : H.4 Opaque-region precedence rules (common pitfalls) Implementations MUST treat certain regions as opaque (tokens inside do not act as comments/terminators): String payload ($...LF/NUL): opaque; comments and terminators are literal bytes. Raw payload (&...raw bytes...): payload bytes are opaque; comments and terminators are literal bytes. Hex-byte payload (%...%) is not opaque to whitespace/comments (whitespace/comments may appear between hex digits). Hex number literal (#...#) is special: while open, PARAM/CMD bytes MUST NOT terminate the field; only closing # ends the literal. H.5 & length derivation (mandatory rule) Requirement (Normative): The raw payload length for & is derived only from the field窶冱 first numeric value (value1). Fractional (value2) and exponent metadata MUST NOT affect payload length. H.6 Implementation checklist for generated parsers Empty fields are allowed (a terminator may occur with no number content). Whitespace and comments behave like whitespace in normal mode (including inside number spelling), except inside opaque regions. Hex digits in #...# MUST be uppercase (A窶擢 only). Lowercase is invalid and should trigger resynchronization. Allow whitespace between qualifiers and numbers, and between numbers and terminators. Allow payloads to interleave with number spelling; payloads do not alter numeric accumulation (except & consumes the accumulator). Exponent marker // may appear with no digits; default magnitude is 1 (discouraged but allowed). No decimal separator may appear after an exponent marker. Streaming model: there is no EOF; unterminated comments/strings continue indefinitely. Reserved reset: the command byte 0x7F (DEL) discards pending line state and reports a parser reset event; it MUST NOT be delivered as an application-visible command (Section 16.1). H.7 Parse error reporting (optional) The syntax specification defines error behavior by requiring the parser to discard the current line and resynchronize on the next command terminator byte (0x60..0x7F). The canonical reference parser (bcode parser with lenprefix v7.c) exposes this via an optional callback. H.8 Parse error codes (bc\\ parse\\ error\\ t) The reference parser reports a stable, small set of error codes when it enters resynchronization. All parse errors are treated uniformly: the current line is dropped and input is discarded until the next CMD byte is seen in normal mode. The numeric values below are stable for this reference implementation. Code (name) Value Meaning Typical trigger --- --- --- --- BC PE SYNTAX 0 Generic syntax error Invalid character for the current parsing context; malformed field structure BC PE OVERFLOW 1 Numeric overflow Decimal/hex accumulator would exceed 64-bit range; exponent magnitude overflow BC PE HEX PAYLOAD ODD NIBBLE 2 Odd nibble in %...% payload Closing % encountered with exactly one hex digit buffered BC PE HEX PAYLOAD BAD HEX 3 Invalid hex digit in %...% payload Non-hex (or lowercase) where a hex digit is required BC PE PAYLOAD HINT MISMATCH 4 Length hint mismatch LEN$ string body length != LEN, or LEN% decoded bytes != LEN BC PE HEX LITERAL BAD HEX 5 Invalid hex digit inside #...# literal Lowercase a..f or other invalid character inside an open hex literal Tip for robust callback wiring in C: use a zero-initialized struct and assign the field explicitly to avoid any ordering issues: Recommended consumer behavior: Drop any partially buffered payload and parsed-but-not-latched fields for the current line. Do not attempt to interpret payload contents; payload bytes are opaque even when used for diagnostics. Wait for the next CMD byte to resume normal parsing. End of document. --- Appendix G 窶・Streaming Conformance Tests BCODe is defined as a streaming protocol; therefore, implementations MUST produce identical parse results regardless of how the incoming byte stream is chunked (e.g., packet boundaries, serial read sizes, etc.). G.1 Chunking invariance requirement Requirement (Normative): For any finite byte sequence B and any partition of B into contiguous chunks C0..Cn, feeding the parser with B in a single call MUST produce the same sequence of parser events as feeding the parser with C0..Cn across multiple calls, assuming identical initial state. G.2 Reference conformance harness The canonical test harness provided with this specification is: bcode streaming conformance tests v7.c 窶・executes each test vector under multiple chunking strategies. bcode parser with lenprefix v7.c 窶・canonical streaming syntax parser used by the harness. bcode-conformance-vectors-v7.md 窶・human-readable description of the streaming stress vectors. G.3 Included stress vectors The v3 suite includes additional 窶從asty窶・vectors beyond the deterministic v2 set, including: Commands occurring inside unterminated ; comments, (...) comments, and $ strings. Malformed %...% payloads (odd nibble / invalid digit) and the resynchronization behavior. Lowercase hex digits in #...# numbers (forbidden) and recovery. Exponent markers and digits split across chunk boundaries, and payloads interrupting exponent digits. Raw & payload bodies split across chunk boundaries; payload length derivation remains invariant. Note: These tests validate syntax-level behavior and parser state machine correctness; they do not assign semantic meaning to any specific CMD or PARAM values."}];</script><script src="../assets/site.js"></script><footer><div class="footer-content"><nav aria-label="Docs"><a href="../docs/intro-reader.html">Intro</a> <span class="footer-sep">|</span> <a href="../docs/syntax-reader.html">Syntax (v13)</a> <span class="footer-sep">|</span> <a href="../docs/interpretation-reader.html">Interpretation</a> <span class="footer-sep">|</span> <a href="../docs/meta-v9-reader.html">BCODe.meta (v9)</a> <span class="footer-sep">|</span> <a href="../docs/meta-v7-reader.html">BCODe.meta (v7)</a> <span class="footer-sep">|</span> <a href="../docs/meta-library-semantics-reader.html">Meta Library Semantics</a> <span class="footer-sep">|</span> <a href="../docs/rest-reader.html">BCODe.rest (v6.1.3)</a> <span class="footer-sep">|</span> <a href="../docs/best-practices-reader.html">Best Practices</a> <span class="footer-sep">|</span> <a href="../docs/telemetry-guide-reader.html">Telemetry Guide</a> <span class="footer-sep">|</span> <a href="../docs/chat-summary-reader.html">Chat Summary</a> </nav><p class="footer-right">BCODe</p></div></footer><script src="../assets/lavalamp.js"></script></body></html>

